{"title_page": "M3 Bradley", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2017}}\n<!-- Significant information on history is uncited. -->\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = M3 Bradley Cavalry Fighting Vehicle\n| image              = Two M-3 Bradleys.jpg\n| image_size         = 300\n| caption            = Two M3 Bradleys in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]\n| origin             = [[United States of America]]\n| type               = [[Reconnaissance vehicle]] [[Infantry fighting vehicle]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          =\n| is_bladed          =\n| is_explosive       =\n| is_artillery       =\n| is_vehicle         = yes\n| is_missile         =\n| is_UK              =\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            =\n| used_by            =\n| wars               = [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]<br />[[Iraq War]]\n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = [[FMC Corporation]] (M3(A0), M3A1), [[United Defense]] (M3A2, M3A3)\n| design_date        =\n| manufacturer       =\n| unit_cost          =\n| production_date    =\n| number             =\n| variants           =\n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         =\n| weight             = 25\u201330.5 short tons (23\u201328 tonnes)\n| length             = 21.2\u201321.5&nbsp;ft (6.45\u20136.55&nbsp;m)\n| part_length        =\n| width              = 126\u2013129&nbsp;in (320\u2013328&nbsp;cm)\n| height             = 117&nbsp;in (297&nbsp;cm)\n| diameter           =\n| crew               = 3 + 7 passengers\n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| armour             = Steel, [[5083 aluminium alloy|5083]] and [[7039 aluminium alloy|7039]] aluminum\n| primary_armament   = 25&nbsp;mm [[M242 Bushmaster|M242]] Chain Gun<br />1500 rounds (300 ready)<br />Dual [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW]] Anti-Tank Missile Launcher<br />12 rounds (2 in launcher)\n| secondary_armament = 7.62&nbsp;mm [[M240 machine gun|M240C]] machine gun\n| engine             = [[Cummins]] VTA-903\n| engine_power       =\n| pw_ratio           =\n| transmission       = [[General Electric]] HMPT-500\n| payload_capacity   =\n| suspension         =\n| clearance          = 18&nbsp;in (46&nbsp;cm)\n| fuel_capacity      = 175\u2013197&nbsp;gal (662\u2013746&nbsp;L)\n| vehicle_range      = '''Road:''' 250\u2013300&nbsp;mi (400\u2013480&nbsp;km)\n| speed              = '''Top road speed:''' 35\u201341&nbsp;mph (56\u201366&nbsp;km/h)<br /> '''Top water speed:''' 4\u20134.5&nbsp;mph (6.4\u20137.2&nbsp;km/h)\n| guidance           =\n| steering           =\n}}\n\nThe '''M3 Bradley Cavalry Fighting Vehicle''' ('''CFV''') is an American tracked armored [[reconnaissance]] vehicle manufactured by [[BAE Systems Land and Armaments]] (formerly [[United Defense]]). A member of the [[Bradley Fighting Vehicle]] family, the M3 CFV is used by heavy armored cavalry units in the [[United States Army]].\n\n==History==\nThe M3 Bradley CFV is very similar to the [[M2 Bradley]] IFV (Infantry Fighting Vehicle) and is fielded with the same two-man 25mm [[M242 Bushmaster|Bushmaster]] Cannon turret with a coaxial [[M240 machine gun|M240C]] 7.62mm machine gun. It only varies from the M2 in a few subtle ways and by role. The M3 is classified as an armored reconnaissance and scout vehicle and does away with the firing ports found in the M2 series. The M3 also carries more [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW]] missiles as well as more ammunition for its 25mm and 7.62mm guns.\n\nThe Bradley family as a whole was originally intended to support the [[M113 armored personnel carrier|M113]] Armored Personnel Carrier (APC), but ended up replacing it in U.S. Army service altogether. Today, the Bradley is fielded in conjunction with the [[M1 Abrams]] series of main battle tanks and often accompanies infantry squads into combat. In the 1991 Persian Gulf War, Bradleys destroyed more enemy tanks than the M1 Abrams.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} Only three Bradleys were lost to enemy fire, however, at least 17 were lost to friendly fire. Improvements to the Bradley family have included enhanced identification features, as well as anti-tank missile countermeasures (for first generation wire-guided missiles only) and improved armor protection in the form of [[explosive reactive armor|ERA]].\n\n===Replacement===\nThe United States and United Kingdom worked jointly on the Future Scout Cavalry System in the 1990s. The U.S. Army's intended replacement for the M3 Bradley and up-armored [[Humvee]] reached the engineering and manufacturing development phase. It reached the engineering and manufacturing development phase before both partners terminated involvement in October 2001 to pursue other more urgent programs: the U.S. [[Interim Armored Vehicle]] and UK [[Future Rapid Effect System]].<ref name=\"FSCS\">{{cite news|last1=Baumgardner|first1=Neil|title=United States, Britain Agree To Terminate Future Scout Cavalry System|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79237089.html|accessdate=12 May 2017|work=Defense Daily|date=18 October 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920152728/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79237089.html|archivedate=20 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 [[Future Combat Systems]] (FCS) planned a successor to the M3 Bradley in the [[Future Combat Systems Manned Ground Vehicles#Reconnaissance and surveillance vehicle|XM1201 Reconnaissance and Surveillance Vehicle]]. That too was canceled when FCS was terminated in 2009.\n\nThe U.S. Army intended the [[Ground Combat Vehicle]] replace the M2 Bradley and M113 by 2018, while the M3 Bradley could later be replaced by future variants of the GCV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20Narrative.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044607/http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20Narrative.pdf |archivedate=2011-04-30 }}</ref><ref>http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4271063&c=AME&s=LAN{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The GCV project was cancelled in 2014.\n\n==Design==\n===Concealment===\nAll versions are equipped with two four-barreled [[M257 grenade launcher]]s on the front of the turret for creating defensive [[smoke screen]]s, [[chaff (countermeasure)|chaff]], and [[flare (countermeasure)|flares]]. It is also fitted with an engine smoke-generating system.\n\n===Armor===\nArmor for the hull and [[turret]] for all variants is [[steel]], [[5083 aluminium alloy|5083 aluminum]], and unique to the turret is [[7039 aluminium alloy|7039 aluminum]].\n\n===NBC===\nThe M3A1 variant introduced a gas particulate filter system.\n\n===Damage control===\nThe M3A1 variant introduced a [[Active fire protection|fire suppression system]].\n\n===Mobility===\nThe Bradley is highly capable in cross-country open terrain, in accordance with one of the main design objectives of keeping pace with the M1 Abrams. Whereas the M113 would float without much preparation, the Bradley was initially designed to float by deploying a flotation curtain around the vehicle. This caused some drownings due to failures during its first trials. Armor upgrades have negated this capability.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} The M3 Bradley was originally developed to accommodate a scout motorcycle. The idea was abandoned when it became apparent that the cycle's unprotected fuel tank could be hazardous to crew members.<ref name=\"motorcycle\">{{cite book |title=M2/M3 Bradley Infantry Fighting Vehicle 1983-95 |author=Steven J. Zaloga, Peter Sarson |year=1996 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=1-85532-538-1 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AwfE210AFj4C&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=M2+Bradley+M3+Bradley+differences#v=onepage&q=M3%20Bradley&f=false |accessdate=2 August 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630102015/http://books.google.com/books?id=AwfE210AFj4C&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=M2+Bradley+M3+Bradley+differences&source=bl&ots=ILpbVlhShs&sig=GRnjkumLssmiItjZ0HmV5n55NbA&hl=en&ei=EOk3TqHHDuOysALkvKU-&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CGAQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=M3%20Bradley&f=false |archivedate=30 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n===M3(A0)===\nThis model is essentially a re-stowed M2 Bradley. The passenger compartment was occupied by two observers and more ammunition and missiles. Because it did not carry a squad, the firing ports were covered. The M3 retained the three periscopes between the cargo hatch and entry ramp and the periscopes along the left side of the vehicle, while those on the right side were covered over as they would have been inaccessible due to the TOW missile stowage rack.<ref name=\"M3\">[http://afvdb.50megs.com/usa/m3bradley.html M3 Bradley] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109060725/http://afvdb.50megs.com/usa/m3bradley.html |date=9 November 2012 }} - afvdb.com</ref>\n\n===M3A1===\nThe M3A1 variant introduced a gas particulate filter system for NBC threats. Unlike the [[M2 Bradley#M2A1|M2A1 Bradley]], the NBC masks connected to the central filter for all five crewmen, instead of just the driver, gunner, and vehicle commander. This variant also introduced a fire suppression system. The three periscopes on the rear deck were omitted on the M3A1, and replaced by four periscopes in the cargo hatch itself.<ref name=\"M3\"/>\n\n===M3A2===\nThe M3A2 incorporated enhanced armor upgrades, such as the ability to mount [[explosive reactive armor]], from the M2A2 Bradley.  After live fire testing, seating and ammunition stowage arrangements were also changed, with the observers moved to a bench on the left side of the vehicle and the missile stowage rearranged to enhance safety.  After the [[Gulf War]], other improvements including an eye-safe carbon dioxide laser rangefinder, [[global positioning system]] and compass, missile countermeasure device, [[Combat Identification Panel|combat identification system]], and thermal viewer for the driver were incorporated into the M3A2-ODS.<ref name=\"M3\"/>\n\n===M3A3===\nThe M3A3 model of the Bradley uses enhanced information and communication equipment, a central processing unit, and information displays for the vehicle commander and squad leader. The M3A3 is compatible with the inter-vehicular communication system of the M1A2 Abrams tank and [[AH-64 Apache|AH-64D Apache Longbow]] helicopter. The commander has an independent thermal viewer and a new integrated sight unit called the Improved Bradley Acquisition System (IBAS), which allows automatic gun adjustments, automatic boresighting, and tracking of dual targets. The roof is reinforced with [[titanium]] armor. Many M3A3s were converted from M3A2s.<ref name=\"M3\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/m2.htm www.fas.org]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/m2.htm www.fas.org]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Cold War armored fighting vehicles of the United States]]\n[[Category:Tracked armoured fighting vehicles]]\n[[Category:Tracked infantry fighting vehicles]]\n[[Category:Military vehicles introduced in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:BAE Systems land vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2017}}\n<!-- Significant information on history is uncited. -->\n{{Infobox weapon\n| name               = M3 Bradley Cavalry Fighting Vehicle\n| image              = Two M-3 Bradleys.jpg\n| image_size         = 300\n| caption            = Two M3 Bradleys in the [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]\n| origin             = [[United States of America]]\n| type               = [[Reconnaissance vehicle]] [[Infantry fighting vehicle]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          =\n| is_bladed          =\n| is_explosive       =\n| is_artillery       =\n| is_vehicle         = yes\n| is_missile         =\n| is_UK              =\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            =\n| used_by            =\n| wars               = [[Gulf War|Persian Gulf War]]<br />[[Iraq War]]\n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = [[FMC Corporation]] (M3(A0), M3A1), [[United Defense]] (M3A2, M3A3)\n| design_date        =\n| manufacturer       =\n| unit_cost          =\n| production_date    =\n| number             =\n| variants           =\n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         =\n| weight             = 25\u201330.5 short tons (23\u201328 tonnes)\n| length             = 21.2\u201321.5&nbsp;ft (6.45\u20136.55&nbsp;m)\n| part_length        =\n| width              = 126\u2013129&nbsp;in (320\u2013328&nbsp;cm)\n| height             = 117&nbsp;in (297&nbsp;cm)\n| diameter           =\n| crew               = 3 + 7 passengers\n<!-- Vehicle/missile specifications -->\n| armour             = Steel, [[5083 aluminium alloy|5083]] and 7039 aluminum\n| primary_armament   = 25&nbsp;mm [[M242 Bushmaster|M242]] Chain Gun<br />1500 rounds (300 ready)<br />Dual [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW]] Anti-Tank Missile Launcher<br />12 rounds (2 in launcher)\n| secondary_armament = 7.62&nbsp;mm [[M240 machine gun|M240C]] machine gun\n| engine             = [[Cummins]] VTA-903\n| engine_power       =\n| pw_ratio           =\n| transmission       = [[General Electric]] HMPT-500\n| payload_capacity   =\n| suspension         =\n| clearance          = 18&nbsp;in (46&nbsp;cm)\n| fuel_capacity      = 175\u2013197&nbsp;gal (662\u2013746&nbsp;L)\n| vehicle_range      = '''Road:''' 250\u2013300&nbsp;mi (400\u2013480&nbsp;km)\n| speed              = '''Top road speed:''' 35\u201341&nbsp;mph (56\u201366&nbsp;km/h)<br /> '''Top water speed:''' 4\u20134.5&nbsp;mph (6.4\u20137.2&nbsp;km/h)\n| guidance           =\n| steering           =\n}}\n\nThe '''M3 Bradley Cavalry Fighting Vehicle''' ('''CFV''') is an American tracked armored [[reconnaissance]] vehicle manufactured by [[BAE Systems Land and Armaments]] (formerly [[United Defense]]). A member of the [[Bradley Fighting Vehicle]] family, the M3 CFV is used by heavy armored cavalry units in the [[United States Army]].\n\n==History==\nThe M3 Bradley CFV is very similar to the [[M2 Bradley]] IFV (Infantry Fighting Vehicle) and is fielded with the same two-man 25mm [[M242 Bushmaster|Bushmaster]] Cannon turret with a coaxial [[M240 machine gun|M240C]] 7.62mm machine gun. It only varies from the M2 in a few subtle ways and by role. The M3 is classified as an armored reconnaissance and scout vehicle and does away with the firing ports found in the M2 series. The M3 also carries more [[BGM-71 TOW|TOW]] missiles as well as more ammunition for its 25mm and 7.62mm guns.\n\nThe Bradley family as a whole was originally intended to support the [[M113 armored personnel carrier|M113]] Armored Personnel Carrier (APC), but ended up replacing it in U.S. Army service altogether. Today, the Bradley is fielded in conjunction with the [[M1 Abrams]] series of main battle tanks and often accompanies infantry squads into combat. In the 1991 Persian Gulf War, Bradleys destroyed more enemy tanks than the M1 Abrams.{{Citation needed|date=June 2016}} Only three Bradleys were lost to enemy fire, however, at least 17 were lost to friendly fire. Improvements to the Bradley family have included enhanced identification features, as well as anti-tank missile countermeasures (for first generation wire-guided missiles only) and improved armor protection in the form of [[explosive reactive armor|ERA]].\n\n===Replacement===\nThe United States and United Kingdom worked jointly on the Future Scout Cavalry System in the 1990s. The U.S. Army's intended replacement for the M3 Bradley and up-armored [[Humvee]] reached the engineering and manufacturing development phase. It reached the engineering and manufacturing development phase before both partners terminated involvement in October 2001 to pursue other more urgent programs: the U.S. [[Interim Armored Vehicle]] and UK [[Future Rapid Effect System]].<ref name=\"FSCS\">{{cite news|last1=Baumgardner|first1=Neil|title=United States, Britain Agree To Terminate Future Scout Cavalry System|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79237089.html|accessdate=12 May 2017|work=Defense Daily|date=18 October 2001|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920152728/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-79237089.html|archivedate=20 September 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 [[Future Combat Systems]] (FCS) planned a successor to the M3 Bradley in the [[Future Combat Systems Manned Ground Vehicles#Reconnaissance and surveillance vehicle|XM1201 Reconnaissance and Surveillance Vehicle]]. That too was canceled when FCS was terminated in 2009.\n\nThe U.S. Army intended the [[Ground Combat Vehicle]] replace the M2 Bradley and M113 by 2018, while the M3 Bradley could later be replaced by future variants of the GCV.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20Narrative.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044607/http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20Narrative.pdf |archivedate=2011-04-30 }}</ref><ref>http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4271063&c=AME&s=LAN{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The GCV project was cancelled in 2014.\n\n==Design==\n===Concealment===\nAll versions are equipped with two four-barreled [[M257 grenade launcher]]s on the front of the turret for creating defensive [[smoke screen]]s, [[chaff (countermeasure)|chaff]], and [[flare (countermeasure)|flares]]. It is also fitted with an engine smoke-generating system.\n\n===Armor===\nArmor for the hull and [[turret]] for all variants is [[steel]], [[5083 aluminium alloy|5083 aluminum]], and unique to the turret is [[7039 aluminium alloy|7039 aluminum]].\n\n===NBC===\nThe M3A1 variant introduced a gas particulate filter system.\n\n===Damage control===\nThe M3A1 variant introduced a [[Active fire protection|fire suppression system]].\n\n===Mobility===\nThe Bradley is highly capable in cross-country open terrain, in accordance with one of the main design objectives of keeping pace with the M1 Abrams. Whereas the M113 would float without much preparation, the Bradley was initially designed to float by deploying a flotation curtain around the vehicle. This caused some drownings due to failures during its first trials. Armor upgrades have negated this capability.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}} The M3 Bradley was originally developed to accommodate a scout motorcycle. The idea was abandoned when it became apparent that the cycle's unprotected fuel tank could be hazardous to crew members.<ref name=\"motorcycle\">{{cite book |title=M2/M3 Bradley Infantry Fighting Vehicle 1983-95 |author=Steven J. Zaloga, Peter Sarson |year=1996 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=1-85532-538-1 |page=17 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=AwfE210AFj4C&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=M2+Bradley+M3+Bradley+differences#v=onepage&q=M3%20Bradley&f=false |accessdate=2 August 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140630102015/http://books.google.com/books?id=AwfE210AFj4C&pg=PA15&lpg=PA15&dq=M2+Bradley+M3+Bradley+differences&source=bl&ots=ILpbVlhShs&sig=GRnjkumLssmiItjZ0HmV5n55NbA&hl=en&ei=EOk3TqHHDuOysALkvKU-&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CGAQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=M3%20Bradley&f=false |archivedate=30 June 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Variants==\n===M3(A0)===\nThis model is essentially a re-stowed M2 Bradley. The passenger compartment was occupied by two observers and more ammunition and missiles. Because it did not carry a squad, the firing ports were covered. The M3 retained the three periscopes between the cargo hatch and entry ramp and the periscopes along the left side of the vehicle, while those on the right side were covered over as they would have been inaccessible due to the TOW missile stowage rack.<ref name=\"M3\">[http://afvdb.50megs.com/usa/m3bradley.html M3 Bradley] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109060725/http://afvdb.50megs.com/usa/m3bradley.html |date=9 November 2012 }} - afvdb.com</ref>\n\n===M3A1===\nThe M3A1 variant introduced a gas particulate filter system for NBC threats. Unlike the [[M2 Bradley#M2A1|M2A1 Bradley]], the NBC masks connected to the central filter for all five crewmen, instead of just the driver, gunner, and vehicle commander. This variant also introduced a fire suppression system. The three periscopes on the rear deck were omitted on the M3A1, and replaced by four periscopes in the cargo hatch itself.<ref name=\"M3\"/>\n\n===M3A2===\nThe M3A2 incorporated enhanced armor upgrades, such as the ability to mount [[explosive reactive armor]], from the M2A2 Bradley.  After live fire testing, seating and ammunition stowage arrangements were also changed, with the observers moved to a bench on the left side of the vehicle and the missile stowage rearranged to enhance safety.  After the [[Gulf War]], other improvements including an eye-safe carbon dioxide laser rangefinder, [[global positioning system]] and compass, missile countermeasure device, [[Combat Identification Panel|combat identification system]], and thermal viewer for the driver were incorporated into the M3A2-ODS.<ref name=\"M3\"/>\n\n===M3A3===\nThe M3A3 model of the Bradley uses enhanced information and communication equipment, a central processing unit, and information displays for the vehicle commander and squad leader. The M3A3 is compatible with the inter-vehicular communication system of the M1A2 Abrams tank and [[AH-64 Apache|AH-64D Apache Longbow]] helicopter. The commander has an independent thermal viewer and a new integrated sight unit called the Improved Bradley Acquisition System (IBAS), which allows automatic gun adjustments, automatic boresighting, and tracking of dual targets. The roof is reinforced with [[titanium]] armor. Many M3A3s were converted from M3A2s.<ref name=\"M3\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [https://fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/m2.htm www.fas.org]\n\n==External links==\n