{"title_page": "Britannia (coin)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox Coin\n|  Denomination = Britannia (One ounce silver)\n|  Country             = United Kingdom\n|  Value               = 2\n|  Unit                = [[pounds sterling]]\n|  Mass                = 32.45g up to 2012<br/> from 2013 31.21\n|  Diameter            = up to 2012 40.00mm<br/> from 2013 38.61\n|  Thickness           =from 2013 3 \n|  Edge                = Milled\n|  Composition         = .958 silver (1997\u20132012)<br/> .999 silver (2013\u2013present)\n|  Years of Minting    = 1997\u2013present\n|  Catalog Number      = \n|  Obverse             =Obverse_of_the_2016_Britannia_bullion_coin.png\n|  Obverse Design      = Queen [[Elizabeth II]]\n|  Obverse Designer    = [[Jody Clark]]\n|  Obverse Design Date = 2015\n|  Reverse             =Britannia-2016-UK-One-Ounce-Silver-Bullion-Coin Reverse.png\n|  Reverse Design      = [[Britannia]]\n|  Reverse Designer    = Philip Nathan\n|  Reverse Design Date = 1987\n}}\n'''Britannia''' [[coins]] are [[United Kingdom|British]] [[bullion coin]]s issued by the [[Royal Mint]] in [[gold]] since 1987 and in [[silver]] since 1997.\n\nBritannia [[gold coin]]s contain one [[troy ounce]] of gold and have a [[face value]] of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]100. Gold Britannias also are issued in fractional sizes of one-half, one-quarter, and one-tenth of a troy ounce and with face values of \u00a350, \u00a325, and \u00a310 respectively. In 2013 two additional sizes were introduced, a five-ounce coin of face value \u00a3500, and a fractional size of one-twentieth of face value \u00a35.<ref name=\"NewValues\">[https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2381622/British-adults-fail-spot-Britannia-coins-confusing-Margaret-Thatcher-Queen-Victoria.html Mrs Thatcher? No that's Britannia! One in four adults cannot recognise figure that has symbolised Britain since Roman times] ''Daily Mail'' 30 July 2013</ref>\n\nBritannia [[silver coin]]s contain one troy ounce of silver and have a face value of \u00a32. Silver Britannias also are issued in fractional sizes of one-half, one-quarter, and one-tenth of a troy ounce and with face values of \u00a31, 50[[Penny sterling|p]], and 20p respectively. Like the gold coins in 2013 two additional sizes were introduced, a five-ounce coin of face value \u00a310, and a fractional size of one-twentieth of face value 10p.<ref name=\"NewValues\" />\n\n==Gold Britannia==\nFrom 2013 the gold coins have a [[millesimal fineness]] of 0.9999 (or 24 carat gold). Until 2012 the gold coins have a [[millesimal fineness]] of 0.917 (91.7% or 22 carat gold) with the non-gold component being [[copper]] until 1989 and silver from 1990.\n\n2013\u2013 '''Gold Britannia specifications''' (gold content, and approx total weight)\n:Five ounces: diameter 65 mm, (156.295 [[gram|g]])\n:One ounce (2013) : diameter 38.61 mm, (31.104 g) 'larger thinner coin' just for 2013\n:One ounce (2014\u2013) : diameter 32.69 mm, (31.104 g)\n:Half ounce: diameter 27 mm, (15.60 g)\n:One quarter ounce: diameter 22 mm, (7.86 g)\n:One tenth ounce: diameter 16.50 mm, (3.13 g)\n:One twentieth ounce: diameter 12 mm, (1.58 g)\n\n1987\u20132012 '''Gold Britannia specifications''' (gold content, not total weight)\n:One ounce: diameter 32.69 mm, (31.104 [[gram|g]]) (total wt 34.050 g)\n:Half ounce: diameter 27.00 mm, (15.552 g)\n:Quarter ounce: diameter 22.00 mm,(7.776 g)\n:Tenth ounce: diameter 16.50 mm, (3.110 g)\n\n==Silver Britannia==\nSince 2013 the silver coins have been produced with a millesimal fineness of 0.999 (99.9% silver).<ref name=\"2013changes\">\n{{cite web\n| url        = https://www.royalmintbullion.com/Products/Britannia/Silver\n| title      = Britannia Silver Coin\n| publisher  = The Royal Mint\n| accessdate = 2020-03-30\n}}</ref> They have a mass of 31.21 grams and diameter of 38.61&nbsp;mm.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/britannia/2020-britannia-coins/britannia-2020-uk-one-ounce-silver-bu-coin/ | title=2020 Britannia One Ounce Silver Brilliant Uncirculated Coin | access-date=2020-03-31 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1997 to 2012 the silver coins had a millesimal fineness of 958 (95.8% or [[Britannia silver]]). Total mass 32.45 grams, diameter 40.00 mm.<ref>[https://www.royalmint.com/The_2012_UK_Britannia_Silver_Proof_One_Ounce_Coin?tab=specification#productdetails 2012 Silver Britannia specifications]</ref>\n\nSilver Britannias have been released each year beginning in 1997, when a silver [[Proof coinage|proof]] set was offered. In 1998 and in all subsequent even-numbered years the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]] design has depicted a standing [[Britannia]] figure. Beginning in 1999 and continuing in odd-numbered years, a series of alternate, non-repeating depictions of Britannia have replaced the standing figure on the reverse. Starting in 2013, the proof versions of the coin will feature a different design each year, while the bullion version of the coin will always feature the classic standing Britannia. While mintage was limited prior to 2013, in 2013 and after mintage of the bullion version of the coin is unlimited based on demand.<ref name=\"2013changes\" />\n\nSome 2014 silver Britannia coins were struck with the incorrect obverse as there was a mix up during the manufacturing process with the 'Lunar' Year of the Horse coins from The Royal Mint, as both coins were to the same fineness and specification,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/shop/Lunar_Year_of_the_Horse_2014_UK_One_Ounce_Silver_Proof_Coin?tab=detail#productdetails | title=Lunar Year of the Horse 2014 UK One Ounce Silver Proof Coin | accessdate=2013-03-12}}</ref> and similar but not identical obverse sides. It is thought that there are around 17,000 examples with the mis-strike, which have been dubbed the 'Mule Britannia' These coins have fetched substantial premiums on online auction sites.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.coinworld.com/news/mule-britannia-error-versions-of-silver-2-coins-surface.all.html | title='Mule' Britannia: error versions of silver \u00a32 coins surface | date=Mar 3, 2014 | accessdate=2014-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Silver Britannia mintages===\nThe following table has the most recent numbers of coins minted by year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://silverbullionworld.com/britanniamintage.html | title=Silver Britannia Mintage | publisher=Silver Bullion World | accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Uncirculated\n!1oz Proof (Orders / Issue Limit)\n!Proof sets (Orders / Issue Limit)\n!5oz Proof\n|-\n|1997   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |\u2013\n|align=\"center\" |16,005\n|align=\"center\" |11,832\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|1998   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |88,909\n|align=\"center\" |3,044\n|align=\"center\" |3,044\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|1999   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |69,394\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2000   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |81,301\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2001   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |44,816\n|align=\"center\" |4,596\n|align=\"center\" |10,000\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2002   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |48,816\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2003<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2003-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2003 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref> (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |73,271\n|align=\"center\" |2,016 / 5,000\n|align=\"center\" |3,669 / 5,000\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2004<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2004-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2004 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |2,174 / 5,000\n|align=\"center\" | \u2013\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2005<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2005-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2005 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |1,539 / 2,500\n|align=\"center\" |2,360 / 3,500\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2006<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2006-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2006 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |2,529 / 2,750\n|align=\"center\" |3,000 / 3,000 (The Silhouette Collection encompasses 5 styles which are 1oz .999 silver & gold gilt)\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2007<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2007-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2007 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |5,157 / 7,500\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2008<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2008-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2008 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2009<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2009-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2009 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |6,784\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2010<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2010-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2010 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |126,367\n|align=\"center\" |6,539\n|align=\"center\" |3,497\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2011<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2011-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2011 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |4,973\n|align=\"center\" |2,483 / 2,500\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2012     (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |2,500\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2013 (.999 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 in limited edition presentation, max mintage 8,500 \n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |1,150 in limited edition presentation, 3,500 in First Strike Presentation, max mintage 4,650\n|-\n|2013 (.999 Ag) Snake Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |300,000\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|-\n|2014 (.999 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 in limited edition presentation, max mintage 5,300\n|align=\"center\" |1,750 in limited edition presentation, 550 in First Strike Presentation \n|align=\"center\" |600 in limited edition presentation, 750 in First Strike Presentation, max mintage 1,350\n|-\n|2014 (.999 Ag) Horse Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |1,000,000\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|-\n|2015 (.999 Ag) \n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |unknown \n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|-\n|2015 (.999 Ag) Goat Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |200,000\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|-\n|2016 (.999 Ag) \n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |unknown \n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|-\n|2016 (.999 Ag) Monkey Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |176,300\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Money|Numismatics|United Kingdom}}\n*[[American Gold Eagle]]\n*[[Australian Gold Nugget]]\n*[[Sovereign (British coin)|British Sovereign coin]]\n*[[Canadian Gold Maple Leaf]]\n*[[Austrian Silver Vienna Philharmonic|Austrian Philharmonic]]\n*[[Krugerrand]]\n*[[Chinese lunar coins]]\n*[[Gold as an investment]]\n*[[Silver as an investment]]\n\n{{British_coinage}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n*{{numis cite SCWC|date=2005}}\n*''Coins of England & The United Kingdom'', 40th ed., Spink, 2005, {{ISBN|1-902040-59-7}}\n\n[[Category:British gold coins]]\n[[Category:Coins of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Silver coins]]\n[[Category:Currencies introduced in 1987]]\n[[Category:Bullion coins]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox Coin\n|  Denomination = Britannia (One ounce silver)\n|  Country             = United Kingdom\n|  Value               = 2\n|  Unit                = [[pounds sterling]]\n|  Mass                = 32.45g up to 2012<br/> from 2013 31.21\n|  Diameter            = up to 2012 40.00mm<br/> from 2013 38.61\n|  Thickness           =from 2013 3 \n|  Edge                = Milled\n|  Composition         = .958 silver (1997\u20132012)<br/> .999 silver (2013\u2013present)\n|  Years of Minting    = 1997\u2013present\n|  Catalog Number      = \n|  Obverse             =Obverse_of_the_2016_Britannia_bullion_coin.png\n|  Obverse Design      = Queen [[Elizabeth II]]\n|  Obverse Designer    = [[Jody Clark]]\n|  Obverse Design Date = 2015\n|  Reverse             =Britannia-2016-UK-One-Ounce-Silver-Bullion-Coin Reverse.png\n|  Reverse Design      = [[Britannia]]\n|  Reverse Designer    = Philip Nathan\n|  Reverse Design Date = 1987\n}}\n'''Britannia''' [[coins]] are [[United Kingdom|British]] [[bullion coin]]s issued by the [[Royal Mint]] in [[gold]] since 1987 and in [[silver]] since 1997.\n\nBritannia [[gold coin]]s contain one [[troy ounce]] of gold and have a [[face value]] of [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]100. Gold Britannias also are issued in fractional sizes of one-half, one-quarter, and one-tenth of a troy ounce and with face values of \u00a350, \u00a325, and \u00a310 respectively. In 2013 two additional sizes were introduced, a five-ounce coin of face value \u00a3500, and a fractional size of one-twentieth of face value \u00a35.<ref name=\"NewValues\">[https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2381622/British-adults-fail-spot-Britannia-coins-confusing-Margaret-Thatcher-Queen-Victoria.html Mrs Thatcher? No that's Britannia! One in four adults cannot recognise figure that has symbolised Britain since Roman times] ''Daily Mail'' 30 July 2013</ref>\n\nBritannia [[silver coin]]s contain one troy ounce of silver and have a face value of \u00a32. Silver Britannias also are issued in fractional sizes of one-half, one-quarter, and one-tenth of a troy ounce and with face values of \u00a31, 50[[Penny sterling|p]], and 20p respectively. Like the gold coins in 2013 two additional sizes were introduced, a five-ounce coin of face value \u00a310, and a fractional size of one-twentieth of face value 10p.<ref name=\"NewValues\" />\n\n==Gold Britannia==\nFrom 2013 the gold coins have a [[millesimal fineness]] of 0.9999 (or 24 carat gold). Until 2012 the gold coins have a [[millesimal fineness]] of 0.917 (91.7% or 22 carat gold) with the non-gold component being [[copper]] until 1989 and silver from 1990.\n\n2013\u2013 '''Gold Britannia specifications''' (gold content, and approx total weight)\n:Five ounces: diameter 65 mm, (156.295 [[gram|g]])\n:One ounce (2013) : diameter 38.61 mm, (31.104 g) 'larger thinner coin' just for 2013\n:One ounce (2014\u2013) : diameter 32.69 mm, (31.104 g)\n:Half ounce: diameter 27 mm, (15.60 g)\n:One quarter ounce: diameter 22 mm, (7.86 g)\n:One tenth ounce: diameter 16.50 mm, (3.13 g)\n:One twentieth ounce: diameter 12 mm, (1.58 g)\n\n1987\u20132012 '''Gold Britannia specifications''' (gold content, not total weight)\n:One ounce: diameter 32.69 mm, (31.104 [[gram|g]]) (total wt 34.050 g)\n:Half ounce: diameter 27.00 mm, (15.552 g)\n:Quarter ounce: diameter 22.00 mm,(7.776 g)\n:Tenth ounce: diameter 16.50 mm, (3.110 g)\n\n==Silver Britannia==\nSince 2013 the silver coins have been produced with a millesimal fineness of 0.999 (99.9% silver).<ref name=\"2013changes\">\n{{cite web\n| url        = https://www.royalmintbullion.com/Products/Britannia/Silver\n| title      = Britannia Silver Coin\n| publisher  = The Royal Mint\n| accessdate = 2020-03-30\nm}}</ref> They have a mass of 31.21 grams and diameter of 38.61&nbsp;mm.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/britannia/2020-britannia-coins/britannia-2020-uk-one-ounce-silver-bu-coin/ | title=2020 Britannia One Ounce Silver Brilliant Uncirculated Coin | access-date=2020-03-31 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 1997 to 2012 the silver coins had a millesimal fineness of 958 (95.8% or [[Britannia silver]]). Total mass 32.45 grams, diameter 40.00 mm.<ref>[https://www.royalmint.com/The_2012_UK_Britannia_Silver_Proof_One_Ounce_Coin?tab=specification#productdetails 2012 Silver Britannia specifications]</ref>\n\nSilver Britannias have been released each year beginning in 1997, when a silver [[Proof coinage|proof]] set was offered. In 1998 and in all subsequent even-numbered years the [[Obverse and reverse|reverse]] design has depicted a standing [[Britannia]] figure. Beginning in 1999 and continuing in odd-numbered years, a series of alternate, non-repeating depictions of Britannia have replaced the standing figure on the reverse. Starting in 2013, the proof versions of the coin will feature a different design each year, while the bullion version of the coin will always feature the classic standing Britannia. While mintage was limited prior to 2013, in 2013 and after mintage of the bullion version of the coin is unlimited based on demand.<ref name=\"2013changes\" />\n\nSome 2014 silver Britannia coins were struck with the incorrect obverse as there was a mix up during the manufacturing process with the 'Lunar' Year of the Horse coins from The Royal Mint, as both coins were to the same fineness and specification,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/shop/Lunar_Year_of_the_Horse_2014_UK_One_Ounce_Silver_Proof_Coin?tab=detail#productdetails | title=Lunar Year of the Horse 2014 UK One Ounce Silver Proof Coin | accessdate=2013-03-12}}</ref> and similar but not identical obverse sides. It is thought that there are around 17,000 examples with the mis-strike, which have been dubbed the 'Mule Britannia' These coins have fetched substantial premiums on online auction sites.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.coinworld.com/news/mule-britannia-error-versions-of-silver-2-coins-surface.all.html | title='Mule' Britannia: error versions of silver \u00a32 coins surface | date=Mar 3, 2014 | accessdate=2014-03-12}}</ref>\n\n===Silver Britannia mintages===\nThe following table has the most recent numbers of coins minted by year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://silverbullionworld.com/britanniamintage.html | title=Silver Britannia Mintage | publisher=Silver Bullion World | accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Uncirculated\n!1oz Proof (Orders / Issue Limit)\n!Proof sets (Orders / Issue Limit)\n!5oz Proof\n|-\n|1997   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |\u2013\n|align=\"center\" |16,005\n|align=\"center\" |11,832\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|1998   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |88,909\n|align=\"center\" |3,044\n|align=\"center\" |3,044\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|1999   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |69,394\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | no proof coins released\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2000   (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |81,301\