ales | title=2007 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |5,157 / 7,500\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2008<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2008-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2008 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2009<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2009-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2009 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |6,784\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 / 2,500 (Sold out)\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2010<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2010-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2010 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |126,367\n|align=\"center\" |6,539\n|align=\"center\" |3,497\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2011<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.royalmint.com/discover/uk-coins/circulation-coin-mintage-figures/2011-dated-uk-collector-coin-sales | title=2011 Dated UK Collector Coin Sales}}</ref>(.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |4,973\n|align=\"center\" |2,483 / 2,500\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2012     (.958 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |100,000\n|align=\"center\" |2,500\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" | not available\n|-\n|2013 (.999 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 in limited edition presentation, max mintage 8,500 \n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |1,150 in limited edition presentation, 3,500 in First Strike Presentation, max mintage 4,650\n|-\n|2013 (.999 Ag) Snake Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |300,000\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|-\n|2014 (.999 Ag)\n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |2,500 in limited edition presentation, max mintage 5,300\n|align=\"center\" |1,750 in limited edition presentation, 550 in First Strike Presentation \n|align=\"center\" |600 in limited edition presentation, 750 in First Strike Presentation, max mintage 1,350\n|-\n|2014 (.999 Ag) Horse Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |1,000,000\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|-\n|2015 (.999 Ag) \n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |unknown \n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|-\n|2015 (.999 Ag) Goat Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |200,000\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|-\n|2016 (.999 Ag) \n|align=\"center\" |Mint to Order\n|align=\"center\" |unknown \n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|align=\"center\" |unknown\n|-\n|2016 (.999 Ag) Monkey Privy Rim\n|align=\"center\" |176,300\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|align=\"center\" |-\n|align=\"center\" |0\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Money|Numismatics|United Kingdom}}\n*[[American Gold Eagle]]\n*[[Australian Gold Nugget]]\n*[[Sovereign (British coin)|British Sovereign coin]]\n*[[Canadian Gold Maple Leaf]]\n*[[Austrian Silver Vienna Philharmonic|Austrian Philharmonic]]\n*[[Krugerrand]]\n*[[Chinese lunar coins]]\n*[[Gold as an investment]]\n*[[Silver as an investment]]\n\n{{British_coinage}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n*{{numis cite SCWC|date=2005}}\n*''Coins of England & The United Kingdom'', 40th ed., Spink, 2005, {{ISBN|1-902040-59-7}}\n\n[[Category:British gold coins]]\n[[Category:Coins of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Silver coins]]\n[[Category:Currencies introduced in 1987]]\n[[Category:Bullion coins]]\n", "name_user": "BlueSingularity", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSilver Britannia:Fixed reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Britannia_(coin)"}
{"title_page": "University College London", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = UCL\n| image_name = University College London logo.svg<!-- Please do not insert the so-called \"crest\" or \"coat of arms\" formerly used by UCL here. It has never been official, and is not in current use. -->\n| caption = UCL logo since 2005\n| former_names = London University (1826\u20131836)<br />University College, London (1836\u20131907)<br />University of London, University College (1907\u20131976) <br />University College London (1977\u20132005; remains legal name)\n| latin_name = Collegium Universitatis Londinensis<ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g6xAAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA537|page=537|title=Record of the Celebration of the Quatercentenary of the University of Aberdeen|publisher=[[University of Aberdeen]]|date=1907|chapter=Address from University College London}}</ref>\n| motto = ''Cuncti adsint meritaeque expectent praemia palmae'' {{small|(Latin)}}\n| mottoeng = ''Let all come who by merit deserve the most reward''\n| established = 1826\n| type = [[Public university|Public]] [[research university]]\n| endowment = \u00a3118.0 million {{small|(at 31 July 2018)}}<ref name=finstat/>\n| budget = [[Pounds sterling|\u00a3]]1.431.7 billion {{small|(university)}}; \u00a31.451.1 billion {{small|(consolidated)\n (2017\u201318)}}<ref name=finstat/>\n| chancellor = [[Anne, Princess Royal|The Princess Royal]]<br />{{small|(as Chancellor of the [[University of London]])}}\n| provost = [[Michael Arthur (physician)|Michael Arthur]]\n| head_label = Chair of the Council\n| head = [[DeAnne Julius|Dame DeAnne Julius]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/srs/governance-and-committees/governance/council/membership|title=UCL Council|publisher=University College London|accessdate=26 October 2014}}</ref>\n| free_label = [[Visitor]]\n| free = [[Terence Etherton]]<br />{{small|(as [[Master of the Rolls]] ''[[ex officio]]'')}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/who-we-are/officers |title=UCL Officers|accessdate=4 February 2013 |publisher=University College London}}</ref>\n| academic_staff = 7,700 (2018/19)<ref name=HESAstaff/>\n| administrative_staff = 5,375 (2018/19)<ref name=HESAstaff/>\n| students = {{HESA student population|INSTID=0149}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| undergrad = {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0149}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| postgrad = {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0149}} ({{HESA year}})<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/>\n| city = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| affiliations = {{Collapsible list\n| [[Alan Turing Institute]]<br />[[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]]<br />[[European Network for Training Economic Research|ENTER]]<br />[[European University Association]]<br />[[Francis Crick Institute]]<br />[[G5 (universities)|G5]]<br />[[Golden triangle (universities)|Golden triangle]]<br />[[League of European Research Universities|LERU]]<br />[[Russell Group]]<br />[[SES (universities)|SES]]<br />[[Thomas Young Centre]]<br />[[UCL Partners]]<br />[[University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust|UCLH]]<br />[[University of London]]<br />[[Universities Research Association|URA]]<br />[[Universities UK]]}}\n| colours = {{scarf|{{cells|3|#602899}}{{cell|#6cf}}{{cells|3|#602899}}{{cell|#6cf}}{{cells|3|#602899}}}}\n| nickname = \n| mascot = \n| website = [https://ucl.ac.uk/ ucl.ac.uk]\n| logo = \n}}\n<!-- Please do not make large changes to the lead without discussing them on the article's talk page.-->\n<!-- Please keep the lead encyclopedic and factual. Please do not selectively cherry pick rankings or attempt to turn this into brochure ware.-->\n<!--Paragraph 1/5: Lead paragraph (should \"should define or identify the topic with a neutral point of view, but without being too specific\". [[WP:LEADPARAGRAPH]])-->\n'''University College London''', officially known as '''UCL''' since 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/submit-events/events/StyleguideFINAL.pdf|title=Making an Impact: the UCL style guide|date=2005|publisher=UCL|page=44|quote=UCL should always be referred to as 'UCL'. \"University College London\" can only be used as part of the postal address.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=John |last=Sutherland |authorlink=John Sutherland (author)|date=29 July 2005|title=What's in a name?|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2005/jul/29/highereducation.news1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/cam/sites/cam/files/migrated-files/ucl-visual-identity-poster.pdf|title=Working with our brand|publisher=UCL|accessdate=30 March 2019|quote=UCL is the university's official name}}</ref> is a [[public university|public]] [[research university]] located in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]. It is a [[Member institutions of the University of London|member institution]] of the [[Federal university|federal]] [[University of London]], and is the {{HESA student population rank|INSTID=0149}} largest [[List of universities in the United Kingdom by enrolment|university in the United Kingdom by total enrolment]],<ref name=\"HESA citation\">{{HESA citation}}</ref> and the largest by postgraduate enrolment.\n\n<!--Paragraph 2/5: Introduction and History (Broad description of type and location):-->\nEstablished in 1826 as '''London University''' by founders inspired by the radical ideas of [[Jeremy Bentham]], UCL was the first university institution to be established in London, and the first in England to be entirely secular and to admit students regardless of their religion.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Harte|first1=Negley|last2=North|first2=John|title=The World of UCL 1828\u20132004|date=2004|publisher=UCL|location=London|isbn=978-1-84472-025-5|pages=29\u201332}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Students defend freedom of expression at University College London|url=http://www.secularism.org.uk/news/2012/01/students-defend-freedom-of-expression-at-university-college-london|accessdate=11 February 2018|publisher=The Secular Society}}</ref> UCL also makes the contested claims of being the [[third oldest university in England debate|third-oldest university in England]]<ref group=\"note\">The title of third-oldest university in England is claimed by three institutions: Durham University as the third-oldest officially recognised university (1832) and the third to confer degrees (1837), the University of London as the third university to be granted a Royal Charter (1836), and University College London as it was founded as London University (1826) and was the third-oldest university institution to start teaching (1828). A fourth institution, King's College London, officially claims to be the fourth-oldest university in England; it was the third university institution to receive a Royal Charter (1829) and some claim it as third oldest on that basis. Deciding which is the \"third oldest university\" depends largely on the definition of university status.</ref> and the first to admit women.<ref group=\"note\">The [[University of Bristol]] also makes this claim, having admitted women from its foundation (as a college) in 1876.</ref> In 1836 UCL became one of the two founding [[colleges of the University of London]], which was granted a royal charter in the same year. It has grown through mergers, including with the [[UCL Institute of Neurology|Institute of Neurology]] (in 1997), the [[Royal Free Hospital]] Medical School (in 1998), the [[UCL Eastman Dental Institute|Eastman Dental Institute]] (in 1999), the [[UCL School of Slavonic and East European Studies|School of Slavonic and East European Studies]] (in 1999), the [[UCL School of Pharmacy|School of Pharmacy]] (in 2012) and the [[UCL Institute of Education|Institute of Education]] (in 2014).\n\n<!--Paragraph 3/5: Location, organisation and academic structure:-->\nUCL has its main campus in the [[Bloomsbury]] area of [[central London]], with a number of institutes and teaching hospitals elsewhere in central London and satellite campuses in [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]] in [[Stratford, London|Stratford]], east London and in [[Doha, Qatar]]. UCL is organised into [[University College London#Faculties and departments|11 constituent faculties]], within which there are over 100 departments, institutes and research centres. UCL operates several museums and collections in a wide range of fields, including the [[Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology]] and the [[Grant Museum of Zoology and Comparative Anatomy]], and administers the annual [[Orwell Prize]] in political writing. In 2017/18, UCL had around 41,500 students and 15,100 staff (including around 7,100 academic staff and 840 professors) and had a total group income of \u00a31.45 billion, of which \u00a3476.3 million was from research grants and contracts.<ref name=finstat>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/finance/docs/docs-corporate/2018_UCL-annual-report.pdf|title=Annual Report and Financial Statements for the year ended 31 July 2018|publisher=University College London|accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n<!--Paragraph 4/5: Rankings and affiliations:-->\nIn the most recent [[Research Excellence Framework]] rankings for research power, UCL was the top-rated university in the UK as calculated by ''[[Times Higher Education]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/ref-2014-is-london-now-dominant/2017617.article |title= REF 2014: Is London now dominant?|work=Times Higher Education |accessdate=20 March 2018|date=18 December 2014|author=Chris Havergal}}</ref> and second as calculated by ''[[The Guardian]]''/''[[Research Fortnight]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/ng-interactive/2014/dec/18/university-research-excellence-framework-2014-full-rankings|title= University Research Excellence Framework 2014 \u2013 the full rankings|work=The Guardian|accessdate=20 March 2018|date=18 December 2014}}</ref> UCL had the 9th highest average entry tariff in the UK for students starting in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Entry+Standards&y=2019|title=University League Tables 2019|work=Complete University Guide|access-date=20 December 2018|at=(Sorted by \"Entry Standards\")}}</ref> UCL is ranked from eighth to eighteenth in the four major international rankings,<ref name=\"Academic Ranking of World Universities\"/><ref name=\"CWTS Leiden Ranking\"/><ref name=\"QS World University Rankings\"/><ref name=\"THE World University Rankings\"/> and from eighth to twenty-second in the [[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom|national league tables]].<ref name=\"Complete League Table\"/><ref name=\"The Guardian University Guide\"/><ref name=\"The Times and Sunday Times University Guide\"/> UCL is a member of numerous academic organisations, including the [[Russell Group]] and the [[League of European Research Universities]], and is part of [[UCL Partners]], the world's largest [[academic health science centre]],<ref name=\"Health Service Journal\">{{cite news|url=http://m.hsj.co.uk/5036604.article|title=UCL Partners to become 'biggest AHSC in the world'|accessdate=25 November 2013|work=Health Service Journal|date=17 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225347/http://m.hsj.co.uk/5036604.article|archivedate=2 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and the \"[[Golden triangle (universities)|golden triangle]]\" of research-intensive English universities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nature.com/naturejobs/2005/050707/full/nj7047-144a.html| title=Golden opportunities|accessdate=19 October 2010|work=Nature| date=6 July 2005}}</ref>\n\n<!--Paragraph 5/5: People:-->\nUCL alumni include the respective \"[[Father of the Nation|Fathers of the Nation]]\" of India, Kenya and Mauritius, the founders of Ghana, modern Japan and Nigeria, the inventor of the telephone, and one of the co-discoverers of the structure of [[DNA]]. UCL academics discovered five of the naturally occurring [[noble gases]], discovered [[hormone]]s, invented the [[vacuum tube]], and made several [[history of statistics|foundational advances]] in modern statistics. As of 2019, [[List of Nobel laureates affiliated with University College London|33 Nobel Prize winners]] and [[List of Fields Medal winners by university affiliation|3 Fields medalists]] have been affiliated with UCL as alumni, faculty or researchers.<ref group=\"note\">Universities practice different methods for counting Nobel prize affiliates, from the flattering to the highly conservative. As of March 2016, UCL had an \"official count\" of 29 Nobel affiliates as students or academics, and a further 11 as honorary graduates or honorary fellows.</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of University College London}}\n\n===1826 to 1836 \u2013 London University===\n[[File:The London University by Thomas Hosmer Shepherd 1827-28.JPG|right|thumb|''The London University'' as drawn by [[Thomas Hosmer Shepherd]] and published in 1827\u20131828 (now the [[UCL Main Building]])]]\nUCL was founded on 11 February 1826 under the name London University, as an alternative to the [[Anglican]] universities of Oxford and Cambridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/about-ucl-home/history-page |title=History |publisher=University College London |accessdate=22 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117132404/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/about-ucl-home/history-page |archive-date=17 January 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RD4hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA6100&dq=university+college+london+february+11+1826 | encyclopedia=Americanized Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica | volume=10 | year=1890 | page=6100 | accessdate=9 February 2011| title=Americanized Encyclopedia Britannica, Revised and Amended: A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences and Literature; to which is Added Biographies of Livings Subjects }}</ref><ref name=\"Penman\">{{cite web|last1=Penman|first1=Colin|title=The youth of our middling rich: how egalitarian were UCL's founders? \u2013 UCL Lunch Hour Lecture|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eMnaY3g7etQ|website=You tube|publisher=UCL Lunch Hour Lectures|accessdate=31 March 2017|date=27 February 2017}}</ref> London University's first Warden was [[Leonard Horner]], who was the first scientist to head a British university.<ref>{{cite book |title=John Phillips and the Business of Victorian Science|first1=Jack|last1=Morrell|publisher=Ashgate Publishing|year=2005|isbn=978-1840142396|page=87|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Hq1VPHtxG00C&dq=Leonard+Horner+first+warden}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Four founders of UCL.JPG|thumb|left|upright|[[Henry Tonks]]' 1923 mural ''The Four Founders of UCL'']]\nDespite the commonly held belief that the philosopher [[Jeremy Bentham]] was the founder of UCL, his direct involvement was limited to the purchase of share No. 633, at a cost of \u00a3100 paid in nine instalments between December 1826 and January 1830. In 1828 he did nominate a friend to sit on the council, and in 1827 attempted to have his disciple [[John Bowring]] appointed as the first professor of English or History, but on both occasions his candidates were unsuccessful.<ref>{{cite book|last=Harte|first=Negley|chapter=The owner of share no. 633: Jeremy Bentham and University College London |editor-first=Catherine |editor-last=Fuller |title=The Old Radical: representations of Jeremy Bentham |location=London |publisher=University College London |year=1998 |pages=5\u20138}}</ref> This suggests that while his ideas may have been influential, he himself was less so. However, Bentham is today commonly regarded as the \"spiritual father\" of UCL, as his radical ideas on education and society were the inspiration to the institution's founders, particularly the Scotsmen [[James Mill]] (1773\u20131836) and [[Henry Brougham, 1st Baron Brougham and Vaux|Henry Brougham]] (1778\u20131868).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Bentham-Project/who/bentham_ucl|title=Bentham and UCL|publisher=University College London|accessdate=28 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306201106/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Bentham-Project/who/bentham_ucl|archive-date=6 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1827, the Chair of Political Economy at London University was created, with [[John Ramsay McCulloch]] as the first incumbent, establishing one of the first departments of economics in England.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Cyclopedia of Education: Volume Two|first1=Paul|last1=Monroe|publisher=The Macmillan Company|year=1915|isbn=978-1440061509|page=388|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KnBQrH2kuZEC}}</ref> In 1828 the university became the first in England to offer English as a subject<ref>{{cite book |title=Beginning Theory: An Introduction to Literary and Cultural Theory|first1=Peter|last1=Barry|publisher=Manchester University Press|year=2002|isbn=978-0719062681|page=12|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SNy26bx7L5UC}}</ref> and the teaching of Classics and medicine began. In 1830, London University founded the London University School, which would later become [[University College School]]. In 1833, the university appointed [[Alexander Maconochie (penal reformer)|Alexander Maconochie]], Secretary to the [[Royal Geographical Society]], as the first professor of geography in the UK. In 1834, [[University College Hospital]] (originally North London Hospital) opened as a teaching hospital for the university's medical school.<ref>{{cite book |title=The University of London and its colleges: constituting, the most wonderful aggregation of institutions to be found anywhere in the world|first1=Stanley|last1=Wilson|publisher=University Tutorial Press|year=1923|isbn=|page=129|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AnAxAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>\n\n===1836 to 1900 \u2013 University College, London===\nIn 1836, London University was incorporated by [[royal charter]] under the name ''University College, London''. On the same day, the [[University of London]] was created by royal charter as a degree-awarding examining board for students from affiliated schools and colleges, with University College and [[King's College London|King's College, London]] being named in the charter as the first two affiliates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TZtRAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA564|title=The English Universities: From the German|first=Victor Aim\u00e9|last=Huber|date=24 June 2017|publisher=William Pickering|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Slade School of Fine Art]] was founded as part of University College in 1871, following a bequest from [[Felix Slade]].<ref>{{cite book |title=The Oxford Dictionary of Art|first1=Ian|last1=Chilvers|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0198604761|page=655|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WYaRX58a0_IC}}</ref>\n\nIn 1878, the University of London gained a supplemental charter making it the first British university to be allowed to award degrees to women. The same year, UCL admitted women to the faculties of Arts and Law and of Science, although women remained barred from the faculties of Engineering and of Medicine (with the exception of courses on public health and hygiene).<ref>{{cite book |title=The University of London, 1836\u20131986: An Illustrated History|first1=N.B.|last1=Harte|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|year=1986|isbn=978-0485120523|page=132|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PysucrsTkWAC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite document|title=The place of university education in the life of women.An address delivered at the Women's institute on November 23rd, 1897|first=Eleanor Mildred|last=Sidgwick|date=15 August 1897|publisher=[London|hdl = 2027/uc2.ark:/13960/t4xg9hw0c}}</ref> While UCL claims to have been the first university in England to admit women on equal terms to men, from 1878, the [[University of Bristol]] also makes this claim, having admitted women from its foundation (as a college) in 1876.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bristol.ac.uk/university/history/|title=History of the University|publisher=University of Bristol|accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref> Armstrong College, a predecessor institution of [[Newcastle University]], also allowed women to enter from its foundation in 1871, although none actually enrolled until 1881.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Durham University Journal]]|title=The Jubilee of Armstrong College|pages=347\u2013354|author=P. Phillips Bedson|url=https://books.google.com/?id=GUxIAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA347|date=December 1921|volume=22}}</ref> Women were finally admitted to medical studies during the First World War in 1917, although limitations were placed on their numbers after the war ended.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LcAeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA120|title=Women in Twentieth-Century Britain: Social, Cultural and Political Change |first=Ina|last=Zweiniger-Bargielowska|author-link=Ina Zweiniger-Bargielowska|date=30 July 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317876922 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n[[File:William Ramsay working.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[William Ramsay]] is regarded as the \"father of noble gases\".]]\n\nIn 1898, [[Sir William Ramsay]] discovered the [[Chemical element|elements]] [[krypton]], [[neon]] and [[xenon]] whilst professor of chemistry at UCL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1904/ramsay-bio.html|title=The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1904: Sir William Ramsay|accessdate=27 June 2012|publisher=The Nobel Foundation}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-12402481|title=Sir William Ramsay: The noble chemist|accessdate=27 June 2012|work=BBC News|date=9 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n===1900 to 1976 \u2013 University of London, University College===\nIn 1900, the University of London was reconstituted as a federal university with new statutes drawn up under the University of London Act 1898. UCL, along with a number of other colleges in London, became a school of the University of London. While most of the constituent institutions retained their autonomy, UCL was merged into the University in 1907 under the University College London (Transfer) Act 1905 and lost its legal independence.<ref>{{cite book|title=\"University of London, the Historical Record: (1836\u20131912)|publisher=[[University of London]]|date=1912|pages=7\u201324|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vyPiAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA7}}</ref> Its formal name became ''University of London, University College'', although for most informal and external purposes the name \"University College, London\" (or the initialism UCL) was still used.\n\n1900 also saw the decision to appoint a salaried head of the college. The first incumbent was [[Carey Foster]], who served as [[Principal (academia)|Principal]] (as the post was originally titled) from 1900 to 1904. He was succeeded by [[Gregory Foster]] (no relation), and in 1906 the title was changed to [[Provost (education)|Provost]] to avoid confusion with the Principal of the University of London. Gregory Foster remained in post until 1929.<ref>Harte and North 2004, pp. 160\u201361.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/special-collections/a-z/foster-gregory|title=Foster, Sir Gregory: Papers|publisher=UCL}}</ref><ref name=\"Former Provosts\">{{cite web |title=Former Provosts |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/provost/former-provosts |publisher=University College London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160229164231/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/provost/former-provosts |archive-date=29 February 2016 |access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref> In 1906, the Cruciform Building was opened as the new home for [[University College Hospital]].<ref>{{cite book |title=University College Hospital and its Medical School: A History|first1=W|last1=Merrington|publisher=Heinemann|year=1976|isbn=978-0434465002|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VbV1QgAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\nUCL sustained considerable bomb damage during the Second World War, including to the Great Hall and the Carey Foster Physics Laboratory. The first UCL student magazine, ''[[Pi Magazine]]'', was published for the first time on 21 February 1946. The [[Institute of Jewish Studies at University College London|Institute of Jewish Studies]] relocated to UCL in 1959.\n\nThe [[Mullard Space Science Laboratory]] was established in 1967.<ref>{{cite book |title=History of British Space Science|first1=Harrie|last1=Massie|first2=M.|last2=Robins|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0521123389|page=220|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bqQsjc3BwZkC}}</ref> In 1973, UCL became the first international node to the precursor of the internet, the ARPANET.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/3280897.stm|title=30 years of the international internet|accessdate=22 June 2012|work=BBC News|date=19 November 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=185049&sectioncode=26|title=UCL marks 30 years of e-networking|accessdate=22 June 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=21 November 2003}}</ref>\n\nAlthough UCL was among the first universities to admit women on the same terms as men, in 1878, the college's senior common room, the Housman Room, remained men-only until 1969. After two unsuccessful attempts, a motion was passed that ended segregation by sex at UCL. This was achieved by [[Brian Woledge]] (Fielden Professor of French at UCL from 1939 to 1971) and [[David Colquhoun]], at that time a young lecturer in pharmacology.<ref>{{cite web |author=David Colquhoun |title=UCL's senior common room and the Boston marathon: emancipation in the 1960s, and now |work=DC's Improbable Science. 2002| url=http://www.dcscience.net/2014/08/25/ucls-senior-common-room-and-the-boston-marathon-emancipation-in-the-1960s-and-now/}}</ref>\n\n===1976 to 2005 \u2013 University College London===\n{{multiple image |align=right |direction=vertical |width=200 |image1=Portico and steps, University College, London - geograph.org.uk - 364428.jpg |alt1=UCL |caption1=The Wilkins Building in 1956 |image2=Wilkins Building 1, UCL, London - Diliff.jpg |alt2=UCL |caption2=Today}}\nIn 1976, a new charter restored UCL's legal independence, although still without the power to award its own degrees.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/history/landmarks |title=Landmarks |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080130051135/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/history/landmarks |archivedate = 30 January 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723085541/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/ras/acs/governance/documents/charter-and-statutes|archive-date=23 July 2013|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/ras/acs/governance/documents/charter-and-statutes |title=Royal Charter granted 17 November 1976 |accessdate=16 August 2013}}</ref> Under this charter the college became formally known as ''University College London''. This name abandoned the comma used in its earlier name of \"University College, London\".\n\nIn 1986, UCL merged with the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology|Institute of Archaeology]].<ref name=guard221002>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2002/oct/22/highereducation.universitymergers |title=The merger and the man|accessdate=23 June 2012|work=The Guardian|date=22 October 2002|first=Donald|last=MacLeod}}</ref> In 1988, UCL merged with the Institute of Laryngology & Otology, the Institute of Orthopaedics, the Institute of Urology & Nephrology and [[Middlesex Hospital|Middlesex Hospital Medical School]].<ref name=guard221002/>\n\nIn 1993, a reorganisation of the University of London meant that UCL and other colleges gained direct access to government funding and the right to confer University of London degrees themselves. This led to UCL being regarded as a ''de facto'' university in its own right.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|title= College vote brings break-up of university a step nearer|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/dec/10/highereducation.administration|quote=Over the past 10 years the university has become an increasingly loose federation of independent institutions that are universities in their own right and receive their grants directly from the Higher Education Funding Council for England, although they still hand out degrees on behalf of the central university.|date=10 December 2005|author1=Rebecca Smithers|author2=Donald MacLeod}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, the [[University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust|University College London Hospitals NHS Trust]] was established.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2011/mar/25/university-college-london-hospitals-nhs-foundation-trust-profile|title=University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust \u2013 NHS hospital trust profile|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 June 2013|first=Kable|last=Healthcare|date=25 March 2011}}</ref> UCL merged with the College of Speech Sciences and the [[UCL Institute of Ophthalmology|Institute of Ophthalmology]] in 1995, the [[UCL Institute of Child Health|Institute of Child Health]] and the School of Podiatry in 1996<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=99328&sectioncode=26|title=UCL steps up to world class|accessdate=14 August 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=6 September 1996}}</ref> and the [[UCL Institute of Neurology|Institute of Neurology]] in 1997.<ref name=guard221002/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=102036&sectioncode=26|title=Medicine in the capital|accessdate=27 June 2012| work=Times Higher Education| date=14 February 1997}}</ref> In 1998, UCL merged with the Royal Free Hospital Medical School to create the Royal Free and University College Medical School (renamed the [[UCL Medical School]] in October 2008). In 1999, UCL merged with the [[UCL School of Slavonic and East European Studies|School of Slavonic and East European Studies]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=145289&sectioncode=26| title=Slavonic school to stay put after UCL merger|accessdate=23 June 2012|work=Times Higher Education| date=5 March 1999}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=147400&sectioncode=26| title=Language school keeps name in UCL merger|accessdate=23 June 2012| work=Times Higher Education| date=30 July 1999}}</ref> and the [[UCL Eastman Dental Institute|Eastman Dental Institute]].<ref name=guard221002/>\n\nThe [[UCL Jill Dando Institute|UCL Jill Dando Institute of Crime Science]], the first university department in the world devoted specifically to reducing crime, was founded in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=156312&sectioncode=26 | title=Director of Jill Dando Institute appointed|accessdate=21 June 2012|work=Times Higher Education| date=5 January 2001}}</ref>\n\nProposals for a merger between UCL and [[Imperial College London]] were announced in 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/4184027/Imperial-and-UCL-discuss-merger-to-be-world-player.html|title=Imperial and UCL discuss merger to be world player|date=15 October 2002|work=[[Daily Telegraph]]|author=Richard Alleyne}}</ref> The proposal provoked strong opposition from UCL teaching staff and students and the [[Association of University Teachers|AUT union]], which criticised \"the indecent haste and lack of consultation\", leading to its abandonment by the UCL provost Sir [[Derek Roberts]].<ref>{{cite web |author=Donald Macleod |title=UCL merger halted to stop \"damaging\" rows |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2002/nov/18/highereducation.universitymergers1 |date=18 November 2002 |accessdate=12 February 2012}}</ref> The blogs that helped to stop the merger are preserved, though some of the links are now broken: see David Colquhoun's blog<ref>{{cite web |author=David Colquhoun |title=Committee for UCL |work=DC's Improbable Science. 2002| url=http://www.homepages.ucl.ac.uk/~ucklucl/takeover.htm}}</ref> and the Save UCL blog,<ref>{{cite web |author=David Conway|title=Save UCL |work=2002| url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Pharmacology/dc-bits/saveucl/index.html}}</ref> which was run by David Conway, a postgraduate student in the department of Hebrew and Jewish studies.\n\nThe [[London Centre for Nanotechnology]] was established in 2003 as a joint venture between UCL and Imperial College London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/2698649.stm | title=London's little idea|accessdate=21 June 2012|work=BBC News| date=27 January 2003|first=Arran|last=Frood}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/2981480.stm | title=Nanotech under the microscope|accessdate=21 June 2012| work=BBC News| date=12 June 2003}}</ref> They were later joined by [[King's College London]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcl.ac.uk/news/kings-college-london-joins-powerhouse-of-nanotechnology-research|title=King's College London joins powerhouse of nanotechnology research|website=www.kcl.ac.uk}}</ref>\n\nSince 2003, when UCL professor [[David Latchman]] became master of the neighbouring [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck]], he has forged closer relations between these two University of London colleges, and personally maintains departments at both. Joint research centres include the UCL/Birkbeck Institute for Earth and Planetary Sciences, the UCL/Birkbeck/[[Institute of Education|IoE]] Centre for Educational Neuroscience, the UCL/Birkbeck Institute of Structural and Molecular Biology, and the Birkbeck-UCL Centre for Neuroimaging.\n\n===2005 to 2010===\n[[File:School of Slavonic and East European Studies.jpg|right|thumb|The [[UCL School of Slavonic and East European Studies]] building, which was opened in 2005]]\nIn 2005, UCL was finally granted its own taught and research degree awarding powers and all UCL students registered from 2007/08 qualified with UCL degrees. Also in 2005, UCL adopted a new corporate branding under which the name University College London was replaced by the [[Acronym and initialism|initialism]] UCL in all external communications.<ref name=Baty>{{cite news |last=Baty |first=Phil |title=Staff fury at '\u00a3600K' rebrand |newspaper=Times Higher Education Supplement |location=London |date=22 July 2005 }}</ref> In the same year, a major new \u00a3422 million building was opened for University College Hospital on [[Euston Road]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/2330133?Story_ID=E1_NPPDTPP|title=PFInancing new hospitals|accessdate=22 June 2012|work=The Economist|date=8 January 2004}}</ref> the [[UCL Ear Institute]] was established and a new building for the [[UCL School of Slavonic and East European Studies]] was opened.\n\nIn 2007, the UCL Cancer Institute was opened in the newly constructed Paul O'Gorman Building. In August 2008, UCL formed [[UCL Partners]], an [[academic health science centre]], with [[Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Trust]], [[Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]], [[Royal Free London NHS Foundation Trust]] and [[University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref name=uclpartners>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclpartners.com/about-us |title=About Us |accessdate=19 September 2010 |publisher=UCL Partners |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100910112932/http://www.uclpartners.com/about-us |archivedate=10 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2008, UCL established the [[UCL Australia|UCL School of Energy & Resources]] in [[Adelaide]], Australia, the first campus of a British university in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0805/08052901|title=UCL School of Energy & Resources, Australia, to be established'|date=29 May 2008|publisher=University College London|accessdate=1 August 2008}}</ref> The School was based in the historic [[Torrens Building]] in Victoria Square and its creation followed negotiations between UCL Vice Provost Michael Worton and South Australian Premier Mike Rann.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/higher/brave-new-territory-university-college-london-to-open-a-branch-in-australia-835571.html|title=Brave new territory: University College London to open a branch in|date=29 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, the Yale UCL Collaborative was established between UCL, [[UCL Partners]], [[Yale University]], [[Yale School of Medicine]] and [[Yale \u2013 New Haven Hospital]].<ref>[http://yale-ucl.org/index.aspx Home]. Yale UCL Collaborative (25 March 2013). Retrieved 17 July 2013.</ref> It is the largest collaboration in the history of either university, and its scope has subsequently been extended to the humanities and social sciences.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=416795|title=Research intelligence \u2013 Transatlantic affair of the heart takes off in big way|accessdate=1 January 2013|work=Times Higher Education|date=14 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2009/10/09/yale-joins-research-alliance/|title=Yale joins research alliance|accessdate=13 January 2013|newspaper=Yale Daily News|date=9 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n===2010 to 2015===\n[[File:Torrens Building, Victoria Square.jpg|thumb|upright|The Torrens Building in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], which housed the UCL School of Energy and Resources]]\nIn June 2011, the mining company [[BHP Billiton]] agreed to donate AU$10 million to UCL to fund the establishment of two energy institutes \u2013 the Energy Policy Institute, based in Adelaide, and the Institute for Sustainable Resources, based in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/bhp-signs-10m-deal-to-set-up-energy-research-facilities/story-e6frg8zx-1226073259419|title=BHP signs $10m deal to set up energy research facilities|accessdate=21 June 2012|work=The Australian|date=11 June 2011|first=Verity|last=Edwards}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, UCL announced plans for a \u00a3500 million investment in its main Bloomsbury campus over 10 years, as well as the establishment of a new 23-acre campus next to the Olympic Park in Stratford in the East End of London.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=418220|title=UCL has sights set on new East End home|accessdate=21 June 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=24 November 2011}}</ref> It revised its plans of expansion in East London and in December 2014 announced to build a campus (UCL East) covering 11 acres and provide up to 125,000m<sup>2</sup> of space on [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]].<ref>{{cite news|title=UCL to open huge tech and engineering campus|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-12/02/ucl-east-technology-engineering|accessdate=30 July 2015|agency=Wired|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709153836/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-12/02/ucl-east-technology-engineering|archive-date=9 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> UCL East will be part of plans to transform the Olympic Park into a cultural and innovation hub, where UCL will open its first school of design, a centre of experimental engineering and a museum of the future, along with a living space for students.<ref>{{cite news|title=London Olympicopolis culture hub plan gets \u00a3141m funding|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/dec/02/london-olympicopolis-culture-hub-stratford|accessdate=30 July 2015|agency=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe [[School of Pharmacy, University of London]] merged with UCL on 1 January 2012, becoming the UCL School of Pharmacy within the Faculty of Life Sciences.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=416145|title=School of Pharmacy to merge with UCL|accessdate=4 July 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=13 May 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/1112/111223-school-of-pharmacy-merged School of Pharmacy merges with UCL]. University College London (1 January 2012). Retrieved 17 July 2013.</ref> In May 2012, UCL, Imperial College London and the semiconductor company [[Intel]] announced the establishment of the Intel Collaborative Research Institute for Sustainable Connected Cities, a London-based institute for research into the future of cities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=420097|title=UCL and Imperial partner with Intel to create research institute|accessdate=22 June 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=26 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/9287696/Intel-London-to-be-city-of-the-future.html|title=Intel: London to be city of the future|accessdate=22 June 2012|work=The Telegraph|date=24 May 2012|first=Matt|last=Warman}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2012, UCL received criticism for advertising an unpaid research position; it subsequently withdrew the advert.<ref>Gibney, Elizabeth. (3 August 2012) [http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=420773&c=1 Advert for unpaid UCL research role withdrawn | General]. Times Higher Education. Retrieved 17 July 2013.</ref>\n\nUCL and the [[Institute of Education]] formed a strategic alliance in October 2012, including co-operation in teaching, research and the development of the London schools system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=421371|title=Bloomsbury institutions enter 'strategic partnership'|accessdate=5 October 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=2 October 2012}}</ref> In February 2014, the two institutions announced their intention to merge,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/ucl-set-to-merge-with-institute-of-education/2011121.article|title=UCL set to merge with Institute of Education|accessdate=3 March 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=5 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/institute-of-education-will-bring-healthy-dowry-to-ucl-marriage/2011259.article|title=Institute of Education will bring 'healthy dowry' to UCL marriage|accessdate=3 March 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=13 February 2014}}</ref> and the merger was completed in December 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/ucl-and-ioe-confirm-merger-date/2017200.article|title=UCL and IoE confirm merger date|accessdate=7 December 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=25 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/comment/opinion/ucl-and-ioe-merger-a-marriage-of-like-minds/2017298.article|title=UCL and IoE merger: a marriage of like minds?|accessdate=7 December 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=4 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, a new Department of Science, Technology, Engineering and Public Policy (STEaPP) was established within the Faculty of Engineering, one of several initiatives within the university to increase and reflect upon the links between research and public sector decision-making.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theengineer.co.uk/issues/policy-projects-special/decision-time/|title=Decision time|last=Stuart|first=Nathan|date=11 March 2013|work=|newspaper=The Engineer|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, it was announced that the Translation Studies Unit of [[Imperial College London]] would move to UCL, becoming part of the UCL School of European Languages, Culture and Society.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/imperial-translation-unit-moves-to-ucl/2007912.article|title=Imperial translation unit moves to UCL|accessdate=29 October 2013|work=Times Higher Education|date=2 October 2013}}</ref> In December 2013, it was announced that UCL and the academic publishing company [[Elsevier]] would collaborate to establish the UCL Big Data Institute.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/reed-elsevier-announces-knowledge-partnership-with-university-college-london-9013049.html|title=Reed Elsevier announces knowledge partnership with University College London|accessdate=25 December 2013|work=The Independent|date=18 December 2013}}</ref> In January 2015, it was announced that UCL had been selected by the UK government as one of the five founding members of the [[Alan Turing Institute]] (together with the universities of Cambridge, Edinburgh, Oxford and Warwick), an institute to be established at the British Library to promote the development and use of advanced mathematics, computer science, algorithms and [[big data]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge-University-announced-partner-new-Alan/story-25934928-detail/story.html|title=Cambridge University announced as partner in new Alan Turing Institute|accessdate=14 February 2015|work=Cambridge News|date=28 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150815054843/http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge-University-announced-partner-new-Alan/story-25934928-detail/story.html|archivedate=15 August 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.techworld.com/news/big-data/five-universities-named-by-government-lead-alan-turing-institute-3595950/|title=Five universities named by government to lead Alan Turing Institute|accessdate=14 February 2015|work=Tech World|date=28 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015 to present===\n[[File:Londres 097..jpg|thumb|upright|[[UCL School of Management]] is located at Level 38, [[One Canada Square]] in [[Canary Wharf]]]]\nIn August 2015, the Department of Management Science and Innovation was renamed as the [[UCL School of Management|School of Management]] and plans were announced to greatly expand UCL's activities in the area of business-related teaching and research.<ref>{{cite news|title=UCL launches School of Management in the heart of London|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/209580a0-3530-11e5-b05b-b01debd57852.html#axzz3hMQAgqyw|accessdate=30 July 2015|agency=Financial Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=University College London comes to Canary Wharf|url=http://www.wharf.co.uk/news/local-news/university-college-london-comes-canary-9753629|website=The Wharf|accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref> The school moved from the Bloomsbury campus to [[One Canada Square]] in Canary Wharf in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.ucl.ac.uk/site/tag/canary-wharf/|title= Head in the Clouds: SITE students visit UCL School of Management at Canary Wharf|author=RebeccaPayne|date=8 February 2017|publisher=UCL|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nUCL established the Institute of Advanced Studies (IAS) in 2015 to promote interdisciplinary research in humanities and social sciences. The prestigious annual [[Orwell Prize]] for political writing moved to the IAS in 2016.\n\nIn June 2016 it was reported in the ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' that as a result of administrative errors hundreds of students who studied at the UCL Eastman Dental Institute between 2005\u20136 and 2013\u201314 had been given the wrong marks, leading to an unknown number of students being attributed with the wrong qualifications and, in some cases, being failed when they should have passed their degrees.<ref name=THE7716>{{cite news |url=http://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/wrong-marks-for-dentistry-students-spark-investigation|title=Wrong marks for dentistry students spark investigation|accessdate=20 July 2016|work=Times Higher Education|date=7 July 2016|first=Jack|last=Grove}}</ref> A report by UCL's Academic Committee Review Panel noted that, according to the Institute's own review findings, senior members of UCL staff had been aware of issues affecting students' results but had not taken action to address them.<ref name=UCLAC1213>{{cite web|url=http://www.whatdotheyknow.com/request/349584/response/864585/attach/4/AC%20Review%20Panel%20MSc%20RDP%20Report%202013%2014%204.pdf|title=Academic Committee Review Panel \u2013 MSc Restorative Dental Practice|accessdate=11 September 2016|publisher=University College London|date=2013}}</ref> The Review Panel concluded that there had been an apparent lack of ownership of these matters amongst the Institute's senior staff.<ref name= UCLAC1213/>\n\nIn December 2016 it was announced that UCL would be the hub institution for a new \u00a3250 million national dementia research institute, to be funded with \u00a3150 million from the [[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)|Medical Research Council]] and \u00a350 million each from [[Alzheimer's Research UK]] and the [[Alzheimer's Society]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/e7086604-c142-11e6-9bca-2b93a6856354|title=UCL to host \u00a3250m national dementia research institute|accessdate=26 December 2016|work=Financial Times|date=13 December 2016|first=|last=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/dec/18/britain-global-science-race-to-treat-dementia-250m-research-project|title=How Britain plans to lead the global science race to treat dementia|accessdate=26 December 2016|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2016|first=|last=}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017 it was reported that staff morale was at \"an all time low\", with 68% of members of the academic board who responded to a survey disagreeing with the statement \"UCL is well managed\" and 86% with \"the teaching facilities are adequate for the number of students\". Michael Arthur, the Provost and President, linked the results to the \"major change programme\" at UCL. He admitted that facilities were under pressure following growth over the past decade, but said that the issues were being addressed through the development of UCL East and rental of other additional space.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2017/may/04/ucl-staff-morale-at-all-time-low-because-of-management-poll-finds-academic-business-university|title=UCL staff morale at all-time low because of management, poll finds|date=4 May 2017|author=Sally Weale|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2017 UCL's council voted to apply for university status while remaining part of the University of London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/staff/staff-news/november-2017/15112017-town-hall-consultations|title=Town hall consultations on UCL's Charter and Statutes|publisher=UCL|date=15 November 2017|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> UCL's application to become a university is subject to Parliament passing a bill to amend the statutes of the University of London, which is, as of July 2018, held up by procedural issues in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/bill-paves-way-london-colleges-gain-university-status|title=Bill paves way for London colleges to gain university status|date=18 April 2018|author=John Morgan|work=[[Times Higher Education]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wonkhe.com/blogs/the-strange-tale-of-the-university-of-london-bill/|title=The strange tale of the University of London Bill|author=David Kernohan|date=26 July 2018|publisher=WONKHE|accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref> The bill received royal assent on 20 December 2018, allowing UCL's application for university status to proceed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://services.parliament.uk/Bills/2017-19/universityoflondon/stages.html|title=Bill stages \u2014 University of London Act 2018|website=parliament.uk|accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe UCL Adelaide satellite campus closed in December 2017, with academic staff and student transferring to the [[University of South Australia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.engineering.ucl.ac.uk/news/move-ucl-engineering-australia-unisa-mawson-lakes-campus/|title=Move of UCL Engineering in Australia to UniSA Mawson Lakes campus|date=17 January 2018| accessdate=2 September 2018|publisher=UCL}}</ref> {{as of|2019}} UniSA and UCL are offering a joint masters qualification in Science in Data Science (international).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unisa.edu.au/IT-Engineering-and-the-Environment/Programs-and-Courses/UCL-UniSA-Partnership/|website=University of South Australia|title=New UniSA and UCL postgraduate partnership|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, UCL opened ''UCL at Here East'', at the Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park, offering courses jointly between the [[The Bartlett|Bartlett Faculty of the Built Environment]] and the [[UCL Faculty of Engineering Sciences|Faculty of Engineering Sciences]].<ref name=\"Here East\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/bartlett/news/2018/feb/high-tech-campus-here-east-marks-new-chapter-bartlett-and-engineering-sciences-ucl|title=High-tech campus at Here East marks new chapter for The Bartlett and Engineering Sciences at UCL|publisher=UCL|date=28 February 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> The campus offers a variety of undergraduate and postgraduate master's degrees,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/here-east/programmes-and-short-courses|title=Programmes and short courses|website=UCL at Here East|publisher=UCL|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> with the first undergraduate students, on a new Engineering and Architectural Design [[MEng]], starting in September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/engineering-architectural-design-meng/2018|title=Engineering and Architectural Design MEng|work=UCL Undergraduate Prospectus|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> It was announced in August 2018 that a \u00a3215 million contract for construction of the largest building in the ''UCL East'' development, Marshgate 1, had been awarded to [[Mace (construction company)|Mace]], with building to begin in 2019 and be completed by 2022.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theconstructionindex.co.uk/news/view/mace-wins-215m-ucl-east-campus-building|title=Mace wins \u00a3215m UCL East campus building|date=31 August 2018|work=The Construction Index}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 UCL disciplined an IT administrator who was also the [[University and College Union]] (UCU) branch secretary for refusing to take down an unmoderated staff mailing list. An employment tribunal subsequently ruled that he was engaged in union activities and thus this disciplinary action was unlawful. {{As of|June 2019}} UCL is appealing this ruling and the UCU congress has declared this to be a \"dispute of national significance\".<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Times Higher Education]]|date=14 June 2019|author= Nick Mayo|title=Support for UCL worker 'disciplined over trade union activities'|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/support-ucl-worker-disciplined-over-trade-union-activities}}</ref>\n\n==Campus and locations==\n\n===Bloomsbury===\n{{See also|Filming at University College London}}\n[[File:University College London -quadrant-11Sept2006 (1).jpg|thumb|The Wilkins Building and main quadrangle]]\n[[File:Rockefeller Building, UCL.jpg|thumb|right|The Rockefeller Building on University Street, one of UCL's largest premises]]\nUCL is primarily based in the [[Bloomsbury]] area of the [[London Borough of Camden]], in [[Central London]]. The main campus is located around [[Gower Street (London)|Gower Street]] and includes the biology, chemistry, economics, engineering, geography, history, languages, mathematics, management, philosophy and physics departments, the preclinical facilities of the [[UCL Medical School]], the [[London Centre for Nanotechnology]], the [[Slade School of Fine Art]], the [[UCL Union]], the main UCL Library, the UCL Science Library, the [[The UCL Bloomsbury|Bloomsbury Theatre]], the [[Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology]], the [[Grant Museum of Zoology]] and the affiliated [[University College Hospital]]. Close by in Bloomsbury are the UCL Cancer Institute, the [[the Bartlett|UCL Faculty of the Built Environment (The Bartlett)]], the [[UCL Faculty of Laws]], the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology]], the [[UCL Institute of Education]], the [[UCL School of Pharmacy]], the UCL School of Public Policy and the [[UCL School of Slavonic and East European Studies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/location/maps |title=Campus location maps, University College London |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080527180840/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/location/maps |archivedate=27 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe area around [[Queen Square, London|Queen Square]] in Bloomsbury, close by to the main campus, is a hub for brain-related research and healthcare, with the [[UCL Institute of Cognitive Neuroscience]] and [[UCL Institute of Neurology]] located in the area along with the affiliated [[National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery]]. The [[UCL Great Ormond Street Institute of Child Health]] and the affiliated [[Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children]] are located adjacently, forming a hub for paediatric research and healthcare. The [[UCL Ear Institute]], the [[UCL Eastman Dental Institute]] and the affiliated [[Royal National Throat, Nose and Ear Hospital]] and [[Eastman Dental Hospital]] are located nearby in east Bloomsbury along [[Gray's Inn Road]] and form a hub for research and healthcare in audiology and dentistry respectively.\n\nNotable UCL buildings in Bloomsbury include the [[UCL Main Building]], including the [[(Octagon)-|Octagon]], Quad, Cloisters and the Wilkins building designed by [[William Wilkins (architect)|William Wilkins]]; the Cruciform Building, Gower Street (a red, cross-shaped building previously home to University College Hospital); and the Rockefeller Building, University Street, home to the original University College Hospital Medical School and named after the American oil magnate [[John D. Rockefeller]] after support from the [[Rockefeller Foundation]] in the 1920s. Due to its position within London and the historical nature of its buildings, including most notably the UCL Main Building and Quad, UCL has been used as a location for a number of film and television productions, including ''[[Doctor in the House]]'' (1954), ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' (2000), ''[[The Mummy Returns]]'' (2001), ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' (2008) and ''[[Inception]]'' (2010).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://filmlondon.org.uk/news/2010/july/nolans_mind_games|title=Nolan's Mind Games|accessdate=11 August 2010|publisher=Film London| date=14 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nA number of important institutions are based near to the main campus, including the [[British Library]], the [[British Medical Association]], the [[British Museum]], [[Cancer Research UK]], [[Gray's Inn]], the [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]], [[RADA]], the [[Royal Academy of Art]], the [[Royal Institution]] and the [[Wellcome Trust]]. Many University of London schools and institutes are also close by, including [[Birkbeck, University of London]], [[London Business School]], the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]], the [[Royal Veterinary College]], the [[School of Advanced Study]], the [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] and the [[Senate House (University of London)|Senate House Library]]. The nearest [[London Underground]] station is [[Euston Square tube station|Euston Square]], with [[Goodge Street tube station|Goodge Street]], [[Russell Square tube station|Russell Square]], [[Tottenham Court Road tube station|Tottenham Court Road]] and [[Warren Street tube station|Warren Street]] all nearby. The mainline railway stations at [[Euston railway station|Euston]], [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]] and [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras]] are all within walking distance.\n\n===UCL East===\nIn 2014 it was announced that UCL would be building an additional campus at the [[Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park]], referred to as UCL East, as part of the development of the so-called ''Olympicopolis'' site at the southern edge of the park. UCL master planners were appointed in spring 2015, and the first University building was, at that time, estimated to be completed in time for academic year 2019/20.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://queenelizabetholympicpark.co.uk/the-park/attractions/olympicopolis |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-01-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205113543/http://queenelizabetholympicpark.co.uk/the-park/attractions/olympicopolis |archivedate=5 February 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed in June 2016 that the UCL East expansion could see the university grow to 60,000 students. The proposed rate of growth was reported to be causing concern, with calls for it to be slowed down to ensure the university could meet financial stability targets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/university-college-london-ucl-floats-plan-to-expand-to-sixty-thousand-students|title=UCL floats plan to expand to 60,000 students|date=23 June 2016|author=David Matthews|newspaper=[[Times Higher Education]]}}</ref>\n\nOutline planning permission for UCL East was submitted in May 2017 by the [[London Legacy Development Corporation]] and UCL, and granted in March 2018. Construction of the first phase of buildings is (as of March 2018)  expected to begin in 2019 with the first building (Pool Street West) expected to be completed for the start of the 2021 academic year and the second building (Marshgate 1) opening in phases from September 2022. As of March 2018, phase 1 is intended to have 50,000 m{{sup|2}} of space, and to house 4,000 extra students and 260 extra academic staff, while the entire UCL East campus, when completed, is expected to have 180,000 m{{sup|2}} of space, 40% of the size of UCL's central London campus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/ucl-east/news-library/Mayor_of_London_grants_outline_planning_permission_for_UCL_East|title=Mayor of London grants outline planning permission for UCL East|date=28 March 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018|publisher=UCL}}</ref> The outline planning permission is for up to 190,800 m{{sup|2}} of space with up to 160,060 m{{sup|2}} of academic development and research space (including up to 16,000 m{{sup|2}} of commercial research space), up to 50,880 m{{sup|2}} of student accommodation, and up to 4,240 m{{sup|2}} of retail space.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planningregister.londonlegacy.co.uk/swift/apas/run/WPHAPPDETAIL.DisplayUrl?theApnID=17/00235/OUT|title=Web APAS \u2013 Planning Application \u2013 Details|publisher=London Legacy Development Corporation|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> According to the planning documents, construction of phase 2 (Pool Street East and Marshfield 2, 3 and 4) is expected to begin in 2030 and be completed by 2034, and the whole project will support 2,337 academic staff and 11,169 students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planningregister.londonlegacy.co.uk/swift/apas/run/WCHDISPLAYMEDIA.showImage?theSeqNo=118307&theApnkey=6925&theModule=1|title=UCL East Site- Non-Technical Summary|publisher=London Legacy Development Corporation|accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref> The campus will include residences for up to 1,800 students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planningregister.londonlegacy.co.uk/swift/apas/run/WCHDISPLAYMEDIA.showImage?theSeqNo=118300&theApnkey=6925&theModule=1|title=UCL East Site- Planning Statement|publisher=London Legacy Development Corporation|accessdate=2 September 2018|page=15}}</ref> In June 2018, UCL revealed that the UK Government would be providing \u00a3100 million of funding for UCL East as part of its \u00a3151 million contribution to the \u00a31.1 billion redevelopment of the Olympic Park as a cultural and education district to be known as the East Bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0618/050618-100-million-secured-for-UCL-East-East-Bank|title=\u00a3100m secured for UCL East as part of East Bank|date=5 June 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018|publisher=UCL}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-44374255|title=London Olympic Park \u00a31.1bn plan unveiled|date=5 June 2018|accessdate=2 September 2018|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2018 UCL is offering degree courses at the Olympic Park, based at ''UCL at Here East'' at the northern end of the East Bank development.<ref name=\"Here East\"/>\n\n===Other sites===\nElsewhere in Central London are the [[UCL Institute of Ophthalmology]] (based in [[Clerkenwell]]), the Windeyer Institute (based in [[Fitzrovia]]), the UCL Institute of Orthopedics and Musculoskeletal Science (based in [[Stanmore]]), [[Royal Free Hospital|The Royal Free Hospital]] and the [[Whittington Hospital]] campuses of the UCL Medical School, and a number of other teaching hospitals. The [[UCL School of Management]] is located at Level 38, [[One Canada Square]] in [[Canary Wharf]], London. The [[Mullard Space Science Laboratory|Department of Space and Climate Physics (Mullard Space Science Laboratory)]] is based in [[Holmbury St Mary]], Surrey, and there is a UCL campus in Doha, Qatar specialised in archaeology, conservation, museum and gallery practice, and library and information studies that will close in 2020 at the end of UCL's contact with the [[Qatar Foundation]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2001/jan/10/voluntarysector.publicsectorcareers1| title=Energy boost|accessdate=14 October 2010|work=Times Higher Education| date=16 April 2009|location=London|first=John|last=Cunningham}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://thedailyq.org/5900/top-news-stories/ucl-qatar-to-leave-education-city-by-2020/|title=UCL Qatar to leave Education City by 2020|author=Sara Sarwar|date=27 November 2016|work=The Daily Q}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://cheesegratermagazine.org/2017/10/23/sheikh-off-inside-ucls-decision-leave-gulf/|title=Sheikh It Off: Inside UCL's Decision To Leave Qatar|date=23 October 2017|author=Weronika Strzy\u017cy\u0144ska|work=Cheese Grater Magazine}}</ref> From 2010 to 2015 UCL ran a University Preparatory Certificate course at Nazarbayev University in [[Nur-Sultan]], Kazakhstan,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/higher/welcome-to-the-new-frontier-ndash-central-asia-1737516.html|title=Welcome to the new frontier \u2013 Central Asia|accessdate=26 October 2010|work=The Independent |location=London |date=9 July 2009}}</ref> and had a [[UCL Australia|campus in Adelaide, Australia]] from 2010 to 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/281c5ab8-ff09-11e4-84b2-00144feabdc0|title=University College London eyes global closures over cost concerns|work=[[Financial Times]]|author=Helen Warrell|date=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation and administration==\n\n===Governance===\nAlthough UCL is a constituent college of the federal University of London, in most ways it is comparable with free-standing, self-governing and independently funded universities, and it awards its own degrees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/current-students/examinations/degree-awarding/faq/ |title=Degree Awarding, University College London |accessdate=2008-02-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812190236/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/current-students/examinations/degree-awarding/faq/ |archivedate=12 August 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nUCL's governing body is the council, which oversees the management and administration of UCL and the conduct of its affairs, subject to the advice of the academic board on matters of academic policy, and approves UCL's long-term plans.<ref name=governance>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/ras/acs/governance/overview|title=Governance overview|accessdate=9 December 2012|publisher=University College London}}</ref> It delegates authority to the provost, as chief executive, for the academic, corporate, financial, estate and human resources management of UCL. The Council normally meets six times each year. The Council comprises 20 members, of whom 11 are members external to UCL; seven are UCL academic staff, including the provost, three UCL professors and three non-professorial staff; and two are UCL students. The chair is appointed by council for a term not normally exceeding five years. The chair is ''ex officio'' chair of the honorary degrees and fellowships committee, nominations committee and remuneration and strategy committee.<ref name=governance/> The current chair of the council is Dame DeAnne Julius.\n\nUCL's principal academic and administrative officer is the president and provost, who is also UCL's designated principal officer for the purposes of the financial memorandum with the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE).<ref name=governance/> The provost is appointed by council after consultation with the academic board, is responsible to the council, and works closely with its members, and especially with the chair of council. The current and tenth provost and president of UCL is [[Michael Arthur (academic)|Michael Arthur]], who replaced Sir [[Malcolm Grant]] in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/provost/ |title=UCL Provost and President |publisher=University College London |accessdate=15 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nVice-provosts are appointed by the provost, through the council, to assist and advise the provost as required. The vice-provosts are members of the provost's senior management team. There are presently six vice-provosts (for education, enterprise, health, international, research, and operations).<ref name=governance/>\n\nThe deans of UCL's faculties are appointed by the council and, together with the vice-provosts and the director of finance and business affairs, form the members of the provost's senior management team. The deans' principal duties include advising the provost and vice-provosts on academic strategy, staffing matters and resources for academic departments within their faculty; overseeing curricula and programme management at faculty level; liaising with faculty tutors on undergraduate admissions and student academic matters; overseeing examination matters at faculty level; and co-ordinating faculty views on matters relating to education and information support.<ref name=governance/>\n\n====List of provosts====\n* Sir [[Gregory Foster]] (1906\u20131929)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* [[Allen Mawer|Sir Allen Mawer]] (1930\u20131942)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* [[David Randall Pye|David Pye]]<!-- Note that he wasn't knighted until after his provostship. --> (1943\u20131951)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* Sir [[Ifor Evans, Baron Evans of Hungershall|Ifor Evans]]<!-- Note that he wasn't raised to the peerage until after his provostship. --> (1951\u20131966)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* [[Noel Annan, Baron Annan|Lord Annan]] (1966\u20131978)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* Sir [[James Lighthill]] (1979\u20131989)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* Sir [[Derek Roberts]] (1989\u20131999;<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/> 2002\u20132003)\n* Sir [[Christopher Llewellyn Smith]] (1999\u20132002)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* Sir [[Malcolm Grant]] (2003\u20132013)<ref name=\"Former Provosts\"/>\n* [[Michael Arthur (physician)|Michael Arthur]] (2013\u2013present)\n\n===Faculties and departments===\n[[File:UCL Drayton House.jpg|thumb|right|Drayton House, which houses the Faculty of Economics]]\n[[File:UCL School of Pharmacy.JPG|thumb|right|The UCL School of Pharmacy building]]\n[[File:Ucl engineering.jpg|thumb|The Faculty of Engineering Sciences building]]\n[[File:UCL Bedford Way.jpg|thumb|right|The Bedford Way building, home to the UCL Institute of Education and the Departments of Geography, Psychology and Language]]\n\n{{See also|Category:Departments of University College London}}\nUCL's research and teaching is organised within a network of faculties and academic departments. Faculties and academic departments are formally established by the UCL Council, the governing body of UCL, on the advice of the Academic Board, which is UCL's senior academic authority. UCL is a comprehensive university with teaching and research across the full range of the arts, humanities, social sciences, physical, biological and medical sciences, engineering and the built environment, although it does not currently have a veterinary, music, drama or nursing school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/white-paper/comprehensive-university|title=UCL Council White Paper 2011\u20132021 \u2013 A comprehensive university|publisher=UCL|accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> UCL is currently organised into the following 11 constituent faculties:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/departments/faculties|title=UCL Faculties|accessdate=19 September 2011|publisher=University College London}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n|-  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"\n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| '''Faculty'''<ref name=annrev2012>{{cite web|url=http://issuu.com/uclcomms/docs/annual-review-2012?e=2187058/1966052|title=UCL Annual Review 2012|publisher=UCL|accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref>\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| '''Academic and research staff'''<br />(as at 30 April 2012)<ref name=annrev2012/>\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| '''Undergraduate students'''<br />(2011/12)<ref name=annrev2012/>\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| '''Postgraduate students'''<br />(2011/12)<ref name=annrev2012/>\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[UCL Faculty of Arts and Humanities]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 328\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 2,157\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,075\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| UCL Faculty of Brain Sciences\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,249\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 722\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,457\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[The Bartlett|UCL Faculty of the Built Environment (The Bartlett)]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 355\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 570\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,241\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[UCL Faculty of Engineering Sciences]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 667\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 2,049\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,642\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[UCL Faculty of Laws]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 137\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 528\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 458\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[UCL Faculty of Life Sciences]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 798\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,183\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 486\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[UCL Faculty of Mathematical and Physical Sciences]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 754\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 2,187\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 677\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| UCL Faculty of Medical Sciences\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,257\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,773\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,342\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| UCL Faculty of Population Health Sciences\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,092\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 64\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 815\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[UCL Faculty of Social and Historical Sciences]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 621\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 2,539\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| 1,894\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\" \n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| [[UCL Institute of Education]]\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| n/a\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| n/a\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| n/a\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|  style=\"width:350px; \"| ''Total''\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| ''5,277 (ex. Institute of Education)''\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| ''13,772 (ex. Institute of Education)''\n|  style=\"width:120px; \"| ''11,087 (ex. Institute of Education)''\n|}\nTo facilitate greater interdisciplinary interaction in research and teaching UCL also has four strategic faculty groupings:\n\n*the UCL School of Life and Medical Sciences (comprising the Faculties of Brain Sciences, Life Sciences, Medical Sciences and Population Health Sciences);\n*the UCL School of the Built Environment, Engineering and Mathematical and Physical Sciences (comprising the UCL Faculty of the Built Environment, UCL Faculty of Engineering Sciences and UCL Faculty of Mathematical & Physical Sciences);\n*the UCL Faculty of Arts & Humanities, UCL Faculty of Laws, UCL Faculty of Social & Historical Sciences and the UCL School of Slavonic & East European Studies.\n*the UCL Institute of Education\n\n===Finances===\nIn the financial year ended 31 July 2016, UCL had a total income (excluding share of joint ventures) of \u00a31.36&nbsp;billion (2014/15 \u2013 \u00a31.26&nbsp;billion) and a total expenditure of \u00a31.23&nbsp;billion (2014/15 \u2013 \u00a31.22&nbsp;billion).<ref name=finstat/> Key sources of income included \u00a3530.4&nbsp;million from research grants and contracts (2014/15 \u2013 \u00a3427.3&nbsp;million), \u00a3421.1&nbsp;million from tuition fees and education contracts (2014/15 \u2013 \u00a3364.2&nbsp;million), \u00a3192.1&nbsp;million from funding body grants (2014/15 \u2013 \u00a3195.2&nbsp;million) and \u00a325.1&nbsp;million from donations and endowments (2014/15 \u2013 \u00a320.3&nbsp;million).<ref name=finstat/> During the 2015/16 financial year UCL had a capital expenditure of \u00a3146.6&nbsp;million (2014/15 \u2013 \u00a3149.3&nbsp;million).<ref name=finstat/> At year end UCL had endowments of \u00a3100.9&nbsp;million (31 July 2015 \u2013 \u00a3104.1&nbsp;million) and total net assets of \u00a31.19&nbsp;billion (31 July 2015 \u2013 \u00a31.07&nbsp;million).<ref name=finstat/><ref group=\"note\">The Institute of Education (IOE) merged with UCL in December 2014. In the year ended 31 July 2013 the IOE had a total income of \u00a371.42 million and total expenditure of \u00a369.97 million. The IOE had total net assets of \u00a3105.17 million at 31 July 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2014/15, UCL had the third-highest total income of any British university (after the University of Cambridge and the University of Oxford), and the third-highest income from research grants and contracts (after the University of Oxford and Imperial College London).<ref name=thefindat>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/sites/default/files/breaking_news_files/university-financial-health-check-2016-uk-institutions-finances-2014-2015.pdf|title=Times Higher Education university financial health check 2016|accessdate=7 June 2016|work=Times Higher Education|date=2 June 2016}}</ref> For the 2015/16 academic year, UCL was allocated a total of \u00a3171.37 million for teaching and research from the [[Higher Education Funding Council for England]] (HEFCE), the highest amount allocated to any English university, of which \u00a339.76 million is for teaching and \u00a3131.61 million is for research.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/winners-and-losers-in-hefce-funding-allocations/2019306.article|title=Winners and losers in Hefce funding allocations|accessdate=29 March 2015|work=Times Higher Education|date=26 March 2015}}</ref> According to a survey published by the Sutton Trust, UCL had the [[List of UK universities by endowment|eighth-largest endowment of any British university]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/oxbridge-uplift-disguises-a-drop-in-the-size-of-average-uk-endowment/2014158.article|title=Oxbridge uplift disguises a drop in the size of average UK endowment|accessdate=13 July 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=26 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nUCL launched a 10-year, \u00a3300 million fundraising appeal in October 2004, at the time the largest appeal target set by a university in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/3718172.stm|title=University launches \u00a3300m appeal|accessdate=14 August 2012|work=BBC News| date=5 October 2004}}</ref> UCL launched a new \u00a3600 million fundraising campaign in September 2016 titled ''\"It's All Academic \u2013 The Campaign for UCL\"''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/university-college-london-bids-to-raise-600-million-in-largest-ever-fundraising-drive-a3341076.html|title=University College London bids to raise \u00a3600 million in largest ever fundraising drive|accessdate=16 September 2016|newspaper=Evening Standard| date=9 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0916/150916-Campaign/|title=UCL launches \u00a3600m philanthropy campaign |publisher=University College London|accessdate=16 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, UCL signed a \u00a3280 million 30-year loan with the [[European Investment Bank]], the largest loan ever borrowed by a UK university and largest ever loan by the EIB to a university.<ref name=FT28416>{{cite news|url=https://next.ft.com/content/ee759cbe-0c6f-11e6-b0f1-61f222853ff3|title=UCL to borrow record \u00a3280m to expand|accessdate=28 April 2016|newspaper=Financial Times| date=28 April 2016}}</ref><ref name=eibloan>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0416/280416-european-investment-bank|title=UCL agrees \u00a3280m European Investment Bank loan for campus developments|publisher=University College London|accessdate=28 April 2016}}</ref> The monies are to be used to fund a \u00a31.25 billion capital expenditure programme in Bloomsbury and Stratford.<ref name=FT28416/><ref name=eibloan/> Some UCL academics oppose the expansion plans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/bb683c1a-387e-11e6-a780-b48ed7b6126f|title=Subscribe to read|website=www.ft.com|access-date=2016-12-03}}</ref>\n\n===Terms===\nThe UCL academic year is divided into three terms.<ref name=terms>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/staff/term-dates|title=Term Dates: 2013\u20132014|accessdate=25 December 2013|publisher=University College London}}</ref> For most departments except the Medical School, Term One runs from late September to mid December, Term Two from mid January to late March, and Term Three from late April to mid June.<ref name=terms/> Certain departments operate reading weeks in early November and mid February.<ref name=terms/>\n\n===Logo, arms and colours===\nWhereas most universities primarily use their logo on mundane documents but their coat of arms on official documents such as degree certificates, UCL exclusively uses its logo. The present logo was adopted as part of a rebranding exercise in August 2005.<ref name=Baty/> Prior to that date, a different logo was used, in which the letters UCL were incorporated into a stylised representation of the Wilkins Building [[portico]].\n\nUCL formerly made some use of a pseudo-heraldic \"coat of arms\" depicting a raised bent arm dressed in armour holding a green upturned open wreath.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/guyfwoodward/950670333/ |title=logobig on Flickr \u2013 Photo Sharing! |publisher=Flickr.com |date=30 July 2007 |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> A version of this badge (not on a shield) appears to have been used by [[University College London Union|UCL Union]] from shortly after its foundation in 1893.<ref>{{cite book |first1=Negley |last1=Harte |first2=John |last2=North |title=The World of UCL 1828\u20132004 |edition=3rd |publisher=UCL Press |place=London |year=2004 |isbn=978-1-84472-068-2 |page=154 }}</ref> However, the arms have never been the subject of an official [[grant of arms]], and depart from several of the rules and conventions of [[heraldry]]. They are no longer formally used by the college, although they are still occasionally seen in unofficial contexts, or used in modified form by sports teams and societies. The [[blazon]] of the arms might be rendered as: ''Purpure, on a wreath of the colours Argent and Blue Celeste, an arm in armour embowed Argent holding an upturned wreath of laurel Vert, beneath which two branches of laurel Or crossed at the nombril and bound with a bowed cord Or, beneath the nombril a motto of Blue Celeste upon which Cuncti adsint meritaeque expectent praemia palmae.'' The motto is a quotation from [[Virgil]]'s ''[[Aeneid]]'', and translates into English as \"Let all come who by merit deserve the most reward\".<ref>{{citation |title=The Aeneid |author=Virgil |editor=Storr, Francis |language=Latin |url=https://archive.org/details/theaeneid00virguoft}}</ref>\n\nUCL's traditional sporting and academic colours of purple [rgb(96,40,153)] and light blue [rgb(102,204,255)] are derived from the arms.\n<gallery>\nFile:UCL old logo.jpg|Former UCL logo, in use until 2005\nFile:UCL Crest.svg|UCL \"coat of arms\"\nFile:UCL Scarf Colours.jpg|UCL scarf colours\n</gallery>\n\n===Secularism===\nFrom its foundation the college was deliberately secular; the initial justification for this was that it would enable students of different Christian traditions (specifically [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholics]], [[Anglicanism|Anglicans]] and [[Protestantism|Protestants]]) to study alongside each other without conflict.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7cZLAAAAcAAJ&pg=PR3|pages=iii\u2013v|title=London University Calendar|date=1832|publisher=UCL}}</ref> UCL has retained this strict secular position and, unlike most other UK universities, has no specific religious prayer rooms. There is, however, a Christian chaplain (who also serves as interfaith advisor) and there is no restriction on religious groups among students. A \"quiet contemplation room\" also allows prayer for staff and students of all faiths.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/students/support-and-wellbeing/specialist-information-and-support/religion-and-faith|title=Religion and faith|publisher=UCL|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.london.anglican.org/articles/university-college-london-welcomes-new-chaplain-and-inter-faith-adviser/|title=University College London welcomes new chaplain and Inter Faith Adviser|publisher=[[Diocese of London]]|accessdate=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Memberships, affiliations and partnerships===\n[[File:University College Hospital - New Building - London - 020504.jpg|thumb|The main building of [[University College Hospital]]]]\nUCL is a constituent college of the federal University of London, of which it was one of the two founding members in 1836 (the other being [[King's College London]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london.ac.uk/history.html|title=A brief history|accessdate=7 August 2014|publisher=University of London}}</ref>\n\nUCL is a founding member of the [[Russell Group]], an association of 24 British research universities established in 1994,<ref name=the91106>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=206624&sectioncode=26|title=Queen's gets key to Russell club door|accessdate=7 August 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=9 November 2006}}</ref> and of the [[G5 (universities)|G5]] lobbying group, which it established in early 2004 with the universities of Cambridge and Oxford, [[Imperial College London]] and the [[London School of Economics]].<ref name=THE1>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=186508&sectioncode=26|title=Super elite in secret bid for cash boost|magazine=Times Higher Education|date=6 February 2004|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/education/student/news/article1015256.ece|title=Universities warned they may face price-fixing fines on fees|newspaper=The Times|date=9 February 2004|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> UCL is regarded as forming part of the \u2018[[Golden triangle (universities)|golden triangle]]\u2019, an unofficial term for a set of leading universities located in the southern English cities of Cambridge, London and Oxford<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/naturejobs/2005/050707/full/nj7047-144a.html| title=Golden opportunities|journal=Nature| date=6 July 2005}}: \"No longer rivals, Oxford, Cambridge and London are now working towards a common goal \u2014 ensuring the 'golden triangle' becomes a global science hub.\"</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=94844&sectioncode=26 |title=Oxbridge windfall |magazine=Times Higher Education |date=4 August 1995}}: \"A large amount of the cash awarded to humanities postgraduates still goes to the \"Golden Triangle\" of Oxford, Cambridge and London, British Academy figures reveal.\"</ref><ref>Kershaw, Alison. [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/uk-universities-slip-in-rankings-8196772.html \"UK universities slip in rankings\"], ''The Independent'', 4 October 2012: \"Rankings editor Phil Baty said: \"Outside the golden triangle of London, Oxford and Cambridge, England's world-class universities face a collapse into global mediocrity.\"</ref> including the universities of Cambridge and Oxford, Imperial College London, King's College London and the London School of Economics.\n\nUCL has been a member of the [[League of European Research Universities]] since January 2006. It is currently one of five British members (the others being the universities of Cambridge, Edinburgh and Oxford and Imperial College London).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/media/library/LERU|title=UCL joins League of European Research Universities|accessdate=9 August 2014|publisher= University College London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leru.org/index.php/public/about-leru/members/|title=LERU Members|accessdate=9 August 2014|publisher=League of European Research Universities}}</ref> Other international groupings that UCL is a member of include the [[Association of Commonwealth Universities]], the [[European University Association]] and the [[Universities Research Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/images/Uni-Lon.pdf |title=The future of the University of London: a discussion paper from the Provost of UCL|author1= Malcolm Grant, President |author2=Provost, UCL |lastauthoramp=yes |date=March 2005 |accessdate=7 August 2014|pages=23}}</ref> UCL has a major collaboration with [[Yale University]], the Yale UCL Collaborative, and has hundreds of other research and teaching partnerships, including around 150 research links and 130 student-exchange partnerships with European universities.<ref name= \"fulbright.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fulbright.org.uk/about/partner-with-us/fulbright-partners/university-college-london|title=University College London (UCL)|publisher=Fulbright Commission|accessdate=4 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nUCL has been a member of the [[SES (universities)|SES]] engineering and physical sciences research alliance since May 2013, which it formed with the universities of Cambridge, Oxford and Southampton and Imperial College London (King's College London subsequently joined in 2016).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/research-heavyweights-deny-ganging-up/2003702.article|title=Research heavyweights deny 'ganging up'|work=Times Higher Education|date=9 May 2013|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> UCL is a member of the [[Thomas Young Centre]], an alliance of London research groups working on the theory and simulation of materials; the other members are Imperial College London, King's College London and Queen Mary University of London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thomasyoungcentre.org/about-tyc/|title=About the Thomas Young Centre| publisher=Thomas Young Centre|date=|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> UCL is one of the five founding members of the [[Alan Turing Institute]], the UK's national institute for data sciences (together with the universities of Cambridge, Edinburgh, Oxford and Warwick).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://turing.ac.uk/partners/|title=Partners|publisher=Alan Turing Institute|date=|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref> It also operates the [[London Centre for Nanotechnology]], a multidisciplinary research centre in physical and biomedical nanotechnology, in partnership with Imperial College London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london-nano.com/about|title=About|publisher=London Centre for Nanotechnology|date=|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Francis Crick Institute building, Oct 2015.jpg|thumb|The [[Francis Crick Institute]] building]]\nUCL has a close partnership with [[University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]]; the Trust's hospitals are teaching sites for the [[UCL Medical School]], UCL and the Trust are joint partners in the [[UCLH/UCL Biomedical Research Centre]] and the [[National Centre for Sport and Exercise Medicine|Institute of Sport, Exercise and Health]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Sports injury institute costing \u00a310m opens in boost to the Olympic legacy|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/sports-injury-institute-costing-10m-opens-in-boost-to-the-olympic-legacy-8670875.html|accessdate=4 October 2016|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=24 June 2013}}</ref> and both are members of the [[UCL Partners]] [[academic health science centre]].<ref name=\"Health Service Journal\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclh.nhs.uk/aboutus/wwd/Pages/Home.aspx|title=What we do|publisher=University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust|date=|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclhospitals.brc.nihr.ac.uk/about-us/about-us|title= About Us|publisher=UCL Hospitals Biomedical Research Centre|date=|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref> UCL is a founding member of the [[Francis Crick Institute]], a major biomedical research centre in London which is a partnership between [[Cancer Research UK]], Imperial College London, King's College London, the [[Medical Research Council (United Kingdom)|Medical Research Council]], the [[Wellcome Trust]] and UCL.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://crick.ac.uk/research/university-partners/|title=University partners|publisher=Francis Crick Institute|date=|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref> UCL also operates the Bloomsbury Research Institute, a research institute focused on basic to clinical and population studies in bacteriology, parasitology and virology, in partnership with the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloomsburyresearchinstitute.org.uk/institute/partners|title=University partners|publisher=Bloomsbury Research Institute|accessdate=28 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028215814/http://www.bloomsburyresearchinstitute.org.uk/institute/partners|archive-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nUCL offers joint degrees with numerous other universities and institutions, including [[Anna Freud Centre|The Anna Freud National Centre for Children and Families]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annafreud.org/training-research/ucl-postgraduate-study/ucl-postgraduate-programmes/|title=UCL Postgraduate Programmes|accessdate=29 July 2016|publisher=The Anna Freud National Centre for Children and Families}}</ref> [[Columbia University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laws.ucl.ac.uk/study/undergraduate/llb-degrees/joint-llb-jd/|title=Joint LLB/Juris Doctor (JD) with Columbia University, New York|accessdate=29 July 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> the [[University of Hong Kong]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laws.ucl.ac.uk/news-article/ucl-lawsdouble-degree-hku/|title=UCL Laws launches double degree with The University of Hong Kong|accessdate=29 July 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> Imperial College London,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/transport-studies|title=Centre for Transport Studies|accessdate=29 July 2016|publisher=Imperial College London}}</ref> [[New York University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wagner.nyu.edu/executivempa/globalexec|title=Global EMPA with University College London|accessdate=29 July 2016|publisher=New York University}}</ref> [[Peking University]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/1116/041116-ucl-peking-joint-MBA-signing/|title=Peking University and UCL agree joint MBA programme|accessdate=5 November 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> and [[Yale University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/pals/study/masters/TMSPSYSDNP01|title=Developmental Neuroscience and Psychopathology MRes|accessdate=29 July 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref>\n\nUCL is the sponsor of the [[UCL Academy]], a [[secondary school]] in the [[London Borough of Camden]]. The school opened in September 2012 and was the first in the UK to have a university as sole sponsor.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper =The Guardian| title = Academia and the academy: what makes a university open a school?|accessdate =23 August 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/higher-education-network/blog/2013/mar/19/ucl-academy-school-university-partnership|date =19 March 2013 }}</ref> UCL also has a strategic partnership with [[Newham Collegiate Sixth Form Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/1114/101114-ncs-partnership|title=UCL announces partnership with Newham Collegiate Sixth Form Centre|publisher=University College London| accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nUCL is a founding member of Knowledge Quarter, a partnership of academic, cultural, research, scientific and media organisations based in the knowledge cluster in the Bloomsbury and King's Cross area of London.<ref name=guard41214>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/dec/04/alan-turing-institute-big-data-knowledge-quarter-london|title=Alan Turing Institute for Data Science to be based at British Library|accessdate=24 January 2015|work=The Guardian|date=4 December 2014}}</ref> Other members of the partnership include the [[British Library]], the [[British Museum]], [[Google]] and the Wellcome Trust.<ref name=guard41214/>\n\nThe university is also a member of the [[Screen Studies Group, London]].\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Faculty and staff===\nIn the 2018/19 academic year, UCL had an average of 7,700 academic and research staff, the highest number of any UK university, of whom 5,845 were full-time and 1,855 part-time.<ref name=HESAstaff>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/staff/working-in-he#provider|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] |title=Who's working in HE |accessdate=1 March 2020|at=Staff numbers by HE provider }}</ref> UCL has 840 professors, the largest number of any British university.<ref name=\"factsandfigures\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/facts-figures|title=Key facts and figures|publisher=University College London|accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> As of August 2016 there were 56 Fellows of the Royal Society, 51 Fellows of the British Academy, 15 Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering and 121 Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences amongst UCL academic and research staff.<ref name=\"factsandfigures\"/>\n\n===Research===\n[[File:John O'Keefe (neuroscientist) 2014.jpg|thumb|[[John O'Keefe (neuroscientist)|John O'Keefe]], neuroscientist and the latest (2014) UCL faculty member to win a Nobel Prize (in [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Physiology or Medicine]] for his discovery of [[place cell]]s)]]\nUCL has made cross-disciplinary research a priority and orientates its research around four \"Grand Challenges\", Global Health, Sustainable Cities, Intercultural Interaction and Human Wellbeing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/grand-challenges/ |title=The Grand Challenges|publisher=University College London |accessdate=27 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014/15, UCL had a total research income of \u00a3427.5 million, the third-highest of any British university (after the University of Oxford and Imperial College London).<ref name=thefindat/> Key sources of research income in that year were BIS research councils (\u00a3148.3 million), UK-based charities (\u00a3106.5 million), UK central government, local/health authorities and hospitals (\u00a361.5 million), EU government bodies (\u00a345.5 million), and UK industry, commerce and public corporations (\u00a316.2 million).<ref name=finstat/> In 2015/16, UCL was awarded a total of \u00a385.8 million in grants by [[Research Councils UK|UK research councils]], the second-largest amount of any British university (after the University of Oxford), having achieved a 28% success rate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/university-oxford-tops-grant-funding-list|title=University of Oxford tops grant funding list|accessdate=27 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education|date=6 October 2016}}</ref> For the period to June 2015, UCL was the fifth-largest recipient of [[Horizon 2020]] EU research funding, and the largest recipient of any university, with \u20ac49.93 million of grants received.<ref name=horizon2020>{{cite web|url= http://vsnu.nl/files/documenten/Nieuwsberichten/Who_are_the_champions_in_Horizon_2020v2.pdf |title=Horizon 2020 champions |publisher=Nikolaos Floratos|date=|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> UCL also had the fifth-largest number of projects funded of any organisation, with 94.<ref name=horizon2020/>\n\nAccording to a ranking of universities produced by SCImago Research Group, UCL is ranked 12th in the world (and 1st in Europe) in terms of total research output.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scimagoir.com/pdf/sir_2010_world_report.pdf |title=SIR World Report 2010 :: Global Ranking |accessdate=2011-02-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121155654/http://www.scimagoir.com/pdf/sir_2010_world_report.pdf |archivedate=21 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> According to data released in July 2008 by [[ISI Web of Knowledge]], UCL is the 13th most-cited university in the world (and most-cited in Europe). The analysis covered citations from 1 January 1998 to 30 April 2008, during which 46,166 UCL research papers attracted 803,566 citations. The report covered citations in 21 subject areas and the results revealed some of UCL's key strengths, including: Clinical Medicine (1st outside North America); Immunology (2nd in Europe); Neuroscience & Behaviour (1st outside North America and 2nd in the world); Pharmacology & Toxicology (1st outside North America and 4th in the world); Psychiatry & Psychology (2nd outside North America); and Social Sciences, General (1st outside North America).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0807/08071504 |title=Research powerhouse: UCL top-cited in UK |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nUCL submitted a total of 2,566 staff across 36 units of assessment to the 2014 [[Research Excellence Framework]] (REF) assessment, in each case the highest number of any UK university (compared with 1,793 UCL staff submitted to the 2008 [[Research Assessment Exercise]] (RAE 2008)).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/ref-2014-winners-who-performed-best/2017591.article|title=REF 2014 winners: who performed best?|accessdate=30 December 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=18 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=therae>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=404786|title=RAE 2008: The results|accessdate=16 December 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=18 December 2008}}</ref> In the REF results 43% of UCL's submitted research was classified as 4* (world-leading), 39% as 3* (internationally excellent), 15% as 2* (recognised internationally) and 2% as 1* (recognised nationally), giving an overall GPA of 3.22 (RAE 2008: 4* \u2013 27%, 3* \u2013 39%, 2* \u2013 27% and 1* \u2013 6%).<ref name=therae/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/table/2008/dec/18/rae-2008-results-uk-universities|title=RAE 2008: results for UK universities|accessdate=16 December 2012|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2008}}</ref><ref name=REFranking>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/download?ac=26855|title=Overall ranking of institutions including power market share|accessdate=30 December 2014|work=Times Higher Education|date=18 December 2014}}</ref> In rankings produced by ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' based upon the REF results, UCL was ranked 1st overall for \"research power\" and joint 8th for GPA (compared to 4th and 7th respectively in equivalent rankings for the RAE 2008).<ref name=REFranking/>\n\n===Medicine===\n[[File:UCL Gower Street.jpg|thumb|The Cruciform Building on [[Gower Street (London)|Gower Street]] houses the preclinical facilities of the UCL Medical School]]\nUCL has offered courses in medicine since 1834, but the current [[UCL Medical School]] developed from mergers with the medical schools of the [[Middlesex Hospital]] (founded in 1746) and [[Royal Free Hospital|the Royal Free Hospital]] (founded as the [[London School of Medicine for Women]] in 1874).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/medicalschool/about-medicalschool |title=UCL Medical School |publisher=University College London |date=17 February 2010 |accessdate=26 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113150026/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/medicalschool/about-medicalschool |archivedate=13 January 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Clinical medicine is primarily taught at the Royal Free Hospital, [[University College Hospital]] and the [[Whittington Hospital]], with other associated teaching hospitals including the [[Eastman Dental Hospital]], [[Great Ormond Street Hospital]], [[Moorfields Eye Hospital]], the [[National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery]] and the [[Royal National Throat, Nose and Ear Hospital]].\n\nUCL is a major centre for biomedical research. In a bibliometric analysis of biomedical and health research in England for the period 2004\u201313, UCL was found to have produced by far the highest number of highly cited publications of any institution, with 12,672 (compared to second-placed Oxford University with 9,952).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rand.org/pubs/research_reports/RR1363.html|title=Bibliometric analysis of highly cited publications of biomedical and health research in England, 2004\u20132013|publisher=RAND Corporate|date=2015 |accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> UCL is part of three of the 20 biomedical research centres established by the [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] in England \u2013 the [[UCLH/UCL Biomedical Research Centre]], the NIHR Biomedical Research Centre at Moorfields Eye Hospital NHS Foundation Trust and UCL Institute of Ophthalmology, and the NIHR Great Ormond Street Biomedical Research Centre.<ref name=nihr>{{cite web|url=http://www.nihr.ac.uk/infrastructure/Pages/infrastructure_biomedical_research_centres.aspx|title=Biomedical Research Centres|accessdate=15 September 2010|publisher=National Institute for Health Research}}</ref> In the latest round of [[Department of Health]] funding for the 5 years from April 2017, the three UCL-affiliated biomedical research centres secured \u00a3168.6 million of the \u00a3811 million total funding nationwide, the largest amount awarded to any university and significantly higher than second-placed Oxford University (with \u00a3126.5 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/new-816-million-investment-in-health-research|title=New \u00a3816 million investment in health research|accessdate=12 October 2016|publisher=Department of Health| date=14 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nUCL is a founding member of [[UCL Partners]], the largest [[academic health science centre]] in Europe with a turnover of approximately \u00a32&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"Carvel\">{{Cite news |work=The Guardian |location=London | title = NHS hospitals to forge \u00a32bn research link-up with university | accessdate =15 September 2010| url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2008/aug/07/health.highereducation | date=7 August 2008  | first=John | last=Carvel}}</ref> UCL is also a member of the [[Francis Crick Institute]] based next to [[St Pancras railway station]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2010/jun/19/largest-biomedical-research-facility-europe|title=Plans for largest biomedical research facility in Europe unveiled|accessdate=15 September 2010|work=The Guardian |location=London | date=19 June 2010  | first=Alok | last=Jha}}</ref> It is one of the world's largest medical research centres, housing 1,250 scientists, and the largest of its kind in Europe.<ref name=pr5>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcmri.ac.uk/news/press-releases/unprecedented-step |title=Project Press Release |accessdate=11 August 2010 |publisher=UK Centre for Medical Research and Innovation web site |date=21 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100911231034/http://www.ukcmri.ac.uk/news/press-releases/unprecedented-step |archivedate=11 September 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Admissions===\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\" style=\"font-size:85%; text-align:center;\"\n|+ UCAS Admission Statistics\n!\n!2017\n!2016\n!2015\n!2014\n!2013\n|-\n|'''Applications'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144241/download?token=nlVZq6el|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_03 Applications by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|43,930\n|41,540\n|40,355\n|38,330\n|36,015\n|-\n|'''Offer Rate (%)'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex, area background and ethnic group: U80 UCL (University College London)|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/145576/download?token=GIr8lTjB|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|62.9\n|63.0\n|61.7\n|56.7\n|55.6\n|-\n|'''Enrols'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144196/download?token=JEpp6fiF|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_02 Main scheme acceptances by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|6,140\n|5,590\n|5,455\n|5,030\n|4,900\n|-\n|[[Yield (college admissions)|'''Yield (%)''']]\n|22.2\n|21.4\n|21.9\n|23.1\n|24.5\n|-\n|'''Applicant/Enrolled Ratio'''\n|7.15\n|7.43\n|7.40\n|7.62\n|7.35\n|-\n|'''[[UCAS Tariff|Average Entry Tariff]]'''<ref name=\"Complete League Table 2019\">{{cite-web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Table and Rankings|publisher=Complete University Guide}}</ref><ref group=note>New [[UCAS]] points from 2016</ref>\n|n/a\n|191\n|501\n|505\n|500\n|}\n[[File:Bentham House, UCL.jpg|right|thumb|Bentham House, the main building of the UCL Faculty of Laws]]\nAdmission to UCL is highly selective with an average entry tariff for 2016\u201317 of 191 [[UCAS points]] (approximately equivalent to A*AAB or AAAA at [[GCE Advanced Level (United Kingdom)|A-level]]), the 9th highest in the country and 3rd in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Entry+Standards|title=University League Tables 2019 (ranked by entry standards)|publisher=Complete University Guide|accessdate=18 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/0/the-10-hardest-universities-to-get-into/|title=The 10 hardest universities to get into|date=2018-06-25|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-07-28|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> UCL was one of the first universities in the UK to make use of the A* grade at A-Level (introduced in 2010) for admissions to courses including Economics, European Social and Political Studies, Law, Mathematics, Medicine, Theoretical Physics and Psychology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/downloads|title=Undergraduate Prospectus (2015 entry)|accessdate=25 January 2015|publisher=University College London}}</ref>\nThe university gave offers of admission to 62.9% of its applicants in 2017, and had the 6th lowest offer rate in the [[Russell Group]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Which elite universities have the highest offer rates |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2016/10/19/which-elite-universities-have-the-highest-offer-rates/|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=21 October 2016}}</ref> For 2017 entry, the university was one of only a few mainstream universities (along with [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], [[Imperial College London]], [[London School of Economics|LSE]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], [[University of St Andrews|St Andrews]], and [[University of Warwick|Warwick]]) to have no courses available in [[UCAS#Confirmation and Clearing|Clearing]].<ref name=Clearing2017>{{cite magazine|last1=Bhardwa|first1=Seeta|title=Clearing 2017: Top 10 UK universities with courses available|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/advice/clearing-2017-top-10-uk-universities-courses-available#survey-answer|magazine=Times Higher Education|accessdate=15 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nOf UCL's undergraduates, 32.4% are [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|privately educated]], the eighth highest proportion amongst mainstream British universities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Widening participation: UK Performance Indicators 2016/17|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/01-02-2018/widening-participation-tables|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> In the 2016\u201317 academic year, the university had a domicile breakdown of 59:12:30 of UK:EU:non-EU students respectively with a female to male ratio of 58:42.<ref>{{cite web|title=Where do HE students study?|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/students/where-study#provider|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nUndergraduate law applicants are required to take the [[National Admissions Test for Law]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=196591&sectioncode=26|title=Law test gains support|accessdate=17 June 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=10 June 2005}}</ref> and undergraduate medical applicants are required to take the [[BioMedical Admissions Test]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=200376&sectioncode=26|title=New test for medics|accessdate=20 June 2012|work=Times Higher Education|date=16 December 2005}}</ref> Applicants for European Social and Political Studies are required to take the [[Thinking Skills Assessment]] (TSA) should they be selected for an assessment day.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.admissionstestingservice.org/for-test-takers/thinking-skills-assessment/tsa-ucl/about-tsa-ucl/ |title=About TSA UCl |work=Admissions Testing Service |year=2014 |accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> Some UCL departments interview undergraduate applicants prior to making an offer of admission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucas.com/students/choosingcourses/choosinguni/instguide/u/u80|title=University College London (University of London) (U80)|accessdate=20 June 2012|publisher=UCAS|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120617175825/http://www.ucas.com/students/choosingcourses/choosinguni/instguide/u/u80|archivedate=17 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nUndergraduate subjects with the highest applicants to places ratio at UCL in 2015 included <!--Please only include subjects with a ratio over 10:1-->Architecture BSc (14:1 ratio),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/architecture-bsc/|title=Architecture BSc|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> Economics BSc (Econ) (11:1 ratio),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/economics-bsc-econ/|title=Economics BSc (Econ)|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> Engineering (Mechanical with Business Finance) MEng (10:1 ratio),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/engineering-mechanical-business-finance-meng/|title=Engineering (Mechanical with Business Finance) MEng|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> English BA (10:1 ratio),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/english-ba/|title=English BA|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> Fine Art BA (23:1 ratio),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/fine-art-ba/|title=Fine Art BA|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> Law LL.B (16:1 ratio)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/law-llb/|title=Law LL.B|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref> and Philosophy, Politics and Economics BSc (30:1 ratio).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/prospective-students/undergraduate/degrees/philosophy-politics-economics-bsc/|title=Philosophy, Politics and Economics BSc|accessdate=18 April 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref>\n\n===Foundation programmes===\nUCL runs intensive one-year foundation courses that lead to a variety of degree programmes at UCL and other top UK universities. Called the [[UCL University Preparatory Certificate (UPC)|UCL University Preparatory Certificate]], the courses are targeted at international students of high academic potential whose education systems in their own countries usually do not offer qualifications suitable for direct admission. There are two pathways \u2013 one in science and engineering called the UPCSE; and one in the humanities called UPCH. Students completing this course progress onto undergraduate programmes at Nazarbayev University.<ref>{{cite news| title =UCL Undergraduate Preparatory Certificates| url   = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/language-centre/preparatory-certificates}}</ref>\n\n===Libraries===\n[[File:Donaldson Reading Room, UCL.jpg|thumb|right|The Donaldson Reading Room, part of UCL's Main Library]]\n[[File:IOE Newsam Library.JPG|thumb|right|The UCL Institute of Education's Newsam Library, the largest education library in Europe]]\nThe UCL library system comprises 17 libraries located across several sites within the main UCL campus and across [[Bloomsbury]], linked together by a central networking catalogue and request system called Explore.<ref name=\"libsites\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/|title=UCL Library Services|publisher=University College London|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ucl-new-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo-explore/search?vid=UCL_VU2&sortby=rank|title=UCL Library Services Explore|access-date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/catalogue.shtml|title=eUCLid library catalogue|accessdate=29 September 2010|publisher=University College London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206123108/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Library/catalogue.shtml|archivedate=6 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}{{cite web|url=http://ucl-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/search.do?dscnt=1&dstmp=1393975596438&vid=UCL_VU1&fromLogin=true|title=Explore library catalogue|accessdate=4 March 2014|publisher=University College London}}</ref> The libraries contain a total of over 2 million books.<ref name=hefcelib>{{cite web|url=http://www.hefce.ac.uk/pubs/rereports/year/2008/reviewofhefcefundingforresearchlibraries/|title=Review of HEFCE funding for research libraries|accessdate=23 June 2012|publisher=Higher Education Funding Council for England }}</ref> The largest library is the UCL Main Library, which is located in the UCL Main Building and contains collections relating to the arts and humanities, economics, history, law and public policy.<ref name=libsites/> The second largest library is the UCL Science Library, which is located in the DMS Watson Building on Malet Place and contains collections relating to anthropology, engineering, geography, life sciences, management and the mathematical and physical sciences.<ref name=libsites/> The Cruciform Hub contains books and periodicals in the subjects of clinical medicine and medical science.<ref>{{cite web |title=UCL Cruciform Hub |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/libraries-and-study-spaces/ucl-cruciform-hub |website=University College London |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> It holds the combined collections of the former Boldero and Clinical Sciences libraries which developed within the [[Middlesex Hospital]], [[University College Hospital]] and [[Royal Free Hospital|Royal Free]] & [[UCL Medical School|University College Medical School]]s up until their merger in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Campbell |first1=P. |last2=Cheney |first2=C. R. |title=Reading medicine: A history of the libraries of The Middlesex and University College Hospitals Medical Schools |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/sites/library/files/reading-medicine.pdf |publisher=UCL Library Services |date=2006 |accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> Other libraries include the [[The Bartlett|UCL Bartlett]] Library (architecture and town planning), the [[UCL Eastman Dental Institute#Library|UCL Eastman Dental Institute Library]] (oral health sciences), the [[UCL Institute of Archaeology]] Library (archaeology and egyptology), the UCL Institute of Education's [[Institute of Education#Library|Newsam Library]] (education and related areas of social science), the [[UCL Institute of Neurology#Library|UCL Institute of Neurology Rockefeller Medical Library]] (neurosurgery and neuroscience), the [[UCL Institute of Ophthalmology#Library|Joint Moorfields Eye Hospital & the UCL Institute of Ophthalmology Library]] (biomedicine, medicine, nursing, ophthalmology and visual science), the UCL Language & Speech Science Library (audiology, communication disorders, linguistics & phonetics, special education, speech & language therapy and voice) and the [[UCL School of Slavonic and East European Studies#Library|UCL School of Slavonic and East European Studies Library]] (the economics, geography, history, languages, literature and politics of Eastern Europe).<ref name=libsites/>\n\nUCL staff and students have full access to the main libraries of the University of London\u2014the [[Senate House Library]] and the libraries of the Institutes of the [[School of Advanced Study]]\u2014which are located close to the main UCL campus in Bloomsbury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ulrls.lon.ac.uk/libraries/index.asp|title=Libraries|accessdate=29 September 2010|publisher=University of London Research Library Services|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105171247/http://www.ulrls.lon.ac.uk/libraries/index.asp|archivedate=5 November 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These libraries contain over 3.7&nbsp;million books and focus on the arts, humanities and social sciences.<ref name=hefcelib/> The [[British Library]], which contains around 14 million books, is also located close to the main UCL campus and all UCL students and staff can apply for reference access.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/library/other-libraries/#special|title=Libraries with special UCL arrangements|accessdate=17 July 2016|publisher=University College London}}</ref>\n\nSince 2004, UCL Library Services has been collecting the scholarly work of UCL researchers to make it freely available on the internet via an [[Institutional repository|open access repository]] known as UCL Eprints.<ref name=eprints>{{cite web|url=http://eprints.ucl.ac.uk/information.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116104938/http://eprints.ucl.ac.uk/information.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=16 January 2008|title=About UCL Eprints|accessdate=29 September 2010|publisher=University College London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0803/08031304|title=UCL Eprints repository rankings|accessdate=29 September 2010|publisher=University College London}}</ref> The intention is that material curated by UCL Eprints will remain accessible indefinitely.<ref name=eprints/>\n\n===Museums and collections===\nUCL's Special Collections contains UCL's collection of historical or culturally significant works. It is one of the foremost university collections of [[manuscripts]], [[archives]] and [[rare book]]s in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Library/special-coll/index.shtml |title=UCL Library Services \u2013 Special Collections Library |publisher=University College London |date=22 January 2010 |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> It includes collections of [[medieval]] manuscripts and early printed books, as well as significant holdings of 18th-century works, and highly important 19th- and 20th-century collections of personal papers, archival material, and literature, covering a vast range of subject areas. Archives include the Latin American archives, the Jewish collections and the [[George Orwell]] Archive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Library/special-coll/azdirect.shtml |title=UCL Library Services \u2013 Special Collections A-Z Directory |publisher=University College London |date=8 September 2008 |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> Collections are often displayed in a series of glass cabinets in the Cloisters of the UCL Main Building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Library/special-coll/index.shtml#news |title=UCL Library Services \u2013 Special Collections Library |publisher=University College London |date=22 January 2010 |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nUCL's most significant works are housed in the Strong Rooms. The special collection includes first editions of [[Isaac Newton]]'s ''[[Philosophiae Naturalis Principia Mathematica|Principia]]'', [[Charles Darwin]]'s ''[[On the Origin of Species]]'' and [[James Joyce]]'s ''[[Ulysses (novel)|Ulysses]]''. The earliest book in the collection is ''The crafte to lyve well and to dye well'', printed in 1505.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Library/special-coll/srbooks.shtml |title=UCL Library Services \u2013 Special Collections Library |publisher=University College London |date=10 February 2005 |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Flaxman Gallery, UCL.JPG|thumb|right|The Flaxman Gallery]]\nUCL is responsible for several museums and collections in a wide range of fields across the arts and sciences, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/ |title=UCL Museums & Collections &#124; Home |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n* [[Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology]]: one of the leading collections of Egyptian and Sudanese archaeology in the world. Open to the public on a regular basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.petrie.ucl.ac.uk/ |title=Welcome to The Petrie Museum of Egyptian Archaeology |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n* UCL Art Museum: the art collections date from 1847, when a collection of sculpture models and drawings by the [[Neoclassicism|neoclassical]] artist [[John Flaxman]] was presented to UCL. There are over 10,000 pieces dating from the 15th century onwards including drawings by [[Joseph Mallord William Turner|Turner]], etchings by [[Rembrandt Harmenszoon van Rijn|Rembrandt]], and works by many leading 20th-century British artists. The works on paper are displayed in the Strang Print Room, which has limited regular opening times. The other works may be viewed by appointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/uclart |title=UCL Museums & Collections |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n* Flaxman Gallery: a series of plaster casts of full-size details of sculptures by John Flaxman is located inside the Main Library under the central dome of the UCL Main Building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/uclart/collections/collections/flaxman |title=The John Flaxman Collection |accessdate=29 September 2010 |publisher=University College London |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622194837/https://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/uclart/collections/collections/flaxman |archivedate=22 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n* [[Grant Museum of Zoology and Comparative Anatomy]]: a diverse Natural History collection covering the whole of the animal kingdom. Includes rare [[dodo]] and [[quagga]] skeletons. A teaching and research collection, it is named after [[Robert Edmund Grant]], UCL's first professor of comparative anatomy and zoology from 1828, now mainly noted for having tutored the undergraduate [[Charles Robert Darwin]] at the [[University of Edinburgh]] in the 1826\u20131827 session.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/culture/grant-museum-zoology|title=UCL Museums & Collections|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Grant.museum.University College London|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n* Geology Collections: founded around 1855. Primarily a teaching resource and may be visited by appointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/geology |title=UCL Museums & Collections |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Institute of Archaeology Collections]]: items include prehistoric ceramics and stone artefacts from many parts of the world, the Petrie collection of Palestinian artefacts, and Classical Greek and Roman ceramics. Visits by appointment only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/archaeology |title=UCL Museums & Collections |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Ethnography]] Collections: this collection exemplifying Material Culture holds an enormous variety of objects, textiles and artefacts from all over the world. Visits by appointment only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/ethno |title=UCL Museums & Collections |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n* Galton Collection: the scientific instruments, papers and personal memorabilia of Sir [[Francis Galton]]. Housed in the department of biology. Visits by appointment only.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/galton |title=UCL Museums & Collections &#124; Home |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n* Science Collections: diverse collections primarily accumulated in the course of UCL's own work, including the operating table on which the first anaesthetic was administered. Items may be a viewed by appointment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/museums/sciences |title=UCL Museums & Collections |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Rankings and reputation===\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| ARWU_W             = 15\n| QS_W               = 8\n| THE_W              = 15\n| LEIDEN_W           = 18\n| LINE_1             = 0\n| Complete           = 10\n| The_Guardian       = 22\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 9\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Silver\n}}\n<!--Please leave rankings in alpha-order for neutrality:-->\n;International\n<!--Main international rankings: ARWU, QS and THE:-->\nIn the 2019/2020 ''[[QS World University Rankings]]'', UCL is ranked 8th in the world, 1st in London, 3rd in the United Kingdom and 4th in Europe.<ref name=\"QS World University Rankings\" /> In the 2019/20 Rankings by Subject, UCL has 38 subjects in the world top 100. It is ranked in the world top 10 for nine subjects: anthropology (10th), archaeology (3rd), architecture (1st), anatomy and physiology (5th), education and training (1st), geography (7th), medicine (9th), pharmacy and pharmacology (7th), and psychology (10th). In broad subject areas, it is ranked 10th for life sciences and medicine, 15th for arts and humanities, 34th for social sciences and management, 49th for engineering and technology, and 63rd equal for natural sciences. In the QS Graduate Employability Ranking, UCL is ranked 22nd.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/universities/ucl-university-college-london#wurs|title=UCL (University College London)|accessdate=18 January 2020|work=Top Universities|publisher=QS Quacquarelli Symonds Limited}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2019 ''[[Academic Ranking of World Universities]]'', UCL is ranked 15th in the world (and 3rd in Europe).<ref name=\"Academic Ranking of World Universities\"/> In the 2016 subject tables it was ranked 8th in the world (and 2nd in Europe) for Clinical Medicine & Pharmacy,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldMED2016.html|title=Academic Ranking of World Universities in Clinical Medicine and Pharmacy \u2013 2016|accessdate=22 September 2016|publisher=Shanghai Ranking Consultancy}}</ref> joint 51st to 75th in the world (and joint 10th in Europe) for Engineering, Technology and Computer Sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldENG2016.html|title=Academic Ranking of World Universities in Engineering/Technology and Computer Sciences \u2013 2016|accessdate=22 September 2016|publisher=Shanghai Ranking Consultancy}}</ref> 9th in the world (and 2nd in Europe) for Life & Agricultural Sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldLIFE2016.html|title=Academic Ranking of World Universities in Life and Agriculture Sciences \u2013 2016|accessdate=22 September 2016|publisher=Shanghai Ranking Consultancy}}</ref> joint 51st to 75th in the world (and joint 14th in Europe) for Natural Sciences and Mathematics<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldSCI2016.html|title=Academic Ranking of World Universities in Natural Sciences and Mathematics \u2013 2016|accessdate=22 September 2016|publisher=Shanghai Ranking Consultancy}}</ref> and joint 51st to 75th in the world (and joint 12th in Europe) for Social Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/FieldSOC2016.html|title=Academic Ranking of World Universities in Social Science \u2013 2016|accessdate=22 September 2016|publisher=Shanghai Ranking Consultancy}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2020 ''[[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]]'', UCL is ranked 15th in the world (and 4th in Europe).<ref name=\"THE World University Rankings\" /> In the 2016/17 subject tables it was ranked 4th in the world (and 2nd in Europe) for Arts and Humanities,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/arts-and-humanities#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title=World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: arts and humanities|accessdate=9 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> 6th in the world (and 4th in Europe) for Clinical, Pre-Clinical and Health,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/clinical-pre-clinical-health#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title=World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: clinical, pre-clinical and health|accessdate=9 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> 12th in the world (and 6th in Europe) for Computer Science,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/computer-science#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title=World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: computer science|accessdate=9 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> joint 38th in the world (and 12th in Europe) for Engineering and Technology,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/engineering-and-IT#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title=World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: engineering and technology|accessdate=9 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> 12th in the world (and 4th in Europe) for Life Sciences,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/life-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title=World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: life sciences|accessdate=9 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> joint 23rd in the world (and 8th in Europe) for Physical Sciences<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/physical-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title=World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: physical sciences|accessdate=9 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> and 14th in the world (and 3rd in Europe) for Social Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/subject-ranking/social-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank_label/sort_order/asc/cols/rank_only|title=World University Rankings 2016\u20132017 by subject: social sciences|accessdate=9 October 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> In the 2017 ''Times Higher Education World Reputation Rankings'', UCL is ranked 16th in the world.<ref name=thereputat>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2017/reputation-ranking#survey-answer|title=World Reputation Rankings 2017|accessdate=17 June 2017|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> In the 2015 ''Times Higher Education Global Employability University Ranking'', UCL is ranked 48th in the world.<ref name=theemployability>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/global-university-employability-ranking-2016|title=The Global Employability University Ranking 2016|accessdate=9 August 2017|date=16 November 2016|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref>\n\n<!--Other global rankings:-->\nIn 2019, UCL ranked 9th among the universities around the world by [[SCImago Institutions Rankings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scimagoir.com/rankings.php?sector=Higher%20educ.&country=all|title=SCImago Institutions Rankings \u2013 Higher Education \u2013 All Regions and Countries \u2013 2019 \u2013 Overall Rank|website=www.scimagoir.com}}</ref> UCL is ranked 18th in the world (2nd in Europe) for number of publications and 18th in the world (6th in Europe) for quality of publications in the 2019 ''[[CWTS Leiden Ranking]]''.<ref name=\"CWTS Leiden Ranking\" /> UCL is ranked 5th in the world (2nd in Europe) in the 2016/17 ''[[University Ranking by Academic Performance]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urapcenter.org/2016/world.php?q=MS0yNTA=|title=2016\u20132017 WORLD RANKING|work=University Ranking by Academic Performance|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> UCL is ranked 10th in the world (2nd in Europe) in the 2017 ''National Taiwan University Performance Ranking of Scientific Papers for World Universities''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nturanking.lis.ntu.edu.tw/DataPage/OverallRanking.aspx?y=2017|title=2017 Overall Ranking|publisher=National Taiwan University|accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref>  UCL is also ranked 17th in the world (8th in Europe) in the 2017 ''[[Round University Ranking]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roundranking.com/ranking.html|title=Round University Rankings 2016|publisher=RUR Rankings Agency|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> In the 2018 ''[[U.S. News & World Report Best Global University Ranking]]'', UCL is ranked 22nd in the world (4th in Europe).<ref name=USNEWSRANKING>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/university-college-london-501693|title=Best Global Universities \u2013 University College London|magazine=U.S. News & World Report|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n;National\nUCL is ranked as one of the top 10 multi-faculty universities in two of the three main  [[Rankings of universities in the United Kingdom|UK university league tables]]. These place more emphasis on the undergraduate student experience than global rankings, using criteria such as teaching quality and learning resources, entry standards, employment prospects, research quality and dropout rates. In the 2019 ''[[Times Higher Education]]'' \"Table of Tables\", which is based on the combined results of the UK's three main domestic university rankings, UCL is ranked 10th.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/table-tables-2019-lincoln-and-nottingham-trent-top-30|title=THE 'Table of Tables' 2019: Lincoln and Nottingham Trent in top 30|author= Ellie Bothwell |date=25 October 2018|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> Historically, in ''[[The Sunday Times]]'' 10-year (1998\u20132007) average ranking of British universities based on their league table performance, UCL was ranked 5th overall in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf|title=University ranking based on performance over 10 years|work=The Times |location=London |year=2007|accessdate=28 April 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080414064446/http://extras.timesonline.co.uk/pdfs/univ07ten.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 14 April 2008}}</ref> UCL was also one of only eight universities (along with the other members of the [[G5 (universities)|G5]], [[University of Bath|Bath]], [[University of St Andrews|St Andrews]] and [[University of Warwick|Warwick]]) to have never been outside the top 15 in one of the three main domestic rankings between 2008\u20132017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Domestic Ranking of British Universisities over a 10-Year Period|url=http://theuniversitybuzz.blogspot.co.uk/2017/01/domestic-ranking-of-british.html|publisher=The University Buzz}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2020 ''Complete University Guide'' subject tables, UCL was ranked in the top 10 in 25 subjects out of 37 offered (67.6%), placing it 9th in terms of proportion of subjects in the top 10.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/who-ranks-top-of-the-tables-by-subject-2020/#topoftables|title=Who Ranks Top of the Tables by Subject 2020|publisher=The Complete University Guide|accessdate=14 June 2019}}</ref> In a 2015 ''Times Higher Education'' study UCL was chosen as the 8th best university in the UK for the quality of graduates according to recruiters from the UK's major companies.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/news/best-uk-universities-chosen-major-employers | location=London | work=Times Higher Education | title=The best UK universities chosen by major employers | date=12 November 2015}}</ref> According to data released by the [[Department for Education]] in 2018, UCL was rated as the 7th best university in the UK for boosting female graduate earnings with female graduates seeing a 15.5% increase in earnings compared to the average graduate, and the 10th best university for males, with male graduates seeing a 16.2% increase in earnings compared to the average graduate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Undergraduate degrees: relative labour market returns (Table 7: HEI \u2013 conditional impact on earnings five years after graduation) |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/undergraduate-degrees-relative-labour-market-returns |publisher=Department for Education |accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial activities==\nUCL has significant commercial activities and in 2014/15 these generated around \u00a3155 million in revenues.<ref name=finstat/> UCL's principal commercial activities include [[UCL Business]], UCL Consultants, and catering and accommodation services.<ref name=finstat/> UCL has also participated in a number of commercial joint ventures, including EuroTempest Ltd and Imanova Ltd (now part of Invicro).<ref name=finstat/>\n\n===UCL Business===\n{{main|UCL Business}}\nUCL Business (UCLB) is a [[technology transfer]] company which is wholly owned by UCL. It has three main activities: licensing technologies, creating spin-out companies, and project management.<ref name=uclbwwd>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclb.com/what-we-do|title=What we do|publisher=UCL Business|accessdate=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028021221/http://www.uclb.com/what-we-do|archive-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> UCLB supports spin-out companies in areas including discovery disclosure, commercialisation, business plan development, contractual advice, incubation support, recruitment of management teams and identification of investors.<ref name=uclbwwd/> In the area of licensing technoloiges, UCLB provides commercial, legal and administrative advice to help companies broker licensing agreements.<ref name=uclbwwd/> UCLB also provides UCL departments and institutes with project management services for single or multi-party collaborative industry projects.<ref name=uclbwwd/>\n\nUCLB had a turnover of \u00a38 million in 2014/15 and as at 31 July 2015 had equity holdings in 61 companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uclb.com/who-we-are/key-facts|title=Key facts|publisher=UCL Business|accessdate=27 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028083854/http://www.uclb.com/who-we-are/key-facts|archive-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===UCL Consultants===\nUCL Consultants (UCLC) is an academic consultancy services company which is wholly owned by UCL.<ref name=uclca>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/consultants/about-us|title=What we do|publisher=UCL Consultants|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref> It provides four main service offerings: Academic Consultancy, Bespoke Short Courses, Testing & Analysis and Expert Witness.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/consultants/our-services|title=Our Services|publisher=UCL Consultants|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\nAs of 31 July 2018 UCLC had over 1,900 registered consultants.\n\nUCLC had a turnover of \u00a317.8 million in 2018/19.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/finance/home/annual-report-and-financial-statements|title=Annual Report and Finances|publisher=UCL|accessdate=5 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n===UCL Press===\nUCL Press is a university press wholly owned by UCL.<ref name=uclpr>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/ucl-press|title=ucl press|publisher=UCL Press |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> It was the first fully [[open access]] university press in the UK, and publishes monographs, textbooks and other academic books in a wide range of academic areas which are available to download for free, in addition to a number of journals<ref name=uclpr2>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0515/270515-ucl-press|publisher=UCL|title=UCL launches UK's first fully Open Access university press |accessdate=25 July 2017}}</ref> As of May 2018, UCL Press had had more than 1 million downloads of its open access books.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0518/230518-ucl-press |title=UCL Press hits one million book downloads milestone|date=23 May 2018 |work= UCL News |publisher=UCL }}</ref>\n\n===Imanova===\nImanova is a joint venture company of UCL, Imperial College London, Kings College London and the Medical Research Council which owns and\nmanages the Clinical Imaging Centre located at Imperial College London's [[Hammersmith Hospital]] campus.<ref name=finstat/>\n\n==Student life==\n[[File:UCL summer ball 2014.jpg|thumb|Performers at the 2014 UCL summer ball]]\n\n===Student body===\nIn the 2014/15 academic year UCL had a total of 35,615 students, of whom 16,830 were undergraduate and 18,785 were postgraduate.<ref name=hesa>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/14-01-2016/sfr224-enrolments-and-qualifications|title=Higher education student enrolments and qualifications obtained at higher education providers in the United Kingdom 2014/15|accessdate=27 October 2016|publisher=HESA}}</ref> In that year, UCL had the [[List of universities in the United Kingdom by enrolment|third-largest total number of students of any university in the United Kingdom]] (after the Open University and the University of Manchester), and the largest number of postgraduate students.<ref name=hesa/>\n\nIn 2013/14 87% of UCL's students were full-time and 13% part-time,<ref name=studenttablea>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/srs/statistics/tables/a/total|title=Student Numbers by Method of Study 2003\u201304 to 2013\u201314|accessdate=31 August 2014|publisher=University College London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150515164109/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/srs/statistics/tables/a/total|archivedate=15 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and 54% were female and 46% male.<ref name=studenttablee>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/srs/statistics/tables/e/all-years|title=Student Numbers by Gender 2003\u201304 to 2013\u201314|accessdate=31 August 2014|publisher=University College London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904024514/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/srs/statistics/tables/e/all-years|archivedate=4 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2013/14, 12,330 UCL students were from outside the UK (43% of the total number of students in that year), of whom 5,504 were from Asia, 3,679 from the European Union ex. the United Kingdom, 1,195 from North America, 516 from the Middle East, 398 from Africa, 254 from Central and South America, and 166 from Australasia.<ref name=studenttablep>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/srs/statistics/tables/p/all-years|title=Comparison of the Numbers of Students of Overseas Nationality 2008\u201309 to 2013\u201314|accessdate=31 August 2014|publisher=University College London|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510081757/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/srs/statistics/tables/p/all-years|archivedate=10 May 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAs of 31 July 2015, UCL had around 220,000 alumni across 190 countries, of whom around 137,000 were based in the United Kingdom (and approximately 60,000 were based in London). The largest alumni communities outside of the UK are in the United States, Greece and China.<ref name=finstat/>\n\n===UCL Union===\n[[File:University College London Union.jpg|upright|thumb|The main UCL Union building situated on Gordon Street]]\n{{main|University College London Union}}\nFounded in 1893, the UCL Union is one of the oldest students' unions in England, although postdating the [[Liverpool Guild of Students]] which formed a student representative council in 1892.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /><ref name=\"LGoS\">{{cite web|title=History of the Guild |publisher=Liverpool Guild of Students |url=http://www.lgos.org/main-menu/guild-life/history-of-the-guild |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140621211819/http://www.lgos.org/main-menu/guild-life/history-of-the-guild |archive-date=21 June 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> UCL Union operates both as the representative voice for UCL students, and as a provider of a wide range of services. It is democratically controlled through General Meetings and referendums, and is run by elected student officers. The Union has provided a prominent platform for political campaigning of all kinds in recent years.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}  It also supports a range of services, including numerous clubs and societies, sports facilities, an advice service, and a number of bars, cafes and shops.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uclunion.org/index.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040427165044/http://www.uclunion.org/index.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 April 2004 |title=UCL Union |publisher=University College London Union |date=13 April 2010 |accessdate=26 April 2010 }}</ref> The union is also responsible for the organisation of a number of events, including, amongst others, the college's annual summer ball.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nThere are currently over 150 clubs and societies under the umbrella of the UCL Union, including: UCL Snowsports (one of the largest sports society at UCL, responsible for organising the annual UCL ski trip),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://studentsunionucl.org/clubs-societies/snowsports-club|title=UCL Snowsports Club|publisher=UCL Union|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Pi Media (responsible for ''[[Pi Magazine]]'' and ''Pi Newspaper'', UCL's official student publications);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pimedia.org.uk |title=University College London student publications \u2013 Home |publisher=Pi Media |accessdate=14 December 2010}}</ref> UCL Union Debating Society, UCL's second oldest society (established 1829),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.ucl.ac.uk/DServe/dserve.exe?dsqIni=Dserve.ini&dsqApp=Archive&dsqCmd=Show.tcl&dsqSearch=RefNo==%27MS%20ADD%2051%27&dsqDb=Catalog|title= University College, London: Guild of Graduates Minute Book|work=UCL Archives|publisher=UCL Library Services|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> UCL Union Film Society, one of the country's oldest film societies with past members including Christopher Nolan;{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} ''[[The Cheese Grater]]'' (a student magazine containing a mix of news investigations and humorous items); and the University College London Investment Society, one of the largest and most popular career societies at UCL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uclis.co.uk/ |title=University College London Investment Society |publisher=UCLIS |accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2018}}\n\n===Sport===\nUCL Union runs over 50 sports clubs, including UCL Cricket Club (Men's and Women's as well as Medical School clubs), UCL Boat Club (Men's and Women's clubs), UCL Cross Country and Athletics Club and UCL Rugby Club (Men's and Women's as well as Medical School clubs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uclu.org/services/active-uclu/uclu-sport|title=UCLU Sport|accessdate=29 December 2012|publisher=University College London Union|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130109061139/http://uclu.org/services/active-uclu/uclu-sport|archivedate=9 January 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nUCL clubs compete in inter-university fixtures in the [[British Universities and Colleges Sport]] (BUCS) competition in a range of sports, including basketball, cricket, fencing, football, hockey, netball, rugby union and tennis. In the 2014/15 season, UCL finished in 24th position in the final BUCS rankings of 151 participating higher education institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bucs.org.uk/bucscore/bucspoints.aspx?season=14|title=BUCS Points 2014/15|accessdate=4 April 2016|publisher=British Universities and Colleges Sport}}</ref>\n\nUCL sports facilities include a fitness centre at the main UCL campus in Bloomsbury, a sports centre in [[Somers Town, London|Somers Town]] and a 90-acre athletics ground in Shenley.<ref>{{cite book |title=Student Book 2007|first1=Klaus|last1=Boehm|first2=Jenny|last2=Lees-Spalding|publisher=Crimson Publishing|year=2006|isbn=978-1844550739|page=711|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ygBJv9ks7Q0C}}</ref>\n\n===Mascot===\nUCL mascot is Phineas Maclino, or Phineas, a wooden tobacconist's sign of a kilted Jacobite Highlander stolen from outside a shop in [[Tottenham Court Road]] during the celebrations of the [[relief of Ladysmith]], part of the [[Second Boer War]], in March 1900.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingscollections.org/exhibitions/archives/mayhem/origins/mascots|title=King's Collections : Online Exhibitions : The College mascots: Phineas and Reggie|website=www.kingscollections.org}}</ref> This establishment of mascots at both UCL and King's saw the beginning of mascotry, where Phineas would be kidnapped by King's and then this act would be avenged by UCL. In 1922, Phineas was briefly stolen by King's, and later during the 1927 rag the King's mascot 'Reggie the Lion' was captured by UCL students and his body filled with rotten apples. In 1993, the university's centenary year, Phineas was placed in the third floor bar of 25 Gordon Street and the bar named after him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uclu.org/about-uclu/who-is-phineas-0|title=Who is Phineas? \u2013 UCLU|website=UCLU}}</ref>\n\n===Rivalry with King's College London===\n[[File:UCL-KCL Varsity Rugby 2014.jpg|thumb|A UCL player attacks in his team's 2014 Varsity victory. UCL's traditional rivalry with King's College is nowadays most noticeable at the annual varsity rugby game]]\n{{main|King's College London\u2013UCL rivalry}}\n\nUCL has a long-running, mostly friendly rivalry with [[King's College London]], which has historically been known as \"Rags\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/depsta/iss/archives/rag/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040810173356/http://www.kcl.ac.uk/depsta/iss/archives/rag/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=10 August 2004 |title=Mayhem in the Metropolis: King's College versus University College in Student Rags |publisher=King's College London |accessdate=26 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> UCL students have been referred to by students from King's as the \"Godless Scum of Gower Street\", in reference to a comment made at the founding of King's, which was based on Christian principles. UCL students in turn referred to King's as \"Strand Polytechnic\".\n\nThe King's' mascot, [[King's College London Students' Union#Mascot|Reggie the Lion]], went missing in the 1990s and was recovered after being found dumped in a field. It was restored at the cost of around \u00a315,000 and then placed on display in the students' union.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/depsta/iss/archives/rag/rag05.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040814040509/http://www.kcl.ac.uk/depsta/iss/archives/rag/rag05.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 August 2004 |title=Mayhem in the Metropolis: King's College versus University College in Student Rags |publisher=King's College London |accessdate=26 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is in a glass case and filled with concrete to prevent theft, particularly by UCL students who once castrated it. In turn, King's' students are also believed to have once stolen Phineas, a UCL mascot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/depsta/iss/archives/rag/rag04.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040814035918/http://www.kcl.ac.uk/depsta/iss/archives/rag/rag04.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=14 August 2004 |title=Mayhem in the Metropolis: King's College versus University College in Student Rags |publisher=King's College London |accessdate=26 April 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is often claimed that King's' students played football with the embalmed head of [[Jeremy Bentham]]. Although the head was indeed stolen, the football story is a myth or legend which is unsupported by official UCL documentation about Bentham available next to his display case (his auto-icon) in the UCL cloisters. The head is now kept in the UCL vaults.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Bentham-Project/who/autoicon |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112065654/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/Bentham-Project/who/autoicon |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 November 2010 |title=Auto-Icon |publisher=University College London |accessdate=28 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Student campaigns===\nStudent campaigns at UCL have included: UCLU Free Education Campaign (a campaign for the return of free and non-marketised higher education); the London Living wage Campaign (a campaign for a basic minimum wage for all UCL staff); Disarm UCL (a campaign which successfully persuaded UCL not to invest in defence companies); and Save UCL (this name has been used by two campaigns: one in 2006 which opposed a merger between UCL and Imperial College London in 2006, and a more recent one against education cuts).\n\nAs part of the [[2010 UK student protests|protests against the UK Government's plans to increase student fees]], around 200 students occupied the Jeremy Bentham Room and part of the [[Slade School of Fine Art]] for over two weeks during November and December 2010.<ref name=\"students stage day of protests\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-11829102 |title= Students stage day of protests over tuition fee rises |work=BBC News  |date=24 November 2010 | accessdate=13 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"uclprotest\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-11954418 |title= University College London granted eviction order |work=BBC News |date=8 December 2010 | accessdate=13 December 2010}}</ref> The university successfully obtained a court order to evict the students but stated that it did not intend to enforce the order if possible.<ref name=\"uclprotest\"/>\n\nStudent campaigns around university run accommodation at UCL have gained momentum in recent years. In 2016, over 1000 students withholding rent and went on rent strike in protest of high rents and poor conditions. This rent strike was claimed by its organisers to have won over \u00a31 million in rent cuts, freezes and grants from UCL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2016/oct/19/why-i-refuse-to-pay-my-university-rent|title=Why I refuse to pay my university rent|author=Anonymous blogger|work=The Guardian |date=19 October 2016}}</ref> Since 2016, there have been rent strikes in 2017, leading to UCL pledging around \u00a31.4 million in bursaries and rent freezes, mostly in the form of bursaries for less well-off students which were set at \u00a3600,000 per year for the 2017/18 and 2018/19 academic years.<ref name=Strike2017>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2017/jul/06/students-win-15m-pledge-from-ucl-after-five-month-rent-strike|title=Students win \u00a31.5m pledge from UCL after five-month rent strike|author=Alfie Packham|date=6 July 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Another rent strike was held at two halls of residence in the third term of the 2017/18 academic year due to complaints over conditions at those Harris.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://leftfootforward.org/2018/05/students-strike-on-rent-pay-after-mice-and-flooding-complaints/|title=Students strike on rent pay after mice and flooding complaints|author=Joana Ramiro|date=8 May 2018|work=[[Left Foot Forward]]}}</ref>\n\n===Student housing===\n[[File:UCL Frances Gardner House.jpg|thumb|Frances Gardner House]]\n\n{{main|Halls of residence at University College London}}\nAll first-year undergraduate students and overseas first-year postgraduates at UCL are guaranteed university accommodation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/university-college-london/accommodation|title=University College London \u2013 Accommodation|accessdate=12 January 2013|publisher=The Complete University Guide}}</ref> The majority of second- and third-year undergraduate students and graduate students find their own accommodation in the private sector; graduate students and affiliate students may apply for accommodation but places are limited.\n\nUCL students are eligible to apply for places in the University of London intercollegiate halls of residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lon.ac.uk/halls.html |title=University of London \u2013 Intercollegiate Halls |publisher=University of London|date=26 March 2010 |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> The halls are: Canterbury Hall, Commonwealth Hall, College Hall, [[Connaught Hall, London|Connaught Hall]], [[Hughes Parry Hall, London|Hughes Parry Hall]] and [[International Hall, London|International Hall]] near [[Russell Square]] in [[Bloomsbury]]; Lillian Penson Hall in [[Paddington]]; and [[Nutford House, London|Nutford House]] in [[Marble Arch]]. Some students are also selected to live in [[International Students House, London|International Students House]].\n\nIn 2013, a new student accommodation building on [[Caledonian Road, London|Caledonian Road]] was awarded the [[Carbuncle Cup]] and named the country's worst new building by ''[[Building Design]]'' magazine, with the comment \"this is a building that the jury struggled to see as remotely fit for human occupation\". Islington Council had originally turned down planning permission for the building, but this had been overturned on appeal.<ref>{{cite news|work=BBC News|date=29 August 2013|title=Carbuncle Cup: UCL student block crowned worst building|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-london-23884446|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people associated with University College London}}\n{{See also|List of Nobel laureates affiliated with University College London|List of University College London people in the Law|School of Slavonic and East European Studies#Notable alumni and staff|Slade School of Fine Art#Notable alumni}}\n\nUCL alumni include [[Mahatma Gandhi]] (leader of the Indian independence moment and is considered the [[Father of the Nation|Father of the Nation of India]]), [[Alexander Graham Bell]] (inventor of the telephone), [[Francis Crick]] (co-discoverer of the structure of DNA), [[William Stanley Jevons]] (early pioneer of modern Economics), [[Jomo Kenyatta]] (\"Father of the Nation\" of Kenya), [[Kwame Nkrumah]] (founder of Ghana and \"Father of African Nationalism\") and [[Charles K. Kao]] (\"Godfather of [[broadband]]\"). Notable former staff include [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk]] (\"Father of the Nation\" of Czechoslovakia\"), [[Peter Higgs]] (proposer of the [[Higgs mechanism]] which predicted the existence of the [[Higgs boson]]), [[Lucien Freud]] (artist) and [[William Ramsay|Sir William Ramsay]] (discoverer of all of the naturally occurring noble gases).\n\nNobel Prizes have been awarded to [[List of Nobel laureates affiliated with University College London|at least 30 UCL academics and students]] (17 of which were in Physiology & Medicine), as well as three [[Fields Medal]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/facts |title=Facts and Figures |publisher=University College London |accessdate=26 April 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080822212403/http://www.ucl.ac.uk/about-ucl/facts |archivedate = 22 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/news-articles/0710/07100801 |title=20th Nobel Prize for UCL community |publisher=University College London |date=8 October 2007 |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n<gallery align=\"center\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Mohandas K. Gandhi, portrait.jpg| [[Mahatma Gandhi]]\nFile:Alexander Graham Bell.jpg| [[Alexander Graham Bell]]\nFile:Francis Crick 1995.jpg| [[Francis Crick]]\nFile:John Stuart Mill by London Stereoscopic Company, c1870.jpg| [[John Stuart Mill]]\nFile:Alfred Edward Housman.jpeg| [[A. E. Housman]]\nFile:Picture of jevons.jpg| [[William Stanley Jevons]]\nFile:Marie Stopes.jpg| [[Marie Stopes]]\nFile:Tagore3.jpg| [[Rabindranath Tagore]]\nFile:Gustav Holst.jpg|[[Gustav Holst]]\nFile:Lister Joseph.jpg| [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]]\nFile:Otto Hahn (Nobel).jpg| [[Otto Hahn]]\nFile:Nobel Prize 24 2013.jpg| [[Peter Higgs]]\nFile:Charles K. Kao cropped 2.jpg| [[Charles K. Kao]]\nFile:Demis Hassabis Royal Society.jpg| [[Demis Hassabis]]\nFile:Christopher Nolan, London, 2013 (crop).jpg| [[Christopher Nolan]]\nFile:Chris Martin of Coldplay.jpg| [[Chris Martin]]\nFile:Ricky Gervais 2010.jpg| [[Ricky Gervais]]\n</gallery>\n\n===Notable faculty and staff===\nNotable former UCL faculty and staff include [[Jocelyn Bell Burnell]] (co-discoverer of radio [[pulsars]]), [[A. S. Byatt]] (writer), [[Ronald Dworkin]] (legal philosopher and scholar of constitutional law),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/15/us/ronald-dworkin-legal-philosopher-dies-at-81.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Ronald Dworkin, Scholar of the Law, Is Dead at 81|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The New York Times|date=14 February 2013|first=Adam|last=Liptak}}</ref> [[John Austin (legal philosopher)|John Austin]] (legal philosopher, founder of [[legal positivism|analytical jurisprudence]]),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/Bentham-Project/who/bentham_ucl|title=Bentham and UCL|accessdate=24 May 2016|work=UCL|date=24 May 2016}}</ref> [[A.J. Ayer|Sir A.J. Ayer]] (philosopher), [[Sir Ambrose Fleming]] (inventor of the first thermionic valve, the fundamental building block of electronics),<ref>{{cite web|title=Sir John Ambrose Fleming|url= https://www.ee.ucl.ac.uk/about/history/fleming|website= UCL Department of Electronic & Electrical Engineering|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref> [[Lucian Freud]] (painter),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/art-obituaries/8653806/Lucian-Freud-OM.html|title=Lucian Freud, OM|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Telegraph|date=21 July 2011}}</ref> [[Andrew J Goldberg|Andrew J Goldberg OBE]] (Chairman of Medical Futures),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2011-06-uh-professor-commendation-medical-asthma.html|title=UH professor given commendation for medical innovation in asthma|access-date=2017-05-07}}</ref> [[Peter Higgs]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/life-and-physics/2010/sep/06/peter-higgs-boson|title=Peter Higgs, UCL and the Right Honorable William Waldegrave|accessdate=4 July 2012|work=The Guardian|date=7 September 2010|first=Jon|last=Butterworth}}</ref> (the proposer of the [[Higgs mechanism]], which predicted the existence of the [[Higgs boson]]), [[Andrew Huxley]] ([[physiology|physiologist]] and [[biophysics|biophysicist]]), [[William Stanley Jevons]] (economist), [[Frank Kermode|Sir Frank Kermode]] (literary critic), [[A. E. Housman]] (classical scholar, and poet), [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk]] (first [[List of Presidents of Czechoslovakia|President]] of [[Czechoslovakia]] and \"Father of the Nation\"), [[John Stuart Mill]] (philosopher), [[Peter T. Kirstein|Peter Kirstein CBE]] (computer scientist, significant role in the creation of the Internet), [[George R. Price]] ([[population genetics|population geneticist]]), [[Edward Teller]] (\"Father of the [[Hydrogen Bomb]]\"), [[David Kemp (physicist)|David Kemp]] (the first scientist to demonstrate the existence of the [[otoacoustic emission]]s)<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1978-11-01|title=Stimulated acoustic emissions from within the human auditory system|journal=The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America|volume=64|issue=5|pages=1386\u20131391|doi=10.1121/1.382104|issn=0001-4966|last1=Kemp|first1=D. T.|pmid=744838}}</ref> and [[Dadabhai Naoroji]] (Indian Parsi leader, the first Asian to be elected to UK House of Commons).\n\n[[File:William Bayliss 1918b.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William Bayliss]], co-discoverer of [[Secretin]], the first identified hormone]]\nAll five of the naturally occurring [[noble gases]] were discovered at UCL by Professor of Chemistry [[William Ramsay|Sir William Ramsay]], after whom Ramsay Hall is named.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chemeducator.org/sbibs/s0009006/spapers/960378gk.htm |title=Sir William Ramsay: Noble Gas Pioneer\u2014On the 100th Anniversary of His Nobel Prize |publisher=Chemeducator.org |accessdate=26 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504073746/http://chemeducator.org/sbibs/s0009006/spapers/960378gk.htm |archivedate=4 May 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHormones were first discovered at UCL by [[William Bayliss]] and [[Ernest Starling]], the former also an alumnus of UCL.<ref name=\"Tata 490\u2013496\">{{Cite journal| last = Tata| first = Jamshed R.| date = 2005-06-01| title = One hundred years of hormones| journal = EMBO Reports| volume = 6| issue = 6| pages = 490\u2013496| doi = 10.1038/sj.embor.7400444| issn = 1469-221X| pmc = 1369102| pmid = 15940278}}</ref>\n\n===Notable alumni===\nNotable UCL alumni include:\n\n* '''Artists''' including [[William Coldstream|Sir William Coldstream]] (realist painter), [[Wyndham Lewis]] (vorticist painter), [[Antony Gormley]] (sculptor), [[Augustus John]] (painter, draughtsman and etcher),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/arts/sites/augustus-john/|title=Augustus John|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref> [[Gerry Judah]] (artist and designer), [[Ben Nicholson]] (abstract painter), [[Eduardo Paolozzi|Sir Eduardo Paolozzi]] (sculptor and artist) and [[Ibrahim el-Salahi]] (artist painter and former diplomat);\n* '''Authors''' including [[Edith Clara Batho]], [[Raymond Briggs]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2004/dec/18/featuresreviews.guardianreview8|title=Profile: Raymond Briggs|accessdate=29 May 2013|work=The Guardian|date=18 December 2004|first=Nicholas|last=Wroe}}</ref> [[Robert Browning]], [[G. K. Chesterton]],<ref name=tele20612>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/6440409/University-College-London-halls-of-high-distinction.html|title=University College London: halls of high distinction |accessdate=20 June 2012|work=The Telegraph|date=27 October 2009|first=Max|last=Davidson}}</ref> [[David Crystal]], [[Stella Gibbons]], [[Clive Sansom]], [[Tom Knox (author)|Sean Thomas]], [[Marie Stopes]],<ref name=tele20612/> [[Helen MacInnes]], [[Chioma Okereke]], [[Rabindranath Tagore]] and [[Demetrius Vikelas]] (who was also the first [[Presidents of the International Olympic Committee|President of the International Olympic Committee]]) and [[Marianne Winder]];\n* '''Business-oriented people''' including [[Colin Chapman]] (founder of [[Lotus Cars]]),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/news/2749326/Lotus-fleet-turns-out-for-Colin-Chapman-tribute.html|title=Lotus fleet turns out for Colin Chapman tribute|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Telegraph|date=3 November 2007}}</ref> [[Demis Hassabis]] (co-founder and CEO of [[DeepMind]]), [[Lord Digby Jones]] (former Director-General of the [[Confederation of British Industry]]),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2004/sep/12/theobserver.observerbusiness12|title=The CBI's megaphone man|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Guardian|date=12 September 2004|first=Oliver|last=Morgan}}</ref> [[Edwin Waterhouse]] (founding partner of the professional services firm [[PwC]]) and billionaire [[Farhad Moshiri]] (Everton F.C part owner).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/feb/28/everton-majority-shareholder-farhad-moshiri-increase-stake-bill-kenwright|title=Everton's new majority shareholder Farhad Moshiri likely to increase stake|last=Hunter|first=Andy|date=2016-02-28|website=the Guardian|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n* '''Medical researchers and specialists''' including [[Archie Cochrane]] (medic, researcher, and pioneer of evidence-based medicine),<ref name=\"Cochrane Org History\">{{cite web |title= Archie Cochrane: The name behind Cochrane |url= http://www.cochrane.org/about-us/history/archie-cochrane |publisher= [[Cochrane Collaboration]] |date= 5 December 2013 |website= www.cochrane.org |accessdate= 10 September 2014}}</ref> [[Terence Coderre]] (Professor of Medicine and Harold Griffith Chair in Anaesthesia Research at [[McGill University]]), [[Jane Dacre]] (current President of the [[Royal College of Physicians]]), [[Jeremy Farrar]] (current Director of the [[Wellcome Trust]]), [[Clare Gerada]] (previous President of the [[Royal College of General Practitioners]]), [[Marc Tessier-Lavigne]] (current president of [[Stanford University]]), [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]] (pioneer of antiseptic surgery), [[Barbara Low]] (founder member of the [[British Psychoanalytical Society]]) and [[Clare Marx]] (current President of the [[Royal College of Surgeons of England]]).\n[[File:Alexander Graham Bell.jpeg|thumb|upright|[[Alexander Graham Bell]]]]\n* '''Engineers and scientists''' including [[Alexander Graham Bell]] (inventor of the telephone),<ref name=tele20612/> [[Francis Crick]] (co-discoverer of the structure of DNA),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/medicine-obituaries/5796359/Francis-Crick-OM.html|title=Obituary: Francis Crick, OM|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Telegraph|date=30 July 2004}}</ref> [[Hans Eysenck]] (psychologist who created the modern scientific theory of personality),<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gray |first=Jeffrey |title= Obituary Hans Jurgen Eysenck (1916\u201397) |journal= Nature |volume=389 |issue=6653 |year=2009 |page=794 |doi=10.1038/39755|pmid=9349806 }}</ref> [[John Ambrose Fleming]] (inventor of the vacuum tube), [[David Jewitt]] (co-discoverer of the Kuiper belt), [[Jaroslav Heyrovsk\u00fd]] (father of the electroanalytical method) and [[Charles Kuen Kao]] (pioneer of the use of fibre optics in telecommunications),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.cctv.com/program/newshour/20091211/102890.shtml|title=Charles Kuen Kao receives Nobel Prize|accessdate=20 April 2013|publisher=CCTV|date=11 December 2009}}</ref> [[Donald Prell]] (psychologist and [[Futurologist]]), [[Arthur Blok]] (first administrative head of the [[Technion \u2013 Israel Institute of Technology]]), and [[Israel Dostrovsky]] (Israeli physical chemist and fifth president of the [[Weizmann Institute of Science]]).  \n* '''Entertainers, musicians, composers and filmmakers''' including [[Ken Adam]] (designer famous for set designs for the [[James Bond films]]), [[Brett Anderson]] (lead singer of the band [[Suede (band)|Suede]]), [[Justine Frischmann]] (lead singer of the band [[Elastica]]), [[Ricky Gervais]] (comedian and actor),<ref name=tele20612/> [[Gustav Holst]] (composer), all of the members of the band [[Coldplay]] ([[Chris Martin]], [[Jonny Buckland]], [[Guy Berryman]] and [[Will Champion]]),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2004/sep/13/highereducation.popandrock|title=Hours of Idleness|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Guardian|date=13 September 2004|first=John|last=Sutherland|authorlink=John Sutherland (author)}}</ref> [[Christopher Nolan]] (director of films including ''The Dark Knight saga''),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/filmblog/2011/feb/24/inception-christopher-nolan-film-oscar-director|title=I was there at the Inception of Christopher Nolan's film career|accessdate=18 August 2012|work=The Guardian|date=24 February 2011|first=Matthew|last=Tempest}}</ref> [[Franny Armstrong]] (director), [[Tim Rice-Oxley]] and [[Richard Hughes (musician)|Richard Hughes]] (members of the band [[Keane (band)|Keane]]), and [[Jonathan Ross (television presenter)|Jonathan Ross]] (television presenter);\n* '''Journalists and commentators''' including [[A. A. Gill]] (columnist), three former editors of ''[[The Economist]]'', most notably [[Walter Bagehot]], two editors of ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', [[Jonathan Dimbleby]] (television and radio current affairs presenter),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jun/07/jonathan-dimbleby-bbc-trust-interview|title=Jonathan Dimbleby: BBC's culture of compliance is 'extremely damaging'|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Guardian|date=7 June 2010|first=Ben|last=Dowell}}</ref> [[Roly Drower]] (satirist and activist), [[Tom Dyckhoff]] (architecture critic and TV presenter),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gloucestershireecho.co.uk/TV-architecture-critic-Tom-Dyckhoff-Cheltenham/story-20823790-detail/story.html|date=18 March 2014|title=TV architecture critic Tom Dyckhoff to give Cheltenham Civic Society annual lecture|newspaper=Gloucestershire Echo|accessdate=14 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416192752/http://www.gloucestershireecho.co.uk/TV-architecture-critic-Tom-Dyckhoff-Cheltenham/story-20823790-detail/story.html|archive-date=16 April 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> former ITN Home Affairs Correspondent [[Sarah Cullen]] and [[Simon Inglis]] (architectural historian and sports writer);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playedinbritain.co.uk/author-simon-inglis.php|title=Played in Britain \u2013 Authors \u2013 Simon Inglis|website=www.playedinbritain.co.uk}}</ref>\n* '''Politicians''' including [[Mahatma Gandhi]] (leader of the Indian independence movement),<ref name=tele20612/> [[Jomo Kenyatta]] (first Prime Minister, first President and \"Father of the Nation\" of Kenya),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/2008/6/20/the-big-read|title=Jomo Kenyatta: emblematic figure of the Independence Movement|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=Daily Observer|date=20 June 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530222404/http://observer.gm/africa/gambia/article/2008/6/20/the-big-read|archivedate=30 May 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Kwame Nkrumah]] (first Prime Minister, President and \"Founder\" of Ghana and \"Father\" of African Nationalism),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.modernghana.com/news/236431/1/nkrumahs-birthday-declared-a-holiday.html|title=Nkrumah's birthday declared a holiday|accessdate=4 September 2009|publisher=Modern Ghana|date=8 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Birmingham|first1=David|title=Kwame Nkrumah : the father of African nationalism|date=1998|publisher=Ohio Univ. Press|location=Athens|isbn=978-0821412428|edition=Rev.}}</ref> [[Sir Seewoosagur Ramgoolam]] (first Prime Minister and \"Father of the Nation\" of Mauritius),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mauritiusnews.co.uk/component/content/article/13-history/43-18-september-2010-commemorating-the-saint-of-mauritius-and-the-father-of-the-nation|title=Commemorating the Saint of Mauritius and the Father of the Nation|accessdate=17 July 2013|publisher=Mauritius News|date=8 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915144916/http://mauritiusnews.co.uk/component/content/article/13-history/43-18-september-2010-commemorating-the-saint-of-mauritius-and-the-father-of-the-nation |archivedate=15 September 2010 }}</ref> [[Chaim Herzog]] (former [[President of Israel]]), [[Sir Abubakar Tafawa Balewa]] (first Prime Minister of Nigeria),<ref>{{cite web|title=Sir Abubakar Tafawa Balewa|url=http://www.britannica.com/biography/Abubakar-Tafawa-Balewa|website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=23 July 2015}}</ref> [[It\u014d Hirobumi]] (first [[Prime Minister of Japan]]),<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reisz|first1=Matthew|title=The pioneering foreign students who rebuilt Japan|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/the-pioneering-foreign-students-who-rebuilt-japan/2005081.article|website=Times Higher Education|accessdate=23 July 2015}}</ref> [[Junichiro Koizumi]] (former Prime Minister of Japan),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-09-11-koizumi-profile_x.htm|title=Reform leader has thoroughly traditional background|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=USA Today|date=11 September 2005}}</ref> [[Wu Tingfang]] (Acting Premier during the early years of the Republic of China), and [[Sir Stafford Cripps]] (former [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]]);\n* '''Lawyers''' including a Lord Chancellor ([[Lord Herschell]]); Chief Justices of England ([[Lord Woolf]]),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2004/jun/17/highereducation.administration|title=UCL appoints Lord Woolf to ruling council|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Guardian|date=17 June 2004|first=Polly|last=Curtis}}</ref> Hong Kong (Sir [[William Meigh Goodman]], and Sir [[Yang Ti-liang]]), the British Supreme Court for China and Japan (Sir [[Nicholas John Hannen]]), India ([[A. S. Anand]]), Malaysia ([[Arifin Zakaria]]), Nigeria ([[Taslim Olawale Elias]]), Ghana ([[Samuel Azu Crabbe]]), The Straits Settlements (Sir [[G. Aubrey Goodman]]) and the Eastern Caribbean Supreme Court (Rt. Hon. Sir [[Vincent Floissac]]); two Masters of the Rolls ([[Herbert Cozens-Hardy, 1st Baron Cozens-Hardy|Lord Cozens-Hardy]] and Sir [[George Jessel (jurist)|George Jessel]]); a permanent judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong]], [[Joseph Fok]]; and Attorneys-General of England ([[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|Lord Goldsmith]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6232764.stm|title=Lord Goldsmith: Profile|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Guardian|date=23 June 2007}}</ref> and [[Baroness Scotland]]), Singapore ([[Tan Boon Teik]] and [[Chao Hick Tin]]), Hong Kong ([[Thomas Chisholm Anstey]]), [[Gambia]] ([[Hassan Bubacar Jallow]]) and [[Sri Lanka]] ([[Dappula de Livera]]);\n* '''Sports people''' including [[David Gower]] (former captain of the England cricket team),<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/153488.article|title=No smarter than an ox?|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=Times Higher Education|date=22 September 2000}}</ref> [[Patrick Head]] (co-founder of the Williams Formula One team)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tomcary/100022807/patrick-heads-exit-stage-left-represents-another-break-with-the-past/|title=Patrick Head's exit stage left another break with the past as F1 enters 2012|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Telegraph|date=2 January 2012}}</ref> and [[Christine Ohuruogu]] (Olympic and World [[400 metres]] gold medalist);<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/passedfailed-an-education-in-the-life-of-the-olympic-gold-medallist-christine-ohuruogu-1716791.html|title=Passed/Failed: An education in the life of the Olympic gold medallist Christine Ohuruogu|accessdate=20 April 2013|work=The Independent|date=25 June 2009}}</ref> and\n* '''Statisticians''' including [[Karl Pearson]] (founder of the world's first university statistics department at UCL)<ref>{{cite web|title=Department History|url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/statistics/department/history|website=UCL Department of Statistical Science|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> and [[Kirstine Smith]] (credited with the creation of [[optimal design]] of experiments).<ref name=GL2009>{{cite journal |last=Guttorp |first=P. |last2=Lindgren |first2=G. |title= Karl Pearson and the Scandinavian school of statistics |journal= International Statistical Review |volume=77 |year=2009 |page=64 |doi=10.1111/j.1751-5823.2009.00069.x|url=http://www.stat.washington.edu/people/peter/history/KP.pdf |citeseerx=10.1.1.368.8328 }}</ref>\n* '''Religious figures''' including [[Francis Lyon Cohen]], the first Jewish chaplain in the [[British Army]],<ref name=Jencyc>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/4473-cohen-francis-lyon|title=COHEN, FRANCIS LYON - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=www.jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref> and [[Michael Adler]], first Jewish chaplain to serve in a Theatre of War.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/827-adler-michael|title=ADLER, MICHAEL - JewishEncyclopedia.com|website=www.jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref><ref>Arthur Barnett, 'The Rev. Michael Adler, D.S.O., S.C.F., B.A. (1868\u20141944)' \u2013 Transactions (Jewish Historical Society of England) Vol. 15 (1939\u20131945), pp. 191\u2013194</ref>\n\n===Heads of state, government and international organisations===\n<gallery align=\"center\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Ito Hirobumi as President of Rikken Seiyu Kai in 1903.jpg| [[It\u014d Hirobumi]]\nFile:Jomo Kenyatta.jpg| [[Jomo Kenyatta]]\nFile:Koizumi 2010 cropped.png| [[Junichiro Koizumi]]\nFile:Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk cph.3a46477.jpg| [[Tom\u00e1\u0161 G. Masaryk]]\nFile:Kwame Nkrumah (JFKWHP-AR6409-A).jpg| [[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n</gallery>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float: center; border: 5px solid #BBB; margin: .96em 0 0 .9em;\"\n|- \n!State/government !! Individual !! Office\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Barbados}}''\n|[[Elliott Belgrave|Sir Elliott Belgrave]]\n|[[Governor-General of Barbados|Governor-General]] (2011\u2013)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Barbados}}''\n|[[Harold Bernard St. John|Sir Bernard St. John]]\n|[[Prime Minister of Barbados|Prime Minister]] (1985\u20131986)\n|-\n|''{{flagicon image|Commonwealth Flag, 2013.svg}}'' ''Commonwealth of Nations''\n|[[Patricia Scotland|Baroness Patricia Scotland]]\n|[[Secretary General of the Commonwealth|Secretary General]] (2016\u2013)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Council of Europe}}''\n|[[Terry Davis (politician)|Terry Davis]]\n|[[Secretary General of the Council of Europe|Secretary General]] (2004\u20132009)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Cyprus}}''\n|[[Nicos Anastasiades|Nicos Anastasiades {{small|(\u039d\u03af\u03ba\u03bf\u03c2 \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03ac\u03b4\u03b7\u03c2)}}]]\n|[[President of Cyprus|President]] (2013\u2013)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovakia}}''\n|[[Tom\u00e1\u0161 Garrigue Masaryk]]\n| First [[President of Czechoslovakia|President]] (1918\u20131935)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Ghana}}''\n|[[Kwame Nkrumah]]\n|First Prime Minister of the [[Gold Coast (British colony)|Gold Coast]], first [[Prime Minister of Ghana|Prime Minister]], first [[President of Ghana|President]] (1952\u20131966)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Israel}}''\n|[[Chaim Herzog|Chaim Herzog {{small|(\u05d7\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd \u05d4\u05e8\u05e6\u05d5\u05d2)}}]]\n|[[President of Israel|President]] (1983\u20131993)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Japan}}''\n|[[It\u014d Hirobumi|It\u014d Hirobumi {{small|(\u4f0a\u85e4 \u535a\u6587)}}]]\n|First [[Prime Minister of Japan|Prime Minister]] (1885\u20131888, 1892\u20131896, 1898, 1900\u20131901)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Japan}}''\n|[[Junichiro Koizumi|Junichiro Koizumi {{small|(\u5c0f\u6cc9\u7d14\u4e00\u90ce)}}]]\n|Prime Minister (2001\u20132006)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Kenya}}''\n|[[Jomo Kenyatta]]\n|First [[Prime Minister of Kenya|Prime Minister]], first [[President of Kenya|President]] (1963\u20131978)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Mauritius}}''\n|[[Seewoosagur Ramgoolam|Sir Seewoosagur Ramgoolam]]\n|Chief Minister of [[British Mauritius]], first [[Prime Minister of Mauritius|Prime Minister]] (1961\u20131982), [[Governor-General of Mauritius|Governor-General]] (1983\u20131985)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Nigeria}}''\n|[[Sir Abubakar Tafawa Balewa]]\n|First [[Prime Minister of Nigeria|Prime Minister]] (1960\u20131966)\n|-\n|''{{flagicon image|Flag of Queensland.svg}}'' ''Queensland''\n|[[Charles Lilley|Sir Charles Lilley]]\n|[[Premier of Queensland|Premier]] (1868\u20131870)\n|-\n|''{{flagicon image|Flag of the Republic of China 1912-1928.svg}}'' ''Republic of China''\n|[[Wu Tingfang|Wu Tingfang {{small|(\u4f0d\u5ef7\u82b3)}}]]\n|[[Premier of the Republic of China|Premier]] (1917)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Romania}}''\n|[[Mihai R\u0103zvan Ungureanu]]\n|[[Prime Minister of Romania|Prime Minister]] (2012)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Saint Lucia}}\n|[[Vincent Floissac|Sir Vincent Floissac]]\n|[[Governor-General of Saint Lucia|Governor-General]] (1987\u20131988)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Trinidad and Tobago}}''\n|[[Ellis Clarke|Sir Ellis Clarke]]\n|[[Governor-General of Trinidad and Tobago|Governor-General]], first [[President of Trinidad and Tobago|President]] (1972\u20131987)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Turks and Caicos Islands}}''\n|[[Martin Bourke]]\n|[[Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands|Governor]] (1993\u20131996)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|Uganda}}''\n|[[Benedicto Kiwanuka]]\n|Chief Minister of the [[Uganda Protectorate]] (1961\u20131962), first [[Prime Minister of Uganda|Prime Minister]] (1962)\n|-\n|''{{flagu|United Nations}}''\n|[[Angie Brooks]]\n|[[President of the United Nations General Assembly]] (1969\u20131970)\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |last1=Bellot |first1=H. Hale |authorlink=Hugh Hale Bellot |title=University College, London 1826\u20131926 |date=1929 |publisher=University of London Press |place=London }}\n*{{cite book |first1=Negley |last1=Harte |first2=John |last2=North |first3=Georgina |last3=Brewis |title=The World of UCL |place=London |publisher=UCL Press |year=2018 |edition=4th |isbn=978-1-78735-294-0 |url=https://www.ucl.ac.uk/ucl-press/browse-books/the-world-of-ucl }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|University College London}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.senatehouselibrary.ac.uk/our-collections/special-collections/archives-manuscripts/university-of-london-students-1836-1934 Lists of UCL students who graduated over 80 years ago, 1836\u2013]\n* [http://www.senatehouselibrary.ac.uk/our-collections/special-collections/archives-manuscripts/university-of-london-military-service-1914-1945 UCL military personnel, 1914\u20131918]\n\n{{University College London|state=expanded|academics}}\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{University of London}}\n{{UCL Partners}}\n{{Francis Crick Institute}}\n{{Universities and colleges in London}}\n{{Universities in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Universities Research Association}}\n{{League of European Research Universities}}\n{{Russell Group}}\n{{European Network for Training Economic Research}