ions          = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| profession         = \n| known_for          = \n| cabinet            = \n| committees         = \n| portfolio          = \n| religion           = \n| awards             =  <!-- For civilian awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |mawards= is not set -->\n| blank1             = \n| data1              = \n| blank2             = \n| data2              = \n| blank3             = \n| data3              = \n| blank4             = \n| data4              = \n| blank5             = \n| data5              = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| website            = \n<!--Military service-->\n| nickname           = \n| allegiance         = \n| branch             = \n| serviceyears       = \n| rank               = \n| unit               = \n| commands           = \n| battles            = \n| mawards            =  <!-- for military awards - appears as \"Awards\" if |awards= is not set -->\n| military_blank1    = \n| military_data1     = \n| military_blank2    = \n| military_data2     = \n| military_blank3    = \n| military_data3     = \n| military_blank4    = \n| military_data4     = \n| military_blank5    = \n| military_data5     = \n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Abdul Hadi Arghandiwal''' (born 1952) is [[Afghanistan|Afghanistan's]] Minister of Economy, and the Head of [[Hezb-i Islami Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Starkey|first=Jerome|title=Man with the money Charlie Wilson unleashed a monster|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/article7024135.ece|accessdate=1 July 2010|newspaper=Times Online|date=12 February 2010}}</ref> He was once allied with Islamist warlord [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]], but in 2008 he was elected chairman of a moderate breakaway faction of [[Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin|Hekmatyar's party]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FACTBOX-Who are Karzai's new cabinet picks? |url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/SGE60801N.htm |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=9 Jan 2010 |accessdate=2010-09-22 }}</ref>\n\nAbdul Hadi Arghandiwal earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in economics, before working at the planning ministry in 1977 and then he went to USA. Back in Afghanistan, he fled from the [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|civil war]] to [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/en/government/?pn=60 |title=Cabinet Biographies |accessdate=2010-09-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Embassy of Afghanistan in Tokyo| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101009101829/http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/en/government/?pn=60| archivedate= 9 October 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as Finance Minister in 1996. Arghandiwal has also served as advisor to President [[Hamid Karzai]] over tribal affairs. On January 16, 2010, he was appointed as Minister of Economy by gaining a vote of confidence from the [[Afghan Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Karzai studying peace offer from militant group|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9EK5LE04.htm|work=Businessweek|accessdate=1 July 2010|author=Riechmann, Deb|author2=Faiez, Rahim}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=O'Donnell|first=Lynne|title=Afghan parliament set to vote on second cabinet list|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/afghan-parliament-set-to-vote-on-second-cabinet-list-20100116-mdam.html|accessdate=1 July 2010|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=16 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arghandiwal, Abdul Hadi}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Afghan expatriates in Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Afghanistan-politician