ate breakaway faction of [[Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin|Hekmatyar's party]].<ref>{{cite news |title=FACTBOX-Who are Karzai's new cabinet picks? |url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/SGE60801N.htm |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=9 Jan 2010 |accessdate=2010-09-22 }}</ref>\n\nAbdul Hadi Arghandiwal earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in economics, before working at the planning ministry in 1977and then he went to USA When the [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|civil war]] broke out he fled to [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/en/government/?pn=60 |title=Cabinet Biographies |accessdate=2010-09-22 |year=2010 |publisher=Embassy of Afghanistan in Tokyo| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101009101829/http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/en/government/?pn=60| archivedate= 9 October 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as Finance Minister in 1996. Arghandiwal has also served as advisor to President [[Hamid Karzai]] over tribal affairs. On January 16, 2010, he was appointed as Minister of Economy by gaining vote of Confidence from the [[Afghan Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Karzai studying peace offer from militant group|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9EK5LE04.htm|work=Businessweek|accessdate=1 July 2010|author=Riechmann, Deb|author2=Faiez, Rahim}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=O'Donnell|first=Lynne|title=Afghan parliament set to vote on second cabinet list|url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/afghan-parliament-set-to-vote-on-second-cabinet-list-20100116-mdam.html|accessdate=1 July 2010|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=16 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arghandiwal, Abdul Hadi}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Afghan expatriates in Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Afghanistan-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Derim Hunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdul_Hadi_Arghandiwal"}
{"title_page": "Sauromatum", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n|image=Sauromatum foglia03.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Sauromatum venosum''\n|display_parents = 2\n|taxon = Sauromatum\n|authority = Schott \n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=wcsp/>\n|synonyms = *''Diversiarum'' <small>J.Murata & Ohi-Toma</small>\n*''Hirsutiarum'' <small>J.Murata & Ohi-Toma</small>\n*''Pedatyphonium'' <small>J.Murata & Ohi-Toma</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Sauromatum''''' is a [[genus]] of flowering plants in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Araceae]]. The genus is native to tropical [[Africa]], tropical [[Asia]], and the [[Arabian Peninsula]].<ref name=wcsp>http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=186368</ref><ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=129334 Flora of China Vol. 23 Page 36, <big>\u6591\u9f99\u828b\u5c5e</big> ban long yu shu, ''Sauromatum'' Schott in Schott & Endlicher, Melet. Bot. 17. 1832. ]</ref> Their [[inflorescence]]s last for only a few hours to a day and give off an unpleasant smell. The inflorescence disperses its odor by heating up.<ref>Brown, Deni (2000). ''Aroids: Plants of the Arum Family''. Timber Press. {{ISBN|0-88192-485-7}}.</ref>\n\n;Species<ref name=wcsp/>\n#''[[Sauromatum brevipes]]'' <small>(Hook.f.) N.E.Br.</small> - Tibet, Nepal, Bhutan, Assam\n#''[[Sauromatum brevipilosum]]'' <small>(Hett. & Sizemore) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Sumatra\n#''[[Sauromatum diversifolium]]'' <small>(Wall. ex Schott) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - eastern Himalayas, Tibet, Sichuan, Yunnan, Nepal, Bhutan, Assam, Myanmar, Cambodia\n#''[[Sauromatum gaoligongense]]'' <small>J.C.Wang & H.Li</small> - Yunnan\n#''[[Sauromatum giganteum]]'' <small>(Engl.) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Anhui, Gansu, Hebei, Henan, Jilin, Liaoning, Shandong, Shanxi, Sichuan, Tibet\n#''[[Sauromatum guttatum]]'' <small>H. W. Schott</small> - type of the name ''Sauromatum'', Nepal\n#''[[Sauromatum hirsutum]]'' <small>(S.Y.Hu) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Yunnan, Laos, Thailand, Vietnam\n#''[[Sauromatum horsfieldii]]'' <small>Miq.</small> - Guangxi, Guizhou, Sichuan, Yunnan, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, Sumatra, Java, Bali\n#''[[Sauromatum tentaculatum]]'' <small>(Hett.) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Thailand\n#''[[Sauromatum venosum]]'' <small>(Dryand. ex Aiton) Kunth</small> - tropical Africa from Ethiopia south to Mozambique and west to Cameroon; Yemen, Saudi Arabia; Indian Subcontinent; Myanmar; Tibet, Yunnan\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3529324}}\n\n[[Category:Aroideae]]\n[[Category:Araceae genera]]\n\n\n{{Araceae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n|image=Sauromatum foglia03.jpg\n|image_caption = ''Sauromatum venosum''\n|display_parents = 2\n|taxon = Sauromatum\n|authority = Schott \n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=wcsp/>\n|synonyms = *''Diversiarum'' <small>J.Murata & Ohi-Toma</small>\n*''Hirsutiarum'' <small>J.Murata & Ohi-Toma</small>\n*''Pedatyphonium'' <small>J.Murata & Ohi-Toma</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Sauromatum''''' is a [[genus]] of flowering plants in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Araceae]]. The genus is native to tropical [[Africa]], tropical [[Asia]], and the [[Arabian Peninsula]].<ref name=wcsp>http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=186368</ref><ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=129334 Flora of China Vol. 23 Page 36, <big>\u6591\u9f99\u828b\u5c5e</big> ban long yu shu, ''Sauromatum'' Schott in Schott & Endlicher, Melet. Bot. 17. 1832. ]</ref> Their [[inflorescence]]s last for only a few hours to a day and give off an unpleasant smell. The inflorescence disperses its odor by heating up.<ref>Brown, Deni (2000). ''Aroids: Plants of the Arum Family''. Timber Press. {{ISBN|0-88192-485-7}}.</ref>\n\n;Species<ref name=wcsp/>\n#''[[Sauromatum brevipes]]'' <small>(Hook.f.) N.E.Br.</small> - Tibet, Nepal, Bhutan, Assam\n#''[[Sauromatum brevipilosum]]'' <small>(Hett. & Sizemore) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Sumatra\n#''[[Sauromatum diversifolium]]'' <small>(Wall. ex Schott) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - eastern Himalayas, Tibet, Sichuan, Yunnan, Nepal, Bhutan, Assam, Myanmar, Cambodia\n#''[[Sauromatum gaoligongense]]'' <small>J.C.Wang & H.Li</small> - Yunnan\n#''[[Sauromatum giganteum]]'' <small>(Engl.) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Anhui, Gansu, Hebei, Henan, Jilin, Liaoning, Shandong, Shanxi, Sichuan, Tibet\n#''[[Sauromatum hirsutum]]'' <small>(S.Y.Hu) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Yunnan, Laos, Thailand, Vietnam\n#''[[Sauromatum horsfieldii]]'' <small>Miq.</small> - Guangxi, Guizhou, Sichuan, Yunnan, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam, Sumatra, Java, Bali\n#''[[Sauromatum tentaculatum]]'' <small>(Hett.) Cusimano & Hett.</small> - Thailand\n#''[[Sauromatum venosum]]'' <small>(Dryand. ex Aiton) Kunth</small> - tropical Africa from Ethiopia south to Mozambique and west to Cameroon; Yemen, Saudi Arabia; Indian Subcontinent; Myanmar; Tibet, Yunnan\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3529324}}\n\n[[Category:Aroideae]]\n[[Category:Araceae genera]]\n\n\n{{Araceae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "RennerSS", "label": "safe", "comment": "Type of the genus added - that species MUST be included by the rules of nomenclature", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sauromatum"}
{"title_page": "Mysore Manjunath", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n [[File:Mysore Manjunath violinist.jpg|thumb|Dr.Mysore Manjunath]] \n'''Mysore Manjunath'''  is an [[India]]n violinist.<ref>https://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref> The son and disciple of violinist Prof. Mahadevappa, Manjunath performed his first concert at the age of 8 in [[Mysore]] as a [[child prodigy]] storming in to the music world <ref>http://indiaepost.com/2018/07/29/world-renowned-violinist-dr-mysore-manjunath-to-perform-at-the-educational-institutes-in-dehradun-from-august-1-to-august-4-2018/</ref> Trained under his father, Manjunath,<ref>http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040828/saturday/main1.htm</ref> and brother Mysore Nagaraj, received special coaching in violin technique and improvisation. He is one of the [[Mysore brothers]] duo enthralling audiences around the world with his mellifluous music and astounding mastery of the violin <ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/549183/twice-prowess.html</ref>. He is honored with the prestigious [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] Award by Govt. of India,bestowed by the Hon. President of India at The [[Rashtrapathi Bhavan]] in New Delhi<ref> https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref>.\n\n\n\n==Education==\nManjunath did his Master of Music at the [[University of Mysore]] securing first Rank with 4 Gold Medals and was awarded Ph.D by the University of Mysore.<ref>https://www.news18.com/news/india/a-sonorous-journey-by-violin-maestros-377583.html</ref><ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/honour-for-mysores-violin-maestros/article5665242.ece</ref>\n\n==Career==\nManjunath started performing at 8 and his initial concerts were with his father and brother.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/raised-to-the-power-of-two/article27546520.ece</ref> He regularly performs along with his elder brother Mysore Nagaraj.<ref>http://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref>  His violin concerts are featured at major international concert stages including [[Royal Albert Hall]] - [[London]], [[Sydney Opera House]] - [[Australia]], International Violin Conference, Common Thread Music festival in [[United States]], [[Federation Square]] in [[Melbourne]], World Music Festival<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MVVSJL7k9ls</ref> in [[Chicago]],<ref>http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/zakir-hussain-niladri-kumar-open-chicago-world-music-festival</ref> [[Oxford University]]<ref>https://www.music.ox.ac.uk/event/the-mysore-brothers-2/</ref>, Tansen Sangith Samaroh-Gwalior,Esplanade Theatre in Singapore, World Music Series by [[BBC]], [[Santa-Fe Festival]]<ref>http://www.sfreporter.com/santafe/article-1735-performing-arts-books-june-27-july-3.html</ref> in [[New Mexico]],Persian Academy of Culture in [[Iran]] Doverlane Music Festival in Kolkata, [[India International Centre]]<ref>http://www.iicdelhi.in/webcasts/view_webcast/carnatic-violin-duet-by-the-mysore-brothers-/</ref>.  He has collaborated with musicians and orchestras including [[Ned McGowan]], [[Fabrizio Cassol]], Jai Uttal,  Joe Craven, Fred Hamilton, Todd Haaby, Pandith [[Vishwa Mohan Bhatt]], [[Ronu Majumdar]], [[N. Rajam]], Tejendra Majumdar such as [[Aka Moon]],<ref>http://www.akamoon.com/index.php?id=159{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Spenifex,<ref>http://www.womex.com/virtual/spinifex</ref> [[Ictus Ensemble|Ictus]].\n\nHe was nominated as cultural ambassador of University of Mysore.<ref>http://www.bangalorefirst.in/?p=13376</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nHe is one of the youngest recipients of the [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]]<ref>https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref> award by the [[Government of India]] and the [[Rajyotsava Award]] by the Government of [[Karnataka]].<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/2003/10/31/stories/2003103101770600.htm</ref> He has received the Excellence award from [[American Institute of World Culture]], honours from the [[American Arts Council]], Best Violinist awards from The [[Music Academy]], Best Violinist award from the Indian fine arts society, Aryabhata Award, Meritorious Award from [[University of Oklahoma]]-USA,  Samskruthi Sinchana Award, Y.T.Tatachari National Award, Sangeeth Samrat, Sangeeth Rathna, Sangitha Vidwanmani, Gana varidhi, Tantri Vadya Shiromani - Asthana Vidwan from [[Sri Kanchi Kamakoti Peetham]], [[Chowdiah National Award]] by Academy of Music,<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/honour-for-musicians/article4132242.ece</ref> Rotary Excellence Award & Rama Ganakalacharya<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/mysore-brothers-to-receive-rama-gana-kalacharya-award/article23531128.ece</ref>, Sangeetha Vedanta Dhurina<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/honour-for-mysores-violin-maestros/article5665242.ece</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mysoremanjunath.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manjunath, Mysore}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Carnatic violinists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mysore]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Indian male classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Rajyotsava Award 2003]]\n[[Category:21st-century violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n [[File:Mysore Manjunath violinist.jpg|thumb|Dr.Mysore Manjunath]] \n'''Mysore Manjunath'''  is an [[India]]n violinist.<ref>https://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref> The son and disciple of violinist Prof. Mahadevappa, Manjunath performed his first concert at the age of 8 in [[Mysore]] as a [[child prodigy]] storming in to the music world <ref>http://indiaepost.com/2018/07/29/world-renowned-violinist-dr-mysore-manjunath-to-perform-at-the-educational-institutes-in-dehradun-from-august-1-to-august-4-2018/</ref> Trained under his father, Manjunath,<ref>http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040828/saturday/main1.htm</ref> and brother Mysore Nagaraj, received special coaching in violin technique and improvisation. He is one of the [[Mysore brothers]] duo enthralling audiences around the world with his mellifluous music and astounding mastery of the violin <ref>https://www.deccanherald.com/content/549183/twice-prowess.html</ref>. He is honored with the prestigious [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]] Award by Govt. of India,bestowed by the Hon. President of India at The [[Rashtrapathi Bhavan]] in New Delhi<ref> https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref>.\n\n\n\n==Education==\nManjunath did his Master of Music at the [[University of Mysore]] securing first Rank with 4 Gold Medals and was awarded Ph.D by the University of Mysore.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Career==\nManjunath started performing at 8 and his initial concerts were with his father and brother.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/raised-to-the-power-of-two/article27546520.ece</ref> He regularly performs along with his elder brother Mysore Nagaraj.<ref>http://mysuru.com/mysoreBros.aspx</ref>  His violin concerts are featured at major international concert stages including [[Royal Albert Hall]] - [[London]], [[Sydney Opera House]] - [[Australia]], International Violin Conference, Common Thread Music festival in [[United States]], [[Federation Square]] in [[Melbourne]], World Music Festival<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MVVSJL7k9ls</ref> in [[Chicago]],<ref>http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/zakir-hussain-niladri-kumar-open-chicago-world-music-festival</ref> [[Oxford University]]<ref>https://www.music.ox.ac.uk/event/the-mysore-brothers-2/</ref>, Tansen Sangith Samaroh-Gwalior,Esplanade Theatre in Singapore, World Music Series by [[BBC]], [[Santa-Fe Festival]]<ref>http://www.sfreporter.com/santafe/article-1735-performing-arts-books-june-27-july-3.html</ref> in [[New Mexico]],Persian Academy of Culture in [[Iran]] Doverlane Music Festival in Kolkata, [[India International Centre]]<ref>http://www.iicdelhi.in/webcasts/view_webcast/carnatic-violin-duet-by-the-mysore-brothers-/</ref>.  He has collaborated with musicians and orchestras including [[Ned McGowan]], [[Fabrizio Cassol]], Jai Uttal,  Joe Craven, Fred Hamilton, Todd Haaby, Pandith [[Vishwa Mohan Bhatt]], [[Ronu Majumdar]], [[N. Rajam]], Tejendra Majumdar such as [[Aka Moon]],<ref>http://www.akamoon.com/index.php?id=159{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Spenifex,<ref>http://www.womex.com/virtual/spinifex</ref> [[Ictus Ensemble|Ictus]].\n\nHe was nominated as cultural ambassador of University of Mysore.<ref>http://www.bangalorefirst.in/?p=13376</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nHe is one of the youngest recipients of the [[Sangeet Natak Akademi]]<ref>https://starofmysore.com/selected-sangith-natak-academy-award/</ref> award by the [[Government of India]] and the [[Rajyotsava Award]] by the Government of [[Karnataka]].<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/2003/10/31/stories/2003103101770600.htm</ref> He has received the Excellence award from [[American Institute of World Culture]], honours from the [[American Arts Council]], Best Violinist awards from The [[Music Academy]], Best Violinist award from the Indian fine arts society, Aryabhata Award, Meritorious Award from [[University of Oklahoma]]-USA,  Samskruthi Sinchana Award, Y.T.Tatachari National Award, Sangeeth Samrat, Sangeeth Rathna, Sangitha Vidwanmani, Gana varidhi, Tantri Vadya Shiromani - Asthana Vidwan from [[Sri Kanchi Kamakoti Peetham]], [[Chowdiah National Award]] by Academy of Music,<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/honour-for-musicians/article4132242.ece</ref> Rotary Excellence Award & Rama Ganakalacharya<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/mysore-brothers-to-receive-rama-gana-kalacharya-award/article23531128.ece</ref>, Sangeetha Vedanta Dhurina<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/honour-for-mysores-violin-maestros/article5665242.ece</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.mysoremanjunath.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Manjunath, Mysore}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Carnatic violinists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Mysore]]\n[[Category:University of Mysore alumni]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Indian male classical musicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Rajyotsava Award 2003]]\n[[Category:21st-century violinists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Manirang1975", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysore_Manjunath"}
{"title_page": "Mickey Mouse Clubhouse", "text_new": "{{distinguish|The Mickey Mouse Club}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=June 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2018}}\n{{Primary sources|date=June 2018}}\n{{Tone|date=June 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Mickey Mouse Clubhouse\n| image                    = Mickey Mouse Clubhouse logo.svg\n| genre                    = [[Children's television series]]<br/>[[Adventure]]<br/>[[Comedy]]<br/>[[Fantasy]]\n| creator                  = Bobs Gannaway\n| based_on                 = {{based on|''[[Mickey Mouse]]''|[[Walt Disney]] and [[Ub Iwerks]]}}\n| developer                = Bobs Gannaway\n| director                 = Rob LaDuca<br />Sherie Pollack<br />Howy Parkins<br />Victor Cook<br />Donovan Cook<br />Broni Likomanov<br />Phil Weinstein\n| voices                   = [[Wayne Allwine]] (2006\u20132009)<br />[[Bret Iwan]] (2009\u20132016)<br />[[Tony Anselmo]]<br />[[Russi Taylor]]<br />[[Tress MacNeille]]<br />[[Bill Farmer]]<br />[[Will Ryan]]<br />[[April Winchell]]<br />[[Jim Cummings]]<br />[[Dee Bradley Baker]]<br />[[Frank Welker]]<br />[[Rob Paulsen]]<br />[[Corey Burton]]\n| composer                 = Mike Himelstein<br />Michael Turner\n| country                  = [[United States]]\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 4\n| num_episodes             = 125\n| list_episodes            = List of Mickey Mouse Clubhouse episodes\n| executive_producer       = Bobs Gannaway (seasons 1-4)<br/>Rob LaDuca (seasons 2-4)\n| opentheme                = \"Mickey Mouse Clubhouse Theme Song\" sung by [[They Might Be Giants]]\n| endtheme                 = \"Hot Dog!\" sung by They Might Be Giants\n| runtime                  = 30 minutes\n| company                  = [[Disney Television Animation]]{{efn|Known as Walt Disney Television Animation from 2006-2012. Animation outsourced to DQ Entertainment and [[Toon City]].}}\n| distributor              = [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]{{efn|Known as Buena Vista Television for the first season.}}\n| network                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Playhouse Disney]] (2006\u20132011)\n* [[Disney Junior]] (2011\u20132016)\n}}\n| picture_format           = [[HDTV]] [[1080p]]/[[720p]]<br />[[SDTV|SD]]: [[480p]]<br /><small>Produced in HD [[16:9]], cropped to [[4:3]] in most countries.</small>\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]] 5.1\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2006|5|5}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2016|11|6}}\n| related                  = [[The Mickey Mouse Club]]<br />[[Mickey Mouse Mixed-Up Adventures]]\n| website                  = https://disneynow.go.com/shows/mickey-mouse-clubhouse\n| website_title            = Official website\n}}\n\n'''''Mickey Mouse Clubhouse''''' is an American interactive computer-animated [[children's television series]] which aired from May 5, 2006 to November 6, 2016.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |pages=387-389}}</ref> The series is [[Disney Television Animation]]'s first [[computer-animated]] series aimed at [[preschool]]ers. The series was created by [[Disney]] veteran {{not a typo|Bobs}} Gannaway, who is also responsible for other preschool shows, such as ''[[Jake and the Never Land Pirates]]'' and for [[Disneytoon Studios]] films including ''[[Secret of the Wings]]'', ''[[The Pirate Fairy]]'' and ''[[Planes: Fire & Rescue]]''. The final episode aired on November 6, 2016.\n\nAfter the series ended, reruns continue to air on Disney Junior.\n\n==Premise==\n[[Mickey Mouse|Mickey]], [[Minnie Mouse|Minnie]], [[Pluto (Disney)|Pluto]], [[Goofy]], [[Daisy Duck|Daisy]], and [[Donald Duck|Donald]] interact with the viewer to stimulate [[problem solving]] during each episode's story. Disney says that each episode has the characters help children \"solve a specific age-appropriate problem utilizing basic math skills, such as identifying [[shapes]] and counting through ten\". The series uses \"[[Disney Junior]]'s 'whole child' [[curriculum]] of [[cognition|cognitive]], [[social]] and [[creativity|creative]] learning opportunities\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disneystore.com/movies-music-books-mickey-mouse-clubhouse-cd/p/1198254/14312/|title=\"Disney Mickey Mouse Clubhouse CD \u2013 Product Description\". Disney Store.|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520181735/http://www.disneystore.com/movies-music-books-mickey-mouse-clubhouse-cd/p/1198254/14312/|archivedate=May 20, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOnce the problem of the episode has been explained, Mickey invites viewers to join him at the Mousekedoer, a giant Mickey-head-shaped computer whose main function is to distribute the day's Mouseketools, a collection of objects needed to solve the day's problem, to Mickey. \nOne of them is a \"Mystery Mouseketool\" represented by a question mark, in which, when the words \"Mystery Mouseketool\" are said, the question mark changes into the Mouseketool you get to use. Another one is a \"Mouseke-Think-About-It Tool\" represented by a silhouette of Mickey's head with rotating gears, in which characters must think of what to use before telling the Tool \"Mouseke-Think-About-It-Tool, we pick the (object)\". Once the tools have been shown to Mickey on the Mousekedoer screen, they are quickly downloaded to Toodles, a small, Mickey-head-shaped flying extension of the Mousekedoer. By calling \"Oh, Toodles!\" Mickey summons him to pop up from where he is hiding and fly up to the screen so the viewer can pick which tool Mickey needs for the current situation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atv.disney.go.com/playhouse/mickeymouseclubhouse/stories/ohtoodles/index.html|title=Oh Toodles! Clubhouse Stories \u2013 Mickey Mouse Clubhouse \u2013 Playhouse Disney|accessdate=June 7, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607163910/http://atv.disney.go.com/playhouse/mickeymouseclubhouse/stories/ohtoodles/index.html|archivedate=June 7, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://atv.disney.go.com/playhouse/mmch/mouskatoolmorning/|title=Playhouse Disney's Mouskatool and Handy Manny Morning|accessdate=June 7, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725050944/http://atv.disney.go.com/playhouse/mmch/mouskatoolmorning/|archivedate=July 25, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe show features two original songs performed by American alternative rock band [[They Might Be Giants]], including the opening theme song, in which a variant of a ''[[Mickey Mouse Club]]'' chant (\"Meeska Mooska Mickey Mouse!\") is used to summon the Clubhouse. They Might Be Giants also perform the song used at the end of every episode, \"Hot Dog!\", which echoes Mickey's first spoken words in the 1929 short ''[[The Karnival Kid]]''.\n\nThis is the first time the major Disney characters have regularly appeared on television in [[computer animation|computer-animated]] form. The characters debuted in [[computer animation|CG]] form in 2003 at the [[Magic Kingdom]] [[theme park]] attraction [[Mickey's PhilharMagic]], then in the 2004 [[home video]] ''[[Mickey's Twice Upon a Christmas]].''\n\n==Characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Mickey Mouse]] (voiced by [[Wayne Allwine]] in 2006\u20132009, and [[Bret Iwan]] in 2009\u20132016)\n* [[Minnie Mouse]] (voiced by [[Russi Taylor]]) \n* [[Goofy]] (voiced by [[Bill Farmer]])\n* [[Daisy Duck]] (voiced by [[Tress MacNeille]])\n* [[Donald Duck]] (voiced by [[Tony Anselmo]])\n* [[Pluto (Disney)|Pluto]] (vocals effects provided by Bill Farmer)\n* Toodles (voiced by [[Rob Paulsen]])\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Pete (Disney)|Pete]] (voiced by [[Jim Cummings]]) \n* [[Chip 'n' Dale|Chip and Dale]] (voiced by Tress MacNeille and [[Corey Burton]] respectively) \n* [[Ludwig Von Drake]] (voiced by Corey Burton) \n* [[Clarabelle Cow]] (voiced by [[April Winchell]]) \n* [[Willie the Giant]] (voiced by [[Will Ryan]]) \n* Martian Mickey (voiced by Wayne Allwine in 2006\u20132009 and Bret Iwan in 2009\u20132016)\n* Martian Minnie (voiced by Russi Taylor) \n* Count Mickula (voiced by Bret Iwan) \n*Quoodles (voiced by Russi Taylor)\n* Goofbot and Goofles (both voiced by Bill Farmer) \n* [[Santa Claus]] \n* Baby Red Bird and Mommy Red Bird (both voiced by Tress MacNeille)\n* Boo Boo Chicken and Coco the Monkey (vocal effects both provided by [[Dee Bradley Baker]])\n* [[Figaro (Disney)|Figaro]], [[Butch the Bulldog]] and Mr. Pettibone (vocal effects all provided by [[Frank Welker]])\n* Bella - Clarabelle's puppy.\n\n===Guest appearances===\n* [[Mortimer Mouse]] (voiced by [[Maurice LaMarche]]) \n* Captain Goof-Beard (voiced by [[Dick van Dyke]]) \n* [[Millie Mouse|Millie]] and [[Melody Mouse]] (voiced by [[Avalon Robbins]] and [[Grace Kaufman]] respectively) \n* The Singing Lock (voiced by [[Nika Futterman]]) \n* Boodles (voiced by [[Chlo\u00eb Grace Moretz]]) \n* Igor the Door (voiced by [[David Tennant]])\n* Cuckoo The Cuckoo Bird\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Mickey Mouse Clubhouse episodes}}\n{{:List of Mickey Mouse Clubhouse episodes}}\n\n==Home media==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2|Title\n! Season(s)\n! Episode count\n! Release date\n! Episodes\n|-\n| style=\"background:#394192|\n| ''Mickey Saves Santa''\n| 1\n| 3\n| November 14, 2006\n|Episode  03 (\"Goofy's Bird\"), 10 (\"Mickey-Go-Seek\") and 20 (\"Mickey Saves Santa\")\n|-\n| style=\"background:#5da9dd|\n| ''Mickey's Great Clubhouse Hunt''\n| 1\n| 2\n| March 20, 2007\n| 24 (\"Mickey's Great Clubhouse Hunt\") and 27 (\"Donald's Hiccups\")\n|-\n| style=\"background:#1f2b75|\n| ''Mickey's Treat''\n| 1\n| 4\n| August 28, 2007\n| 18 (\"Mickey's Treat\"), 21 (\"Goofy the Great\"), 25 (\"Doctor Daisy, M.D.\") and A Little Einsteins Halloween\n|-\n| style=\"background:#403696|\n| ''Mickey's Storybook Surprises''\n| 1, 2\n| 4\n| February 24, 2009\n| Episode 07 (\"Donald the Frog Prince\"), 18 (\"Minnie Red Riding Hood\"), 19 (\"Sleeping Minnie\") and 50 (\"Minnie's Mystery\")\n|-\n| style=\"background:#39c4ef|\n| ''Mickey's Big Splash''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/disney-mickey-mouse-clubhouse-mickeys-big-splash.html |title=Disney Mickey Mouse Clubhouse: Mickey's Big Splash {{!}} Now On DVD {{!}} Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment |accessdate=2012-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505151506/http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/disney-mickey-mouse-clubhouse-mickeys-big-splash.html |archivedate=May 5, 2012 }}</ref>\n| 1, 2\n| 4\n| October 5, 2009\n| Episode 06 (\"Mickey Goes Fishing\"), 43 (\"Pluto's Bubble Bath\"), 57 (\"Pete's Beach Blanket Luau\") and 58 (\"Donald's Ducks\")\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ac3593|\n| ''Mickey's Adventures in Wonderland''\n| 1, 2, 3, 4\n| 5\n| December 1, 2009\n| Epsiode 14 (\"Daisy in the Sky\"), 04 (\"Donald's Big Balloon Race\"), 15 (\"Pluto's Puppy-Sitting Adventure\") 13, (\"Mickey's Treasure Hunt\") and (  65 (\"Mickey's Adventures In Wonderland\")\n|\n| style=\"background:#006fb7|\n| ''Choo-Choo Express''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/disney-mickey-mouse-clubhouse-mickeys-choo-choo-express.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426082503/http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/disney-mickey-mouse-clubhouse-mickeys-choo-choo-express.html |archivedate=April 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n| 2\n| 2\n| December 9, 2009\n| 41 (\"Mickey's Big Job\") and 60 (\"Choo-Choo Express\")\n|-\n| style=\"background:#f0669a|\n| ''Minnie's Bow-Tique''\n| 2, 3\n| 4\n| February 9, 2010\n| 32 (\"Minnie's Picnic\"), 61 (\"Minnie's Bee Story\"), 75 (\"Minnie's Pajama Party\") and 83 (\"Minnie's Bow-Tique\")\n|-\n| style=\"background:#40b4e7|\n| ''Road Rally''\n| 1-3\n| 5\n| September 7, 2010\n| 76 (\"Road Rally\"), 5 