{"title_page": "Indigenous land claims in Canada", "text_new": "{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}\n\n'''Indigenous land claims in Canada''' are demands from [[indigenous peoples in Canada|indigenous peoples]] to have their [[Indigenous land rights|land rights]] and their [[Aboriginal title]]s be respected by the authorities. They are one of the main issues facing indigenous peoples in [[Canada]] today.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/land-claims|title=Indigenous Land Claims|author=Gretchen Albers|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|date=April 20, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/12/world/canada/canada-first-nations-algonquin-land-claims.html|title=Vast Indigenous Land Claims in Canada Encompass Parliament Hill|last=Austen|first=Ian|date=2017-11-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Canada]] started recognizing indigenous land claims in 1973. Federal policy divided the claims in two categories: comprehensive claims and [[Indigenous specific land claims in Canada|specific claims]]. Comprehensive claims deal with indigenous rights of [[M\u00e9tis in Canada|M\u00e9tis]], [[First Nations]] and [[Inuit]] communities that did not sign treaties with the Government of Canada. Specific claims, on the other hand, are filed by First Nations communities over Canada's breach of the [[Numbered Treaties]], the [[Indian Act]] or any other agreement between [[the Crown]] and First Nations.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/specific-claims|title=Indigenous People: Specific Land Claims|author=Gretchen Albers|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica Canada]]|date=June 29, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Comprehensive claims ==\n{{See also|British Columbia Treaty Process|Yukon Land Claims}}\nComprehensive claims are assertions of [[aboriginal title]] by Indigenous groups over their ancestral lands. Comprehensive Land Claim Agreements, also called modern treaties, first started being negotiated by the federal government in 1973 to gain the consent from Indigenous peoples for Canada to assert sovereignty over their unceded land.<ref name=\":3\" /> Example of modern treaties include the [[Nunavut Land Claims Agreement]] and the [[James Bay and Northern Quebec Agreement]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/comprehensive-land-claims-modern-treaties|title=Comprehensive Land Claims: Modern Treaties|author=Keith Crowe|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica Canada]]|date=July 11, 2019|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Nunavut-Land-Claims-Agreement-Act|title=Nunavut Land Claims Agreement Act {{!}} Canada [1993]|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> As of 2017, a total of 25 modern treaties have been signed,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/aboriginal-title-rights-elsipogtog-first-nation-mou-1.5132320|title=Aboriginal title: What it means for Elsipogtog First Nation|date=May 11, 2019|website=CBC News}}</ref> and 140 Indigenous groups are in the process of negotiating a modern treaty with the federal government.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Specific claims ==\n{{Main|Indigenous specific land claims in Canada}}\nSpecific claims are claims made by [[First Nations]] communities related to the administration of land and other First Nations assets by the [[Government of Canada]], or breaches of treaty obligations or of any other agreements between First Nations and [[the Crown]] by the government of Canada. They can also involve mismanagement of Indigenous land or assets by the Crown under the [[Indian Act]].<ref name=\":0\" /> They are based on lawful obligations of the Crown toward the First Nations. First Nations cannot use [[aboriginal title]]s or [[punitive damages]] as the basis of their claims.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rcaanc-cirnac.gc.ca/eng/1100100030291/1539617582343|title=Specific claims|date=2015-01-12|publisher=Crown-Indigenous Relations and Northern Affairs Canada|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe government of Canada typically resolves specific claims by negotiating a monetary compensation for the breach with the [[band government]], and in exchange, they require the extinguishment of the First Nation's rights to the land in question.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afn.ca/uploads/files/specific_claims/expert_panel_report.pdf|title=SPECIFIC CLAIMS REVIEW: EXPERT BASED \u2010 PEOPLES DRIVEN|date=May 15, 2015|website=www.afn.ca|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Land claim]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/eng/1100100030501/1100100030506 Specific Claims - CIRNAC]\n* [https://www.aadnc-aandc.gc.ca/eng/1100100030577/1100100030578 Comprehensive Claims - CIRNAC]\n\n[[Category:First Nations history]]\n[[Category:Indigenous rights in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Indigenous Peoples of Canada}}\n\n'''Indigenous land claims in Canada''' are demands from [[indigenous peoples in Canada|indigenous peoples]] to have their [[Indigenous land rights|land rights]] and their [[Aboriginal title]]s be respected by the authorities. They are one of the main issues facing indigenous peoples in [[Canada]] today.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/land-claims|title=Indigenous Land Claims|author=Gretchen Albers|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|publisher=Historica Canada|date=April 20, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/12/world/canada/canada-first-nations-algonquin-land-claims.html|title=Vast Indigenous Land Claims in Canada Encompass Parliament Hill|last=Austen|first=Ian|date=2017-11-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-01-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Government of Canada]] started recognizing indigenous land claims in 1973. Federal policy divided the claims in two categories: comprehensive claims and [[Indigenous specific land claims in Canada|specific claims]]. Comprehensive claims deal with indigenous rights of [[M\u00e9tis in Canada|M\u00e9tis]], [[First Nations]] and [[Inuit]] communities that did not sign treaties with the Government of Canada. Specific claims, on the other hand, are filed by First Nations communities over Canada's breach of the [[Numbered Treaties]], the [[Indian Act]] or any other agreement between [[the Crown]] and First Nations.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/specific-claims|title=Indigenous People: Specific Land Claims|author=Gretchen Albers|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica Canada]]|date=June 29, 2015|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Comprehensive claims ==\n{{See also|British Columbia Treaty Process|Yukon Land Claims}}\nComprehensive claims are assertions of [[aboriginal title]] by Indigenous groups over their ancestral lands. Comprehesive Land Claim Agreements, also called modern treaties, first started being negotiated by the federal government in 1973 to gain the consent from Indigenous peoples for Canada to assert sovereignty over their unceded land.<ref name=\":3\" /> Example of modern treaties include the [[Nunavut Land Claims Agreement]] and the [[James Bay and Northern Quebec Agreement]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/comprehensive-land-claims-modern-treaties|title=Comprehensive Land Claims: Modern Treaties|author=Keith Crowe|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|publisher=[[Historica Canada]]|date=July 11, 2019|accessdate=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Nunavut-Land-Claims-Agreement-Act|title=Nunavut Land Claims Agreement Act {{!}} Canada [1993]|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> As of 2017, a total of 25 modern treaties have been signed,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/aboriginal-title-rights-elsipogtog-first-nation-mou-1.5132320|title=Aboriginal title: What it means for Elsipogtog First Nation|date=May 11, 2019|website=CBC News}}</ref> and 140 Indigenous groups are in the process of negotiating a modern treaty with the federal government.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Specific claims ==\n{{Main|Indigenous specific land claims in Canada}}\nSpecific claims are claims made by [[First Nations]] communities related to the administration of land and other First Nations assets by the [[Government of Canada]], or breaches of treaty obligations or of any other agreements between First Nations and [[the Crown]] by the government of Canada. They can also involve mismanagement of Indigenous land or assets by the Crown under the [[Indian Act]].<ref name=\":0\" /> They are based on lawful obligations of the Crown toward the First Nations. First Nations cannot use [[aboriginal title]]s or [[punitive damages]] as the basis of their claims.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rcaanc-cirnac.gc.ca/eng/1100100030291/1539617582343|title=Specific claims|date=2015-01-12|publisher=Crown-Indigenous Relations and Northern Affairs Canada|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe government of Canada typically resolves specific claims by negotiating a monetary compensation for the breach with the [[band government]], and in exchange, they require the extinguishment of the First Nation's rights to the land in question.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afn.ca/uploads/files/specific_claims/expert_panel_report.pdf|title=SPECIFIC CLAIMS REVIEW: EXPERT BASED \u2010 PEOPLES DRIVEN|date=May 15, 2015|website=www.afn.ca|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Land claim]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n