{"title_page": "Rusalka (novel)", "text_new": "{{Short description|1989 novel by C. J. Cherryh}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = Rusalka\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = CherryhRusalkalHCover.jpg\n| image_size    = 200\n| caption       = [[Del Rey Books|Del Rey]] hardcover first edition, 1989\n| author        = [[C. J. Cherryh]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = [[Keith Parkinson]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Fantasy literature|Fantasy novel]]\n| publisher     = [[Del Rey Books]]\n| pub_date      = October 1989\n| media_type    = Print (hardback, paperback, [[e-book]])\n| pages         = 374 (hardcover edition)\n| isbn          = 978-0-3453-5953-7\n| dewey= \n| congress= \n| oclc= \n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   = [[Chernevog]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rusalka''''' is a [[Fantasy literature|fantasy novel]] by American [[science fiction]] and fantasy author [[C. J. Cherryh]]. It was first published in October 1989 in the United States in a hardcover edition by [[Ballantine Books]] under its [[Del Rey Books]] imprint. ''Rusalka'' is book one of Cherryh's three-book ''[[The Russian Stories (C. J. Cherryh)|Russian Stories]]'' trilogy set in medieval Russia in forests along the [[Dnieper]] river near [[Kiev]] in modern-day [[Ukraine]].<ref name=Day/>{{sfn|Bogstad|2004|p=114}} The novel draws on [[Slavic mythology|Slavic folklore]] and concerns the fate of a girl who has drowned and become a [[rusalka]]. It is also an exploration of magic and the development of a young wizard.{{sfn|Bogstad|2004|p=118}}\n\n''Rusalka'' was nominated for the [[Locus Award for Best Fantasy Novel]] in 1990 and was a third-place runner-up.<ref name=WWE-1990/>\n\nCherryh [[self-publishing|self-published]] a revised edition of ''Rusalka'' in e-book format in October 2010 at Closed Circle Publications.<ref name=Wave1/><ref name=Wave4/><ref name=Wave2/><ref name=Closed-Circle/>\n\n==Plot summary==\n:\"A rusalka is a wish. A wish not to die. A wish for revenge.\" <small>\u2014 ''Rusalka'', page 226{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=226}}</small>\nSasha is a 15-year-old downtrodden stable boy living with his aunt and uncle at an inn they run in the town of Vojvoda. Sasha's parents had been killed in a house fire that he was accused of starting through [[Magician (paranormal)|wizardry]]. Pyetr is one of the town's audacious young men, and one day he is attacked and wounded by old Yurishev for having a liaison with his young wife. Pyetr escapes, but later learns that Yurishev is dead, and that he has been accused of murdering him by [[Maleficium (sorcery)|sorcery]]. Pyetr hides in the stables at the inn, and Sasha helps him leave the town. With no future for himself in Vojvoda, Sasha accompanies the wounded Pyetr.\n\nPyetr and Sasha walk for days through fields and into a dead forest. Sasha does not believe he is a wizard, but finds he sometimes has the ability to successfully wish for things. Pyetr does not believe in wizards at all, and laughs at Sasha's wishing. Exhausted and without food, the pair find a cottage by a river. Its occupant, a wizard named Uulamets, heals Pyetr and agrees to let them stay on condition that they help him find his daughter, Eveshka, who had drowned when she was 16 and is now a [[rusalka]]. Pyetr is suspicious of Uulamets and does not believe in rusalkas.{{refn|In her book, Cherryh uses the pural \"rusalkas\", not \"rusalki\".{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=86}}|group=\"nb\"}} Later, while the three of them are searching for Eveshka, she makes herself visible to Pyetr, overpowers him, and leads him into the forest. Rusalkas are renowned for drowning men they have chosen, but Eveshka abandons Pyetr and disappears again. Uulamets and Sasha find Pyetr unharmed, but are attacked by Hwiuur, a [[shapeshifting]] [[Vodyanoy|vodyanoi]], known to drown people who go too close to the water.\n\nUulamets traps Hwiuur and threatens to kill it. The creature pleads for its life and admits to drowning Eveshka, but blames Chernevog, a former student of Uulamets. Eveshka had fallen in love with Chernevog and run off with him, but Chernevog had used his newly acquired wizardry to control her, and then handed her over to Hwiuur. Even as a rusalka Chernevog still controls Eveshka and will not let her return to her father. Uulamets agrees to let Hwiuur go on condition that he helps them find Chernevog.\n\nWhile searching for Chernevog, Pyetr spots Eveshka and chases after her. Sasha wants to follow Pyetr to protect him, but Uulamets wills Sasha to stay. Uulamets had recognised Sasha's potential for wizardry and taught him how to use his talents, but stressed the dangers of unchecked wishing and the importance of considering their consequences first. Pyetr, who now has feelings for Eveshka, and is slowly accepting this new world of wizards, rusalkas and river creatures, finds her and together they locate Chernevog's house in the forest. Chernevog immediately takes control of Pyetr and instructs Hwiuur to guard him. As Uulamets and Sasha approach the house Chernevog starts sending lightning bolts at them, but Uulamets is able to redirect them back at the house, setting it ablaze. In the chaos, Pyetr breaks free of Hwiuur and overpowers a weakened Chernevog. Uulamets then casts a wizard's once-in-a-lifetime spell and commands Eveshka to \"live!\".{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=295}} This final wish kills the wizard but resurrects Eveshka. Sasha discovers that that spell also bestowed on him all of the wizard's knowledge and abilities.\n\nChernevog is unconscious, but Sasha cannot kill him and instead puts him into a long, deep sleep. Hwiuur has disappeared, and [[leshy]]s{{refn|In her book, Cherryh uses the pural \"leshys\", not \"leshies\".{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=36}}|group=\"nb\"}}, woodland spirits, appear and celebrate the downfall of Chernevog. They put him on a stone in a circle of trees and agree to guard him. With Eveshka flesh and bone again, she and Pyetr finally unite, and Sasha, now a wizard, has new responsibilities to attend to.\n\n==Reception==\nIn a review in the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', science fiction and fantasy writer [[Roland J. Green]] called ''Rusalka'' \"one of 1989's better fantasies\".<ref name=Green/> While he was critical of Cherryh's \"occasional lapses of narrative technique\", he said that she excelled in her \"characterization, command of the language, world-building, and background in anthropology, linguistics and folklore\".<ref name=Green/> A reviewer in [[Kirkus Reviews]] said that ''Rusalka'''s plot was \"pretty good\", but complained about it being \"plodding, uncompelling, and ... overlong\", and that it lacked \"atmosphere, tension, chills and thrills\".<ref name=Kirkus/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=WWE-1990>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1990 |title=1990 Award Winners & Nominees |website=Worlds Without End |accessdate=August 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kirkus>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/cj-cherryh/rusalka/ |title=Rusalka |magazine=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |date=September 15, 1989 |accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Closed-Circle>{{cite web |url=http://www.closed-circle.net/c-j-cherryhs-rusalka-books/ |title=Rusalka |website=Closed Circle Publications |accessdate=August 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wave1>{{cite web |last=Cherryh |first=C. J. |authorlink=C. J. Cherryh |url=http://www.cherryh.com/WaveWithoutAShore/?p=551 |title=Patching up old mistakes |website=Wave Without a Shore |date=July 12, 2009 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wave2>{{cite web |last=Cherryh |first=C. J. |authorlink=C. J. Cherryh |url=http://www.cherryh.com/WaveWithoutAShore/?p=2331 |title=Blood Red Moon and Rusalka |website=Wave Without a Shore |date=October 30, 2010 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wave4>{{cite web |last=Cherryh |first=C. J. |authorlink=C. J. Cherryh |url=http://www.cherryh.com/WaveWithoutAShore/?p=3584 |title=Getting very close to adding Chernevog and Yvgenie |website=Wave Without a Shore |date=March 31, 2012 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Green>{{cite news |title=Their strengths are mightier than their flaws |author=Green, Roland J. |authorlink=Roland J. Green |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3978689.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018224057/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3978689.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 18, 2016 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=January 7, 1990 |accessdate=March 1, 2013 |url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research|HighBeam]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Day>{{cite journal | last1 = Day | first1 = Mildred Leake | last2 = | first2 =  | year = 1991 | title = Arthurian News and Events | journal = Quondam et Futurus | volume = 1 | issue = 3 | pages = 106\u2013107 | publisher = Scriptorium Press | jstor = 27870146}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Works cited==\n*{{cite book |last=Bogstad |first=Janice M. |editor-last=Carmien |editor-first=Edward |title=The Cherryh Odyssey |title-link=The Cherryh Odyssey |chapter=Shifting Ground: Subjectivities in Cherryh's Slavic Fantasy Trilogy |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bj9Jbnak3S0C&pg=PA113 |year=2004 |publisher=Wildside Press LLC |isbn=978-0-8095-1071-9 |pages=113\u2013131|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Cherryh |first=C. J. |authorlink=C. J. Cherryh |title=Rusalka |year=2010 |origyear=1989 |edition=e-book |publisher=Closed Circle Publications |location=[[Spokane, Washington]] |ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite magazine |first=Neil |last=Jones |title=Review of ''Rusalka'' |magazine=[[Interzone (magazine)|Interzone]] |volume=40 |date=October 1990 |page=68}}\n*{{cite magazine |first=Faren |last=Miller |title=Review of ''Rusalka'' |magazine=[[Locus (magazine)|Locus]] |volume=23 |issue=3 |date=September 1989}}\n*{{cite magazine |first=Nik |last=Morton |title=Review of ''Rusalka'' |magazine=[[Vector (magazine)|Vector]] |date=December 1990 |page=15}}\n*{{cite book |first=Lynn F. |last=Williams |editor1-first=Robert A. |editor1-last=Collins |editor2-first=Robert A. |editor2-last=Latham |chapter=Review of ''Rusalka'' |title=Science Fiction & Fantasy Book Review Annual |publisher=Meckler |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-313-28150-1 |pages=231\u2013232}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{isfdb title|id=1280|title=Rusalka}}.\n*[https://www.worldswithoutend.com/novel.asp?ID=752 Rusalka] at Worlds Without End\n\n{{C. J. Cherryh}}\n\n[[Category:1989 American novels]]\n[[Category:1989 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Fiction about magic]]\n[[Category:Fantasy novels by C. J. Cherryh]]\n[[Category:Slavic mythology in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Fictional Slavic people]]\n[[Category:Del Rey books]]\n[[Category:Slavic folklore characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|1989 novel by C. J. Cherryh}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = Rusalka\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| image         = CherryhRusalkalHCover.jpg\n| image_size    = 200\n| caption       = [[Del Rey Books|Del Rey]] hardcover first edition, 1989\n| author        = [[C. J. Cherryh]]\n| illustrator   = \n| cover_artist  = [[Keith Parkinson]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Fantasy literature|Fantasy novel]]\n| publisher     = [[Del Rey Books]]\n| pub_date      = October 1989\n| media_type    = Print (hardback, paperback, [[e-book]])\n| pages         = 374 (hardcover edition)\n| isbn          = 978-0-3453-5953-7\n| dewey= \n| congress= \n| oclc= \n| preceded_by   =\n| followed_by   = [[Chernevog]]\n}}\n\n'''''Rusalka''''' is a [[Fantasy literature|fantasy novel]] by American [[science fiction]] and fantasy author [[C. J. Cherryh]]. It was first published in October 1989 in the United States in a hardcover edition by [[Ballantine Books]] under its [[Del Rey Books]] imprint. ''Rusalka'' is book one of Cherryh's three-book ''[[The Russian Stories (C. J. Cherryh)|Russian Stories]]'' trilogy set in medieval Russia in forests along the [[Dnieper]] river near [[Kiev]] in modern-day [[Ukraine]].<ref name=Day/>{{sfn|Bogstad|2004|p=114}} The novel draws on [[Slavic mythology|Slavic folklore]] and concerns the fate of a girl who has drowned and become a [[rusalka]]. It is also an exploration of magic and the development of a young wizard.{{sfn|Bogstad|2004|p=118}}\n\n''Rusalka'' was nominated for the [[Locus Award for Best Fantasy Novel]] in 1990 and was a third-place runner-up.<ref name=WWE-1990/>\n\nCherryh [[self-publishing|self-published]] a revised edition of ''Rusalka'' in e-book format in October 2010 at Closed Circle Publications.<ref name=Wave1/><ref name=Wave4/><ref name=Wave2/><ref name=Closed-Circle/>\n\n==Plot summary==\n:\"A rusalka is a wish. A wish not to die. A wish for revenge.\" <small>\u2014 ''Rusalka'', page 226{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=226}}</small>\nSasha is a 15-year-old downtrodden stable boy living with his aunt and uncle at an inn they run in the town of Vojvoda. Sasha's parents had been killed in a house fire that he was accused of starting through [[Magician (paranormal)|wizardry]]. Pyetr is one of the town's audacious young men, and one day he is attacked and wounded by old Yurishev for having a liaison with his young wife. Pyetr escapes, but later learns that Yurishev is dead, and that he has been accused of murdering him by [[Maleficium (sorcery)|sorcery]]. Pyetr hides in the stables at the inn, and Sasha helps him leave the town. With no future for himself in Vojvoda, Sasha accompanies the wounded Pyetr.\n\nPyetr and Sasha walk for days through fields and into a dead forest. Sasha does not believe he is a wizard, but finds he sometimes has the ability to successfully wish for things. Pyetr does not believe in wizards at all, and laughs at Sasha's wishing. Exhausted and without food, the pair find a cottage by a river. Its occupant, a wizard named Uulamets, heals Pyetr and agrees to let them stay on condition that they help him find his daughter, Eveshka, who had drowned when she was 16 and is now a [[rusalka]]. Pyetr is suspicious of Uulamets and does not believe in rusalkas.{{refn|In her book, Cherryh uses the pural \"rusalkas\", not \"rusalki\".{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=86}}|group=\"nb\"}} Later, while the three of them are searching for Eveshka, she makes herself visible to Pyetr, overpowers him, and leads him into the forest. Rusalkas are renowned for drowning men they have chosen, but Eveshka abandons Pyetr and disappears again. Uulamets and Sasha find Pyetr unharmed, but are attacked by Hwiuur, a [[shapeshifting]] [[Vodyanoy|vodyanoi]], known to drown people who go too close to the water.\n\nUulamets traps Hwiuur and threatens to kill it. The creature pleads for its life and admits to drowning Eveshka, but blames Chernevog, a former student of Uulamets. Eveshka had fallen in love with Chernevog and run off with him, but Chernevog had used his newly acquired wizardry to control her, and then handed her over to Hwiuur. Even as a rusalka Chernevog still controls Eveshka and will not let her return to her father. Uulamets agrees to let Hwiuur go on condition that he helps them find Chernevog.\n\nWhile searching for Chernevog, Pyetr spots Eveshka and chases after her. Sasha wants to follow Pyetr to protect him, but Uulamets wills Sasha to stay. Uulamets had recognised Sasha's potential for wizardry and taught him how to use his talents, but stressed the dangers of unchecked wishing and the importance of considering their consequences first. Pyetr, who now has feelings for Eveshka, and is slowly accepting this new world of wizards, rusalkas and river creatures, finds her and together they locate Chernevog's house in the forest. Chernevog immediately takes control of Pyetr and instructs Hwiuur to guard him. As Uulamets and Sasha approach the house Chernevog starts sending lightning bolts at them, but Uulamets is able to redirect them back at the house, setting it ablaze. In the chaos, Pyetr breaks free of Hwiuur and overpowers a weakened Chernevog. Uulamets then casts a wizard's once-in-a-lifetime spell and commands Eveshka to \"live!\".{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=295}} This final wish kills the wizard but resurrects Eveshka. Sasha discovers that that spell also bestowed on him all of the wizard's knowledge and abilities.\n\nChernevog is unconscious, but Sasha cannot kill him and instead puts him into a long, deep sleep. Hwiuur has disappeared, and [[leshy]]s{{refn|In her book, Cherryh uses the pural \"leshys\", not \"leshies\".{{sfn|Cherryh|2010|p=36}}|group=\"nb\"}}, woodland spirits, appear and celebrate the downfall of Chernevog. They put him on a stone in a circle of trees and agree to guard him. With Eveshka flesh and bone again, she and Pyetr finally unite, and Sasha, now a wizard, has new responsibilities to attend to.\n\n==Reception==\nIn a review in the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', science fiction and fantasy writer [[Roland J. Green]] called ''Rusalka'' \"one of 1989's better fantasies\".<ref name=Green/> While he was critical of Cherryh's \"occasional lapses of narrative technique\", he said that she excelled in her \"characterization, command of the language, world-building, and background in anthropology, linguistics and folklore\".<ref name=Green/> A reviewer in [[Kirkus Reviews]] said that ''Rusalka'''s plot was \"pretty good\", but complained about it being \"plodding, uncompelling, and ... overlong\", and that it lacked \"atmosphere, tension, chills and thrills\".<ref name=Kirkus/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=WWE-1990>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldswithoutend.com/books_year_index.asp?year=1990 |title=1990 Award Winners & Nominees |website=Worlds Without End |accessdate=August 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Kirkus>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/cj-cherryh/rusalka/ |title=Rusalka |magazine=[[Kirkus Reviews]] |date=September 15, 1989 |accessdate=August 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Closed-Circle>{{cite web |url=http://www.closed-circle.net/c-j-cherryhs-rusalka-books/ |title=Rusalka |website=Closed Circle Publications |accessdate=August 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wave1>{{cite web |last=Cherryh |first=C. J. |authorlink=C. J. Cherryh |url=http://www.cherryh.com/WaveWithoutAShore/?p=551 |title=Patching up old mistakes |website=Wave Without a Shore |date=July 12, 2009 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wave2>{{cite web |last=Cherryh |first=C. J. |authorlink=C. J. Cherryh |url=http://www.cherryh.com/WaveWithoutAShore/?p=2331 |title=Blood Red Moon and Rusalka |website=Wave Without a Shore |date=October 30, 2010 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Wave4>{{cite web |last=Cherryh |first=C. J. |authorlink=C. J. Cherryh |url=http://www.cherryh.com/WaveWithoutAShore/?p=3584 |title=Getting very close to adding Chernevog and Yvgenie |website=Wave Without a Shore |date=March 31, 2012 |accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Green>{{cite news |title=Their strengths are mightier than their flaws |author=Green, Roland J. |authorlink=Roland J. Green |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3978689.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161018224057/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-3978689.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 18, 2016 |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=January 7, 1990 |accessdate=March 1, 2013 |url-access=subscription |via=[[HighBeam Research|HighBeam]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Day>{{cite journal | last1 = Day | first1 = Mildred Leake | last2 = | first2 =  | year = 1991 | title = Arthurian News and Events | journal = Quondam et Futurus | volume = 1 | i